{"title_page": "SS Virginia Dare", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Lot-3452-11 (26786237301).jpg\n|Ship caption=SS Virginia Dare launched at Wilmington, North Carolina, February 3, 1942\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag= {{USN flag|1941}}\n|Ship name= ''Virginia Dare''\n|Ship namesake=[[Virginia Dare]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[North Carolina Shipbuilding Company]], [[Wilmington, North Carolina]]\n|Ship yard number=3\n|Ship way number=3\n|Ship laid down=28 May 1941\n|Ship launched=3 February 1942\n|Ship delivered=27 March 1942\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=6 March 1944\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honors=[[Image:Bronze-service-star-3d.png|18px]] 1 \u00d7 [[Battle star#Navy warships|battle star]]\n|Ship fate=scrapped 1948\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type= [[Liberty ship]]\n|Ship tonnage={{DWT|7,000|long|disp=long}}\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length= {{convert|441|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam= {{convert|56|ft|11|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft= {{convert|27|ft|9|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship propulsion=*Two oil-fired boilers\n*Triple expansion steam engine\n*Single screw\n*{{convert|2500|hp|0|abbr=on}}\n|Ship speed= {{convert|11|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range= \n|Ship capacity=9,140 tons cargo\n|Ship complement=41\n|Ship armament=*1 \u00d7 Stern-mounted [[4\"/50 caliber gun|{{convert|4|in|mm|abbr=on}}]] [[deck gun]]\n*AA guns\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''SS ''Virginia Dare''''' ([[Maritime Commission|MC]] contract 147) was a [[Liberty ship]] built in the United States during [[World War II]]. She was named after [[Virginia Dare]], the first English child born in America, who disappeared along with the rest of the [[Roanoke Colony]].\n\nThe ship was laid down by [[North Carolina Shipbuilding Company]] in their [[Cape Fear River]] yard on 28 May 1941, then launched on 3 February 1942.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://shipbuildinghistory.com/shipyards/emergencylarge/northcarolina.htm |title=North Carolina Shipbuilding |publisher=shipbuildinghistory.com |accessdate=2018-01-05 }}</ref>  She was operated by the South Atlantic Steamship Line for the [[War Shipping Administration]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vesselhistory.marad.dot.gov/sh/ShipHistory/Detail/6392 |title=Virginia Dare |publisher=MARAD Vessel History Database |accessdate=2019-01-05 }}</ref> In September 1942 ''Greene'' was part of the heavily escorted Arctic [[Convoy PQ 18]] when her crew was credited with shooting down seven German aircraft and received the [[Merchant Marine Gallant Ship Citation|Gallant Ship Citation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130105210528/http://veterans.house.gov/witness-testimony/mr-brian-herbert |title=Hearing on 04/18/2007: H.R. 23, the \"Belated Thank You to the Merchant Mariners of World War II Act of 2007\". |publisher=House Committee on Veterans Affairs |accessdate=2018-01-05 }}</ref>\n\nWhile operating off of [[Bizerte, Tunisia]] she struck a mine and had to be beached.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usmm.org/sunk44.htm |title=Chronological List of U.S. Ships Sunk or Damaged during 1944 |publisher=American Merchant Marine at War |accessdate=2019-01-05 }}</ref> Seven days later she broke in half.  In 1948 she was scrapped by an Italian salvage company.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vesselhistory.marad.dot.gov/sh/ShipHistory/Detail/6392 |title=Virginia Dare |publisher=MARAD Vessel History Database |accessdate=2019-01-05 }}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*''Virginia Dare''{{'}}s [[Naval Armed Guard]] detachment received one [[battle star]] for [[World War II]] service in [[Arctic convoys of World War II|Murmansk convoy]] operations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usmm.org/battle-n-z.html |title=U.S. Merchant Marine Ships whose Naval Armed Guard crews earned \"Battle Stars\" in World War II - Ships with names \"N to Z\" |publisher=American Merchant Marine at War |accessdate=2019-01-09 }}</ref>\n*Captain Arthur L. Johnson, Master of ''Virginia Dare'' was given the [[Merchant Marine Distinguished Service Medal]] by The President of the United States. He was awarded for leadership and high courage in the face of attacking planes. The award was given by Admiral [[Emory S. Land]].<ref>[http://www.usmm.org/heroes.html usmm.org Heroes] </ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Liberty ships V}}\n{{MARCOM ships North Carolina SB Co.}}\n{{Liberty ships }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Virginia Dare}}\n[[Category:Liberty ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Wilmington, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:1942 ships]]\n\n\n{{liberty-ship-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Lot-3452-11 (26786237301).jpg\n|Ship caption=SS Virginia Dare launched at Wilmington, North Carolina, February 3, 1942\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag= {{USN flag|1941}}\n|Ship name= ''Virginia Dare''\n|Ship namesake=[[Virginia Dare]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[North Carolina Shipbuilding Company]], [[Wilmington, North Carolina]]\n|Ship yard number=3\n|Ship way number=3\n|Ship laid down=28 May 1941\n|Ship launched=3 February 1942\n|Ship delivered=27 March 1942\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=6 March 1944\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honors=[[Image:Bronze-service-star-3d.png|18px]] 1 \u00d7 [[Battle star#Navy warships|battle star]]\n|Ship fate=scrapped 1948\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship type= [[Liberty ship]]\n|Ship tonnage={{DWT|7,000|long|disp=long}}\n|Ship displacement=\n|Ship length= {{convert|441|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam= {{convert|56|ft|11|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship draft= {{convert|27|ft|9|in|m|abbr=on}}\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship propulsion=*Two oil-fired boilers\n*Triple expansion steam engine\n*Single screw\n*{{convert|2500|hp|0|abbr=on}}\n|Ship speed= {{convert|11|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range= \n|Ship capacity=9,140 tons cargo\n|Ship complement=41\n|Ship armament=*1 \u00d7 Stern-mounted [[4\"/50 caliber gun|{{convert|4|in|mm|abbr=on}}]] [[deck gun]]\n*AA guns\n|Ship armor=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''SS ''Virginia Dare''''' ([[Maritime Commission|MC]] contract 147) was a [[Liberty ship]] built in the United States during [[World War II]]. She was named after [[Virginia Dare]], the first English child born in America, who disappeared along with the rest of the [[Roanoke Colony]].\n\nThe ship was laid down by [[North Carolina Shipbuilding Company]] in their [[Cape Fear River]] yard on 28 May 1941, then launched on 3 February 1942.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://shipbuildinghistory.com/shipyards/emergencylarge/northcarolina.htm |title=North Carolina Shipbuilding |publisher=shipbuildinghistory.com |accessdate=2018-01-05 }}</ref>  She was operated by the South Atlantic Steamship Line for the [[War Shipping Administration]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vesselhistory.marad.dot.gov/sh/ShipHistory/Detail/6392 |title=Virginia Dare |publisher=MARAD Vessel History Database |accessdate=2019-01-05 }}</ref> In September 1942 ''Greene'' was part of the heavily escorted Arctic [[Convoy PQ 18]] when her crew was credited with shooting down seven German aircraft and received the [[Merchant Marine Gallant Ship Citation|Gallant Ship Citation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130105210528/http://veterans.house.gov/witness-testimony/mr-brian-herbert |title=Hearing on 04/18/2007: H.R. 23, the \"Belated Thank You to the Merchant Mariners of World War II Act of 2007\". |publisher=House Committee on Veterans Affairs |accessdate=2018-01-05 }}</ref>\n\nWhile operating off of [[Bizerte, Tunisia]] she struck a mine and had to be beached.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usmm.org/sunk44.htm |title=Chronological List of U.S. Ships Sunk or Damaged during 1944 |publisher=American Merchant Marine at War |accessdate=2019-01-05 }}</ref> Seven days later she broke in half.  In 1948 she was scrapped by an Italian salvage company.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://vesselhistory.marad.dot.gov/sh/ShipHistory/Detail/6392 |title=Virginia Dare |publisher=MARAD Vessel History Database |accessdate=2019-01-05 }}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n*''Virginia Dare'''s [[Naval Armed Guard]] detachment received one [[battle star]] for [[World War II]] service in [[Arctic convoys of World War II|Murmansk convoy]] operations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.usmm.org/battle-n-z.html |title=U.S. Merchant Marine Ships whose Naval Armed Guard crews earned \"Battle Stars\" in World War II - Ships with names \"N to Z\" |publisher=American Merchant Marine at War |accessdate=2019-01-09 }}</ref>\n*Captain Arthur L. Johnson, Master of the SS ''Virginia Dare'' was given the [[Merchant Marine Distinguished Service Medal]] by The President of the United States. He was awarded for leadership and high courage in the face of attacking planes. The award was given by Admiral [[Emory S. Land]].<ref>[http://www.usmm.org/heroes.html usmm.org Heroes] </ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Liberty ships V}}\n{{MARCOM ships North Carolina SB Co.}}\n{{Liberty ships }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Virginia Dare}}\n[[Category:Liberty ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Wilmington, North Carolina]]\n[[Category:1942 ships]]\n\n\n{{liberty-ship-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Pennsy22", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAwards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SS_Virginia_Dare"}
{"title_page": "Solomon Grundy (nursery rhyme)", "text_new": "{{short description|English nursery rhyme}}\n{{distinguish|text=[[Salmagundi]] or [[Solomon Gundy]]}}\n[[File:BookOfNurseryRhymes p89.jpg|thumb|\"Here lies ye bodye of Solomon Grundy. Died on Saturday...\" An illustration from Clara E. Atwood's 1901 ''A Book of Nursery Rhymes'']]\n\n\"'''Solomon Grundy'''\" is an [[English people|English]] [[nursery rhyme]]. It has a [[Roud Folk Song Index]] number of 19299.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.vwml.org/record/RoudFS/S276827 | title=Roud Folksong Index S276827Solomon Grundy, born on a Monday | publisher=[[English Folk Dance and Song Society]] | work=[[Vaughan Williams Memorial Library]] | accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Lyrics==\nThe rhyme has varied very little since it was first collected by [[James Orchard Halliwell]] and published in 1842 with the lyrics:\n\n;Short version\n{{quote|<poem>Solomon Grundy,\nBorn on a Monday,\nChristened on Tuesday,\nMarried on Wednesday,\nTook ill on Thursday,\nGrew worse on Friday, \nDied on Saturday,\nBuried on Sunday,\nThat was the end,\nOf Solomon Grundy.<ref name=Opie1997>[[I. Opie and P. Opie]], ''The Oxford Dictionary of Nursery Rhymes'' (Oxford University Press, 1951, 2nd edn., 1997), p. 394-5.</ref><ref>[http://www.rhymezone.com/r/gwic.cgi?Word=_&Path=goose/s/38// \"Solomon Grundy\"]. Rhyme Zone. Retrieved January 3, 2018.</ref></poem>}}\n\n;Long version\n{{quote|<poem>Solomon Grundy, born on a Monday, \nChristened on a stark and stormy Tuesday, \nMarried on a grey and grisly Wednesday, \nTook ill on a mild and mellow Thursday, \nGrew worse on a bright and breezy Friday, \nDied on a grey and glorious Saturday, \nBuried on a baking, blistering Sunday. \nThat was the end of Solomon Grundy.<ref>[http://www.nursery-rhymes.org/nursery-rhymes/solomon-grundy.html \"Solomon Grundy\"]. Mother Goose Nursery Rhymes.org. Retrieved January 3, 2018.</ref></poem>}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The nursery rhyme is the inspiration for the [[DC Comics]] character [[Solomon Grundy (comics)|Cyrus Gold/Solomon Grundy]], a large, strong [[zombie]] [[supervillain]] created in 1944 as an adversary for the [[Alan Scott|Green Lantern]], though later a common foe of [[Batman]] and [[Superman]].<ref>Conroy, M. ''500 Comicbook Villains'' (Collins & Brown, 2004), p. 262.</ref>\n* In 1964, [[Jamaicans|Jamaican]] singer [[Eric \"Monty\" Morris]] released the [[ska]] song \"[[Solomon Gundie]]\" whose lyrics were based on the nursery rhyme. It was [[cover version|covered]] in 1980 by French singer [[Amandhihijhjjjjjk Lear]] to a chart success. \n* The premiere episode of ''[[Sesame Street]]'' (air date November 10, 1969) features a Solomon Grundy cartoon in which he washes only one part of the left half of his body each day. At the end of the week Solomon is still \"half dirty\".\n* Jamaican [[Deejay (Jamaican)|deejay]] [[Big Youth]] recorded the song \"Solomon a Gunday\" on his 1972 album ''[[Screaming Target]]'', which was loosely based on the story of Solomon Grundy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Big-Youth-Screaming-Target/master/139872 |title=Big Youth - Screaming Target at Discogs |publisher=www.discogs.com |accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref>\n* \"Hippopotamus\" by Nokoinoko, a Japanese song, was based on the poem. It was aired on \"Hirake Ponkikki\", a TV show for kids, and became popular in 1970s. The strange lyrics made it a cult song and it was used in ''[[The Lost Village (anime)|The Lost Village]]'' anime in 2016.\n* In a 1979 episode of ''[[Wile E. Coyote and the Road Runner]]'', \"Solomon / Grundy Binding\" is referenced on the box of ''ACME Jet-Propelled Skis''.\n* The poet [[Philippe Soupault]] adapted this rhyme and called it \"The Life of Philippe Soupault\".<ref>Stewart, Susan. ''Nonsense: Aspects of Intertextuality in Folklore and Literature'', Johns Hopkins, 1979, p. 191. {{ISBN|0-8018-2258-0}}</ref>\n* The comic book version of Solomon Grundy is mentioned in the song \"[[Superman's Song]]\" by the [[Crash Test Dummies]].\n* There was a professional wrestler named Solomon Grundy who competed as a \"hillbilly\" type character in bib overalls and competed primarily in the Dallas based Wild West and World Class Wrestling companies, as well as in Mexico for the CMLL promotion during the late 80's and early 1990s.\n* The 1992 song \"Mars Ultras, You'll Never Make the Station\" by the band [[Half Man Half Biscuit]] refers to the song in the lines: \"Surrogate Grundy, sold on a Monday, to Richard and Judy\".\n* Comic artist and writer [[Kaori Yuki]] wrote a short story concerning the poem using characters from her series ''[[Earl Cain|Godchild]]'', which was published at the end of book five.<ref>[[Yuki, Kaori]]. ''Godchild'', vol 5, VIZ Media LLC, 2007.</ref> \n* The name and structure of [[Ian McDonald (author)|Ian McDonald]]'s [[science fiction]] novella \"The Days of Solomon Gursky\" (''[[Asimov's Science Fiction]]'' June 1998, reprinted in [[Mike Ashley (writer)|Mike Ashley]]'s 2006 anthology ''[[The Mammoth Book of Extreme Science Fiction]]'')<ref>{{isfdb title |82252|title=The Days of Solomon Gursky}}</ref> are based on the nursery rhyme. The title character (his name coincides with [[Mordecai Richler]]'s 1989 novel ''[[Solomon Gursky Was Here]]'') invents a way to resurrect the dead using [[nanotechnology]], developed in McDonald's 1994 novel ''Necroville''. The spin-off novella consists of seven episodical chapters (titled after the days of the week) showing in increasing intervals Gursky's life from the early 21st century through the [[posthuman]] future in space to the [[end of the universe]] when he constructs a [[Tipler machine]] to be reborn.\n* [[The Bluetones]] song \"[[Solomon Bites the Worm]]\" (1998) was based on this nursery rhyme.\n* Jamaican deejay [[Tapper Zukie]] released the song \"Solomon a Gunday\" on the 2003 re-release of his 1973 album ''Man ah Warrior''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Tapper-Zukie-Man-Ah-Warrior/release/9125796 |title=Tapper Zukie - Man Ah Warrior (CD, Album) at Discogs |publisher=www.discogs.com |accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref>\n* Solomon Grundy appears as a character (and suspect) in [[Jasper Fforde]]'s novel ''[[The Big Over Easy]]'': \"'I'll be dead tired on Saturday,' he quipped to waiting journalists, 'but will bury myself in work again on Sunday.'\"<ref>Fforde, Jasper. ''The Big Over Easy'' (2006) p.163</ref>\n* \"Solomon Grundy\" is the title of the ninth track of ''[[Mic Tyson]]'', the third studio album of American rapper [[Sean Price]].\n* ''Solomon Grundy'', a feature film based on the poem and its structure, was released in 2012. Grundy is portrayed as a child's imaginary friend, and each of the poem's days is represented as a stage in the development of their.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n* \"[[Monday's Child]]\", a traditional English rhyme mentioning the days of the week\n* \"[[Dashing Away with the Smoothing Iron]]\", a traditional [[English folk song]] written in the 19th century about a housewife carrying out one part of her linen chores each day of the week\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:English nursery rhymes]]\n[[Category:Roud Folk Song Index songs]]\n[[Category:English folk songs]]\n[[Category:English children's songs]]\n[[Category:Traditional children's songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about fictional male characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English nursery rhyme}}\n{{distinguish|text=[[Salmagundi]] or [[Solomon Gundy]]}}\n[[File:BookOfNurseryRhymes p89.jpg|thumb|\"Here lies ye bodye of Solomon Grundy. Died on Saturday...\" An illustration from Clara E. Atwood's 1901 ''A Book of Nursery Rhymes'']]\n\n\"'''Solomon Grundy'''\" is an [[English people|English]] [[nursery rhyme]]. It has a [[Roud Folk Song Index]] number of 19299.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.vwml.org/record/RoudFS/S276827 | title=Roud Folksong Index S276827Solomon Grundy, born on a Monday | publisher=[[English Folk Dance and Song Society]] | work=[[Vaughan Williams Memorial Library]] | accessdate=May 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Lyrics==\nThe rhyme has varied very little since it was first collected by [[James Orchard Halliwell]] and published in 1842 with the lyrics:\n\n;Short version\n{{quote|<poem>Solomon Grundy,\nBorn on a Monday,\nChristened on Tuesday,\nMarried on Wednesday,\nTook ill on Thursday,\nGrew worse on Friday, \nDied on Saturday,\nBuried on Sunday,\nThat was the end,\nOf Solomon Grundy.<ref name=Opie1997>[[I. Opie and P. Opie]], ''The Oxford Dictionary of Nursery Rhymes'' (Oxford University Press, 1951, 2nd edn., 1997), p. 394-5.</ref><ref>[http://www.rhymezone.com/r/gwic.cgi?Word=_&Path=goose/s/38// \"Solomon Grundy\"]. Rhyme Zone. Retrieved January 3, 2018.</ref></poem>}}\n\n;Long version\n{{quote|<poem>Solomon Grundy, born on a Monday, \nChristened on a stark and stormy Tuesday, \nMarried on a grey and grisly Wednesday, \nTook ill on a mild and mellow Thursday, \nGrew worse on a bright and breezy Friday, \nDied on a grey and glorious Saturday, \nBuried on a baking, blistering Sunday. \nThat was the end of Solomon Grundy.<ref>[http://www.nursery-rhymes.org/nursery-rhymes/solomon-grundy.html \"Solomon Grundy\"]. Mother Goose Nursery Rhymes.org. Retrieved January 3, 2018.</ref></poem>}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The nursery rhyme is the inspiration for the [[DC Comics]] character [[Solomon Grundy (comics)|Cyrus Gold/Solomon Grundy]], a large, strong [[zombie]] [[supervillain]] created in 1944 as an adversary for the [[Alan Scott|Green Lantern]], though later a common foe of [[Batman]] and [[Superman]].<ref>Conroy, M. ''500 Comicbook Villains'' (Collins & Brown, 2004), p. 262.</ref>\n* In 1964, [[Jamaicans|Jamaican]] singer [[Eric \"Monty\" Morris]] released the [[ska]] song \"[[Solomon Gundie]]\" whose lyrics were based on the nursery rhyme. It was [[cover version|covered]] in 1980 by French singer [[Amanda Lear]] to a chart success. \n* The premiere episode of ''[[Sesame Street]]'' (air date November 10, 1969) features a Solomon Grundy cartoon in which he washes only one part of the left half of his body each day. At the end of the week Solomon is still \"half dirty\".\n* Jamaican [[Deejay (Jamaican)|deejay]] [[Big Youth]] recorded the song \"Solomon a Gunday\" on his 1972 album ''[[Screaming Target]]'', which was loosely based on the story of Solomon Grundy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Big-Youth-Screaming-Target/master/139872 |title=Big Youth - Screaming Target at Discogs |publisher=www.discogs.com |accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref>\n* \"Hippopotamus\" by Nokoinoko, a Japanese song, was based on the poem. It was aired on \"Hirake Ponkikki\", a TV show for kids, and became popular in 1970s. The strange lyrics made it a cult song and it was used in ''[[The Lost Village (anime)|The Lost Village]]'' anime in 2016.\n* In a 1979 episode of ''[[Wile E. Coyote and the Road Runner]]'', \"Solomon / Grundy Binding\" is referenced on the box of ''ACME Jet-Propelled Skis''.\n* The poet [[Philippe Soupault]] adapted this rhyme and called it \"The Life of Philippe Soupault\".<ref>Stewart, Susan. ''Nonsense: Aspects of Intertextuality in Folklore and Literature'', Johns Hopkins, 1979, p. 191. {{ISBN|0-8018-2258-0}}</ref>\n* The comic book version of Solomon Grundy is mentioned in the song \"[[Superman's Song]]\" by the [[Crash Test Dummies]].\n* There was a professional wrestler named Solomon Grundy who competed as a \"hillbilly\" type character in bib overalls and competed primarily in the Dallas based Wild West and World Class Wrestling companies, as well as in Mexico for the CMLL promotion during the late 80's and early 1990s.\n* The 1992 song \"Mars Ultras, You'll Never Make the Station\" by the band [[Half Man Half Biscuit]] refers to the song in the lines: \"Surrogate Grundy, sold on a Monday, to Richard and Judy\".\n* Comic artist and writer [[Kaori Yuki]] wrote a short story concerning the poem using characters from her series ''[[Earl Cain|Godchild]]'', which was published at the end of book five.<ref>[[Yuki, Kaori]]. ''Godchild'', vol 5, VIZ Media LLC, 2007.</ref> \n* The name and structure of [[Ian McDonald (author)|Ian McDonald]]'s [[science fiction]] novella \"The Days of Solomon Gursky\" (''[[Asimov's Science Fiction]]'' June 1998, reprinted in [[Mike Ashley (writer)|Mike Ashley]]'s 2006 anthology ''[[The Mammoth Book of Extreme Science Fiction]]'')<ref>{{isfdb title |82252|title=The Days of Solomon Gursky}}</ref> are based on the nursery rhyme. The title character (his name coincides with [[Mordecai Richler]]'s 1989 novel ''[[Solomon Gursky Was Here]]'') invents a way to resurrect the dead using [[nanotechnology]], developed in McDonald's 1994 novel ''Necroville''. The spin-off novella consists of seven episodical chapters (titled after the days of the week) showing in increasing intervals Gursky's life from the early 21st century through the [[posthuman]] future in space to the [[end of the universe]] when he constructs a [[Tipler machine]] to be reborn.\n* [[The Bluetones]] song \"[[Solomon Bites the Worm]]\" (1998) was based on this nursery rhyme.\n* Jamaican deejay [[Tapper Zukie]] released the song \"Solomon a Gunday\" on the 2003 re-release of his 1973 album ''Man ah Warrior''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.discogs.com/Tapper-Zukie-Man-Ah-Warrior/release/9125796 |title=Tapper Zukie - Man Ah Warrior (CD, Album) at Discogs |publisher=www.discogs.com |accessdate=2018-01-08}}</ref>\n* Solomon Grundy appears as a character (and suspect) in [[Jasper Fforde]]'s novel ''[[The Big Over Easy]]'': \"'I'll be dead tired on Saturday,' he quipped to waiting journalists, 'but will bury myself in work again on Sunday.'\"<ref>Fforde, Jasper. ''The Big Over Easy'' (2006) p.163</ref>\n* \"Solomon Grundy\" is the title of the ninth track of ''[[Mic Tyson]]'', the third studio album of American rapper [[Sean Price]].\n* ''Solomon Grundy'', a feature film based on the poem and its structure, was released in 2012. Grundy is portrayed as a child's imaginary friend, and each of the poem's days is represented as a stage in the development of their relationship.<ref>{{IMDb title|1717686}}</ref>\n* The 2013 track \"Kingston Be Wise\" by [[Protoje]] from his album ''The 8 Year Affair'', references Solomon Grundy in the second verse: \"Then where the gun deh? Dead pon Saturday; Buried Sunday like Solomon Grundy.\"\n* In the 2016 movie ''[[The Accountant (2016 film)|The Accountant]]'', Ben Affleck's autistic character recites the rhyme \"Solomon Grundy\" to calm himself down.\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n* \"[[Monday's Child]]\", a traditional English rhyme mentioning the days of the week\n* \"[[Dashing Away with the Smoothing Iron]]\", a traditional [[English folk song]] written in the 19th century about a housewife carrying out one part of her linen chores each day of the week\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:English nursery rhymes]]\n[[Category:Roud Folk Song Index songs]]\n[[Category:English folk songs]]\n[[Category:English children's songs]]\n[[Category:Traditional children's songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about fictional male characters]]\n", "name_user": "2406:3400:21c:3b70:7d63:4967:768:3771", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eIn popular culture:Hi)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solomon_Grundy_(nursery_rhyme)"}
{"title_page": "Castle of Good Hope", "text_new": "7+1=9\n6-2=1\n90/3=15\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox military structure\n| name = Castle of Good Hope\n| native_name = \n| partof = \n| location = South Africa\n| image = Castle of Good Hope, Cape Town 01.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = Gateway to the Castle of Good Hope\n| pushpin_map = Cape Town Central\n| coordinates = {{coord|-33.9259|18.4278|format=dms|type:landmark_region:ZA|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_mapsize = \n| pushpin_map_alt = \n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in central Cape Town\n| pushpin_label_position = left\n| type = [[Bastion fort]]\n| code = \n| built = {{Start date|1666\u20131679}}\n| builder = \n| materials = \n| height = \n| used = \n| demolished = \n| condition = \n| ownership = \n| open_to_public = Yes\n| controlledby = {{RSA}}\n| garrison = \n| current_commander = \n| commanders = \n| occupants = \n| battles = [[Second Boer War]]\n| events = \n| image2 = \n| caption2 = \n}}\n\nThe '''Castle of Good Hope''' ({{lang-nl|Kasteel de Goede Hoop}}; {{lang-af|Kasteel die Goeie Hoop}}) known locally as '''the Castle'''<ref name=\"worldJourneyTorture\">https://janalinesworldjourney.com/2016/03/28/torture-chambers-at-castle/</ref> or '''Cape Town Castle'''<ref>https://www.iol.co.za/castle-of-good-hope-350/castle350-capes-bastion-of-history-2086709</ref> is a [[bastion fort]] built in the 17th century in [[Cape Town]], South Africa. Originally located on the coastline of [[Table Bay]], [[Foreshore, Cape Town|following land reclamation]] the fort is now located inland.<ref name=teeuwen>[http://www.rendez-vous-batavia.nl/photogallery/south-africa/castle-of-good-hope.pdf Dirk Teeuwen (2007) ''Kasteel De Goede Hoop, Castle of Good Hope''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724163936/http://www.rendez-vous-batavia.nl/photogallery/south-africa/castle-of-good-hope.pdf |date=24 July 2011 }}</ref><ref name=castle>{{cite web|url=http://www.castleofgoodhope.co.za/|title=Home|work=castleofgoodhope.co.za}}</ref> In 1936 the Castle was declared a historical monument (now a [[provincial heritage site (South Africa)|provincial heritage site]]) and following restorations in the 1980s it is considered the best preserved example of a Dutch East India Company fort.<ref name=places/>\n\n==History==\nBuilt by the [[Dutch East India Company]] between 1666 and 1679, the Castle is the oldest existing building in South Africa.<ref name=castle/> It replaced an older fort called the [[Fort de Goede Hoop]] which was constructed from clay and timber and built by [[Jan van Riebeeck]] upon his arrival at the [[Cape of Good Hope]] in 1652.<ref name=capetown>Peter Schirmer (1983) ''Cape Town, The Fairest Cape'', C.Struik (Pty) Ltd., Cape Town {{ISBN|0-86977-186-8}}</ref> Two [[redoubt]]s, Redoubt Kyckuit (Lookout) and [[Redoubt Duijnhoop]] (Duneheap) were built at the mouth of the [[Salt River (river, Cape Town)|Salt River]] in 1654.<ref name=colonial/> The purpose of the Dutch settlement in the Cape was to act as a replenishment station for ships passing the treacherous coast around the Cape on long voyages between the [[Netherlands]] and the [[Dutch East Indies]] (now [[Indonesia]]).<ref name=colonial/>\n\nDuring 1664, tensions between [[Early Modern Britain|Great Britain]] and the Netherlands rose amid rumours of war. That same year, Commander [[Zacharias Wagenaer]], successor to Jan van Riebeeck, was instructed by Commissioner Isbrand Goske to build a pentagonal fortress out of stone. The first stone was laid on 2 January 1666.<ref name=colonial/> Work was interrupted frequently because the Dutch East India Company was reluctant to spend money on the project. On 26 April 1679, the five bastions were named after the main titles of [[William III of England|William III of Orange-Nassau]]: [[Leerdam]] to the west, with [[Buren|Buuren]], [[County of Katzenelnbogen|Katzenellenbogen]], [[House of Orange-Nassau|Nassau, and Oranje]] clockwise from it.<ref name=capetown/> The names of these bastions have been used as street names in suburbs, primarily of Cape Town, such as [[Stellenberg, Bellville]] {{nowrap|({{coord|-33.8687|18.6548|format=dms|region:ZA_type:edu|display=inline}})}}, but also in other provinces.\n\n[[File:Kasteel de Goede Hoop circa 1680.jpg|thumb|left|Sketch of Castle of Good Hope in 1680]]\nIn 1682 the gated entry replaced the old entrance, which had faced the sea. A bell tower, situated over the main entrance, was built in 1684\u2014the original bell, the oldest in South Africa, was cast in [[Amsterdam]] in 1697 by the [[East-Frisia]]n bellmaker [[:fy:Claude Fremy|Claude Fremy]], and weighs just over {{convert|300|kg}}. It was used to announce the time, as well as warning citizens in case of danger, since it could be heard 10 kilometres away. It was also rung to summon residents and soldiers when important announcements needed to be made.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cape-town.org/ShowSite.asp?SecId=1&MemId=142 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911180927/http://www.cape-town.org/ShowSite.asp?SecId=1&MemId=142 |archivedate=11 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe fortress housed a church, bakery, various workshops, living quarters, shops, and cells, among other facilities. The yellow paint on the walls was originally chosen because it lessened the effect of heat and the sun. A wall, built to protect citizens in case of an attack, divides the inner courtyard, which also houses the De Kat Balcony,{{#tag:ref|\"Kat\" is a Dutch term for a transverse wall built for fortification purposes. It dates from Roman times when it also meant a seat of authority or place of command on a battlefield.<ref>Cape Town Highlanders {{cite web |url=http://www.cthighlanders.co.za/castle/voorplein.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005002549/http://www.cthighlanders.co.za/castle/voorplein.htm |archivedate=5 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}, Dirk Teeuwen (2007) ''Kasteel De Goede Hoop''</ref>|group=\"note\"}}  which was designed by [[Louis Michel Thibault]] with [[relief]]s and sculptures by [[Anton Anreith]]. The original was built in 1695, but rebuilt in its current form between 1786 and 1790. From the balcony, announcements were made to soldiers, slaves and ''burghers'' of the Cape. The balcony leads to the [[William Fehr]] collection of paintings and antique furniture.<ref name=colonial>{{cite web|url=http://www.colonialvoyage.com/africa/eng/southafrica/capetown/castleofgoodhope.html|title=Colonial Voyage - The website dedicated to the Colonial History|work=Colonial Voyage|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725115547/http://www.colonialvoyage.com/africa/eng/southafrica/capetown/castleofgoodhope.html|archivedate=25 July 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Second Boer War]] (1899\u20131902), part of the castle was used as a prison, and the former cells remain to this day. [[Fritz Joubert Duquesne]], later known as the ''man who killed [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Kitchener]]'' and the leader of the [[Duquesne Spy Ring]], was one of its more well-known residents. The walls of the castle were extremely thick, but night after night, Duquesne dug away the cement around the stones with an iron spoon. He nearly escaped one night, but a large stone slipped and pinned him in his tunnel. The next morning, a guard found him unconscious but alive.<ref name=\"chances\">{{cite book | last =Burnham | first =Frederick Russell | authorlink =Frederick Russell Burnham | coauthors = | title =Taking Chances | publisher =Haynes Corp | date =1944 | location = Los Angeles, California| url = | doi = | isbn = 1-879356-32-5| page = 293 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1936, the Castle was declared an historical monument (from 1969 known as a [[National Monuments Council (South Africa and Namibia)|national monument]] and since 1 April 2000 a [[Provincial heritage site (South Africa)|provincial heritage site]]), the first site in South Africa to be so protected.<ref>p.2, Oberholster JJ, The Historical Monuments of South Africa, Cape Town: The Rembrandt van Rijn Foundation, 1972</ref> Extensive restorations were completed during the 1980s making the Castle the best preserved example of a Dutch East India Company fort.<ref name=places>{{cite web|url=http://www.places.co.za/html/ct_castle.html|title=Castle Of Good Hope|work=places.co.za}}</ref>\n\nThe Castle acted as local headquarters for the [[South African Army]] in the [[Western Cape]], and today houses the Castle Military Museum and ceremonial facilities for the [[Traditional South African Regiments#Western Cape|traditional Cape Regiments]]. The Castle is also the home of the [[Cape Town Highlanders Regiment]], a mechanised infantry unit.<ref name=colonial/>\n\n==Symbolism==\nPrior to being replaced in 2003, the distinctive shape of the pentagonal castle was used on [[South African Defence Force]] flags, formed the basis of some rank insignia of major and above, and was used on [[South African Air Force]] aircraft.\n\n<gallery>\nEnsign of the South African National Defence Force (1994\u20132003).svg|The [[South African Defence Force Ensign]] from 1994 to 2003\nNaval Ensign of South Africa (1981\u20131994).svg|Naval ensign of South Africa prior to 1994, showing the castle insignia\nRoundel of South Africa (1982-2003).svg|Roundel of the [[South African Air Force]] from 1982 to 2003\n</gallery>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nKasteel van Goede Hoop binnenkant hoofdingang.JPG|Inner view of the entrance\nSouth Africa Cape Town Castle Flags.jpg|The six historical flags that have flown over the Cape, in chronological order from right to left: the [[Prince's Flag]], the [[Union Flag#History|flag of Great Britain]], the [[Flag of the Netherlands|Batavian flag]], the [[Union Flag|flag of the United Kingdom]], the [[Flag of South Africa (1928\u20131994)|old South African flag]], and the [[Flag of South Africa|current South African flag]]\nPediment above enterance to CT Castle.jpg|Pediment above entrance to castle.\nCastle of Good Hope, Cape Town 02.jpg|Entrance of main building\nCastle of Good Hope, Cape Town 04.jpg|A cannon in the castle\nCastle of Good Hope - model of the castle in 1710-90.jpg| A model of the castle as it would have appeared between 1710 and 1790.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fortifications of the Cape Peninsula]]\n* [[History of Cape Colony Pre-1806]]\n* [[Noon Gun]]\n* [[List of castles and fortifications in South Africa]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l53FAQAACAAJ|title=The Castle of Good Hope, Cape Town|author=Lalou Meltzer|publisher=Art Link|year=1997|isbn=0-620-20823-6}}\n* Ras, A.C. (1959).  ''Die Kasteel en Ander Vroe Kaapse Vestingwerke''. Tafelberg-Uitgewers\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SO2CGwAACAAJ|title=300 years of the Castle at Cape Town|author=Eric Rosenthal|publisher=H.M. Joynt|year=1966}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://castleofgoodhope.co.za/ Official website]\n* [http://www.aboutcapetown.com/castle.htm Description on tourism website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080516062828/http://www.iziko.org.za/castle/castle.html Castle of Good Hope on the Iziko Museums of Cape Town website]\n* [http://www.fortified-places.com/capetown/ Castle of Good Hope on the Fortified Places website]\n* {{SAHRA site | 920180056 | Castle of Good Hope }}\n\n{{Cape Town}}{{Castles and fortifications in South Africa}}\n[[Category:Castles in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Forts in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1679]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Cape Town]]\n[[Category:History of Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Maritime history of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Military history of South Africa]]\n[[Category:National symbols of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Historic sites in South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African heritage sites]]\n[[Category:1679 establishments in the Dutch Empire]]\n[[Category:Former properties of the Dutch East India Company]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures associated with the Dutch East India Company]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Fort de Goede Hoop}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox military structure\n| name = Castle of Good Hope\n| native_name = \n| partof = \n| location = South Africa\n| image = Castle of Good Hope, Cape Town 01.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| caption = Gateway to the Castle of Good Hope\n| pushpin_map = Cape Town Central\n| coordinates = {{coord|-33.9259|18.4278|format=dms|type:landmark_region:ZA|display=inline,title}}\n| pushpin_mapsize = \n| pushpin_map_alt = \n| pushpin_map_caption = Location in central Cape Town\n| pushpin_label_position = left\n| type = [[Bastion fort]]\n| code = \n| built = {{Start date|1666\u20131679}}\n| builder = \n| materials = \n| height = \n| used = \n| demolished = \n| condition = \n| ownership = \n| open_to_public = Yes\n| controlledby = {{RSA}}\n| garrison = \n| current_commander = \n| commanders = \n| occupants = \n| battles = [[Second Boer War]]\n| events = \n| image2 = \n| caption2 = \n}}\n\nThe '''Castle of Good Hope''' ({{lang-nl|Kasteel de Goede Hoop}}; {{lang-af|Kasteel die Goeie Hoop}}) known locally as '''the Castle'''<ref name=\"worldJourneyTorture\">https://janalinesworldjourney.com/2016/03/28/torture-chambers-at-castle/</ref> or '''Cape Town Castle'''<ref>https://www.iol.co.za/castle-of-good-hope-350/castle350-capes-bastion-of-history-2086709</ref> is a [[bastion fort]] built in the 17th century in [[Cape Town]], South Africa. Originally located on the coastline of [[Table Bay]], [[Foreshore, Cape Town|following land reclamation]] the fort is now located inland.<ref name=teeuwen>[http://www.rendez-vous-batavia.nl/photogallery/south-africa/castle-of-good-hope.pdf Dirk Teeuwen (2007) ''Kasteel De Goede Hoop, Castle of Good Hope''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724163936/http://www.rendez-vous-batavia.nl/photogallery/south-africa/castle-of-good-hope.pdf |date=24 July 2011 }}</ref><ref name=castle>{{cite web|url=http://www.castleofgoodhope.co.za/|title=Home|work=castleofgoodhope.co.za}}</ref> In 1936 the Castle was declared a historical monument (now a [[provincial heritage site (South Africa)|provincial heritage site]]) and following restorations in the 1980s it is considered the best preserved example of a Dutch East India Company fort.<ref name=places/>\n\n==History==\nBuilt by the [[Dutch East India Company]] between 1666 and 1679, the Castle is the oldest existing building in South Africa.<ref name=castle/> It replaced an older fort called the [[Fort de Goede Hoop]] which was constructed from clay and timber and built by [[Jan van Riebeeck]] upon his arrival at the [[Cape of Good Hope]] in 1652.<ref name=capetown>Peter Schirmer (1983) ''Cape Town, The Fairest Cape'', C.Struik (Pty) Ltd., Cape Town {{ISBN|0-86977-186-8}}</ref> Two [[redoubt]]s, Redoubt Kyckuit (Lookout) and [[Redoubt Duijnhoop]] (Duneheap) were built at the mouth of the [[Salt River (river, Cape Town)|Salt River]] in 1654.<ref name=colonial/> The purpose of the Dutch settlement in the Cape was to act as a replenishment station for ships passing the treacherous coast around the Cape on long voyages between the [[Netherlands]] and the [[Dutch East Indies]] (now [[Indonesia]]).<ref name=colonial/>\n\nDuring 1664, tensions between [[Early Modern Britain|Great Britain]] and the Netherlands rose amid rumours of war. That same year, Commander [[Zacharias Wagenaer]], successor to Jan van Riebeeck, was instructed by Commissioner Isbrand Goske to build a pentagonal fortress out of stone. The first stone was laid on 2 January 1666.<ref name=colonial/> Work was interrupted frequently because the Dutch East India Company was reluctant to spend money on the project. On 26 April 1679, the five bastions were named after the main titles of [[William III of England|William III of Orange-Nassau]]: [[Leerdam]] to the west, with [[Buren|Buuren]], [[County of Katzenelnbogen|Katzenellenbogen]], [[House of Orange-Nassau|Nassau, and Oranje]] clockwise from it.<ref name=capetown/> The names of these bastions have been used as street names in suburbs, primarily of Cape Town, such as [[Stellenberg, Bellville]] {{nowrap|({{coord|-33.8687|18.6548|format=dms|region:ZA_type:edu|display=inline}})}}, but also in other provinces.\n\n[[File:Kasteel de Goede Hoop circa 1680.jpg|thumb|left|Sketch of Castle of Good Hope in 1680]]\nIn 1682 the gated entry replaced the old entrance, which had faced the sea. A bell tower, situated over the main entrance, was built in 1684\u2014the original bell, the oldest in South Africa, was cast in [[Amsterdam]] in 1697 by the [[East-Frisia]]n bellmaker [[:fy:Claude Fremy|Claude Fremy]], and weighs just over {{convert|300|kg}}. It was used to announce the time, as well as warning citizens in case of danger, since it could be heard 10 kilometres away. It was also rung to summon residents and soldiers when important announcements needed to be made.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cape-town.org/ShowSite.asp?SecId=1&MemId=142 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110911180927/http://www.cape-town.org/ShowSite.asp?SecId=1&MemId=142 |archivedate=11 September 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe fortress housed a church, bakery, various workshops, living quarters, shops, and cells, among other facilities. The yellow paint on the walls was originally chosen because it lessened the effect of heat and the sun. A wall, built to protect citizens in case of an attack, divides the inner courtyard, which also houses the De Kat Balcony,{{#tag:ref|\"Kat\" is a Dutch term for a transverse wall built for fortification purposes. It dates from Roman times when it also meant a seat of authority or place of command on a battlefield.<ref>Cape Town Highlanders {{cite web |url=http://www.cthighlanders.co.za/castle/voorplein.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-09-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005002549/http://www.cthighlanders.co.za/castle/voorplein.htm |archivedate=5 October 2011 |df=dmy-all }}, Dirk Teeuwen (2007) ''Kasteel De Goede Hoop''</ref>|group=\"note\"}}  which was designed by [[Louis Michel Thibault]] with [[relief]]s and sculptures by [[Anton Anreith]]. The original was built in 1695, but rebuilt in its current form between 1786 and 1790. From the balcony, announcements were made to soldiers, slaves and ''burghers'' of the Cape. The balcony leads to the [[William Fehr]] collection of paintings and antique furniture.<ref name=colonial>{{cite web|url=http://www.colonialvoyage.com/africa/eng/southafrica/capetown/castleofgoodhope.html|title=Colonial Voyage - The website dedicated to the Colonial History|work=Colonial Voyage|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100725115547/http://www.colonialvoyage.com/africa/eng/southafrica/capetown/castleofgoodhope.html|archivedate=25 July 2010|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Second Boer War]] (1899\u20131902), part of the castle was used as a prison, and the former cells remain to this day. [[Fritz Joubert Duquesne]], later known as the ''man who killed [[Herbert Kitchener, 1st Earl Kitchener|Kitchener]]'' and the leader of the [[Duquesne Spy Ring]], was one of its more well-known residents. The walls of the castle were extremely thick, but night after night, Duquesne dug away the cement around the stones with an iron spoon. He nearly escaped one night, but a large stone slipped and pinned him in his tunnel. The next morning, a guard found him unconscious but alive.<ref name=\"chances\">{{cite book | last =Burnham | first =Frederick Russell | authorlink =Frederick Russell Burnham | coauthors = | title =Taking Chances | publisher =Haynes Corp | date =1944 | location = Los Angeles, California| url = | doi = | isbn = 1-879356-32-5| page = 293 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1936, the Castle was declared an historical monument (from 1969 known as a [[National Monuments Council (South Africa and Namibia)|national monument]] and since 1 April 2000 a [[Provincial heritage site (South Africa)|provincial heritage site]]), the first site in South Africa to be so protected.<ref>p.2, Oberholster JJ, The Historical Monuments of South Africa, Cape Town: The Rembrandt van Rijn Foundation, 1972</ref> Extensive restorations were completed during the 1980s making the Castle the best preserved example of a Dutch East India Company fort.<ref name=places>{{cite web|url=http://www.places.co.za/html/ct_castle.html|title=Castle Of Good Hope|work=places.co.za}}</ref>\n\nThe Castle acted as local headquarters for the [[South African Army]] in the [[Western Cape]], and today houses the Castle Military Museum and ceremonial facilities for the [[Traditional South African Regiments#Western Cape|traditional Cape Regiments]]. The Castle is also the home of the [[Cape Town Highlanders Regiment]], a mechanised infantry unit.<ref name=colonial/>\n\n==Symbolism==\nPrior to being replaced in 2003, the distinctive shape of the pentagonal castle was used on [[South African Defence Force]] flags, formed the basis of some rank insignia of major and above, and was used on [[South African Air Force]] aircraft.\n\n<gallery>\nEnsign of the South African National Defence Force (1994\u20132003).svg|The [[South African Defence Force Ensign]] from 1994 to 2003\nNaval Ensign of South Africa (1981\u20131994).svg|Naval ensign of South Africa prior to 1994, showing the castle insignia\nRoundel of South Africa (1982-2003).svg|Roundel of the [[South African Air Force]] from 1982 to 2003\n</gallery>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nKasteel van Goede Hoop binnenkant hoofdingang.JPG|Inner view of the entrance\nSouth Africa Cape Town Castle Flags.jpg|The six historical flags that have flown over the Cape, in chronological order from right to left: the [[Prince's Flag]], the [[Union Flag#History|flag of Great Britain]], the [[Flag of the Netherlands|Batavian flag]], the [[Union Flag|flag of the United Kingdom]], the [[Flag of South Africa (1928\u20131994)|old South African flag]], and the [[Flag of South Africa|current South African flag]]\nPediment above enterance to CT Castle.jpg|Pediment above entrance to castle.\nCastle of Good Hope, Cape Town 02.jpg|Entrance of main building\nCastle of Good Hope, Cape Town 04.jpg|A cannon in the castle\nCastle of Good Hope - model of the castle in 1710-90.jpg| A model of the castle as it would have appeared between 1710 and 1790.\n</gallery>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fortifications of the Cape Peninsula]]\n* [[History of Cape Colony Pre-1806]]\n* [[Noon Gun]]\n* [[List of castles and fortifications in South Africa]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=l53FAQAACAAJ|title=The Castle of Good Hope, Cape Town|author=Lalou Meltzer|publisher=Art Link|year=1997|isbn=0-620-20823-6}}\n* Ras, A.C. (1959).  ''Die Kasteel en Ander Vroe Kaapse Vestingwerke''. Tafelberg-Uitgewers\n* {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SO2CGwAACAAJ|title=300 years of the Castle at Cape Town|author=Eric Rosenthal|publisher=H.M. Joynt|year=1966}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://castleofgoodhope.co.za/ Official website]\n* [http://www.aboutcapetown.com/castle.htm Description on tourism website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080516062828/http://www.iziko.org.za/castle/castle.html Castle of Good Hope on the Iziko Museums of Cape Town website]\n* [http://www.fortified-places.com/capetown/ Castle of Good Hope on the Fortified Places website]\n* {{SAHRA site | 920180056 | Castle of Good Hope }}\n\n{{Cape Town}}{{Castles and fortifications in South Africa}}\n[[Category:Castles in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Forts in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1679]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Cape Town]]\n[[Category:History of Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Maritime history of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Military history of South Africa]]\n[[Category:National symbols of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Cape Town]]\n[[Category:Historic sites in South Africa]]\n[[Category:South African heritage sites]]\n[[Category:1679 establishments in the Dutch Empire]]\n[[Category:Former properties of the Dutch East India Company]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures associated with the Dutch East India Company]]\n", "name_user": "105.225.155.163", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castle_of_Good_Hope"}
{"title_page": "Thames Barrier", "text_new": "{{Infobox dam\n| name = Thames Barrier\n| name_official = \n| image = Thames Barrier 03.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_caption = View of the barrier gates, which are closed when a flood warning is issued\n| image_alt = \n| location_map = \n| location_map_size = \n| location_map_caption = \n| location_map_alt = \n| coordinates = {{coord|51|29|49|N|0|2|12|E|display=inline,title}}\n| country = United Kingdom\n| location = [[London]]\n| purpose = F\n| status = O\n| construction_began = 1974\n| opening = 1982\n| cost = \u00a3534 million\n| builder = {{plainlist|\n*[[Costain Group|Costain]]\n*[[Royal BAM Group|Hollandsche Beton Maatschappij]]\n*[[Tarmac Limited|Tarmac Construction]]\n*[[Cleveland Bridge & Engineering Company|Cleveland Bridge & Engineering]]}}\n| owner = \n| operator = [[Greater London Council]]\n| dam_type = B\n| dam_crosses = River Thames\n| dam_height_foundation = \n| dam_height_thalweg = 20.1 [[metre]]s\n| dam_length = 520 [[metre]]s\n| dam_elevation_crest = \n| dam_width_crest = \n| dam_width_base = \n| dam_volume = \n| spillway_count = \n| spillway_type = \n| spillway_capacity = \n| res_name = \n| res_capacity_total = \n| res_capacity_active = \n| res_capacity_inactive = \n| res_catchment = \n| res_surface = \n| res_max_length = \n| res_max_width = \n| res_max_depth = \n| res_elevation = \n| res_tidal_range = \n| plant_name = \n| plant_coordinates = \n| plant_operator = [[Environment Agency]]\n| plant_commission = \n| plant_decommission = \n| plant_type = \n| plant_hydraulic_head = \n| plant_turbines = 0\n| plant_capacity = \n| plant_capacity_factor = \n| plant_annual_gen = \n| website = [https://www.gov.uk/guidance/the-thames-barrier gov.uk Guidance: The Thames Barrier]\n| extra = \n}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n[[File:Thames Barrier London.jpg|thumb|300px|Far view of the River Thames Flood Barrier]]\nThe '''Thames Barrier''' is a movable barrier system that is designed to prevent the [[floodplain]] of most of [[Greater London]] from being flooded by exceptionally high [[tide]]s and [[storm surge]]s moving up from the [[North Sea]]. It has been operational since 1982. When needed, it is closed (raised) during high tide; at low tide it can be opened to restore the river's flow towards the sea. Built approximately {{convert|3|km|mi|abbr=on|}} due east of the [[Isle of Dogs]], its northern bank is in [[Silvertown]] in the [[London Borough of Newham]] and its southern bank is in the [[New Charlton]] area of the [[Royal Borough of Greenwich]].\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Background ===\nFlooding in London has been a problem since the city was first established in Roman times.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Kendrick|first=Mary|date=1988|title=The Thames Barrier|url=|journal=Landscape and Urban Planning|volume=16|pages=57-68|via=ScienceDirect}}</ref>\u00a0In 1954 the Waverley Committee, established to investigate the serious [[North Sea flood of 1953]] which affected parts of the Thames Estuary and parts of London, recommended that \"''as an alternative to raising the banks, the possibility and cost of erecting a structure across the Thames which could be closed in a surge should be urgently investigated''\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/written-answers/1954/jun/03/coastal-flooding-committees-report|title=Coastal Flooding (Committee's Report) (Hansard, 3 June 1954)|website=api.parliament.uk|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> A large number of designs were put forward, ranging from a huge road viaduct with two 500 foot (150 m) sluice gates crossing the Thames at Crayfordness to flap gates lying on the river bed and floated up by compressed air.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Gilbert, Stuart (Stuart K.)|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11594001|title=The Thames barrier|date=1984|publisher=T. Telford|others=Horner, Ray.|isbn=0-7277-0182-7|location=London|oclc=11594001}}</ref>\u00a0By 1965, when the Greater London Council (GLC) took over responsibility, two major schemes were under consideration, costed at \u00a324 million and \u00a341 million respectively<ref name=\":0\" /> (\u00a3500 million and \u00a3800 million at 2020 prices).\n\nIn 1966 [[Hermann Bondi|Sir Hermann Bondi]] was asked to take an independent view of the situation. He considered the estimated construction costs and the probability of a flood and of damage if the barrier was not built.\u00a0He strongly recommended that a barrier should be built in order to avoid the catastrophe of flooding central London, and a site was agreed at Woolwich.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe barrier protects central London against a storm surge, caused when a deep depression forms to the north of Scotland and progresses across the North Sea and south-easterly towards southern Scandinavia. When such a surge coincides with a high [[spring tide]], the high winds associated with the depression can funnel the water up the Thames Estuary and cause surges of up to 3.5 metres. The planners assessed that in the absence of a barrier, such a surge could inundate 45 square miles (117 km<sup>2</sup>) of land, put hospitals, powers stations and the London Underground out of action and cause damage estimated in 1966 at \u00a32.0 billion<ref>The Thames Barrier:  The Background and Basic Engineering Requirements.  D Ayres Director of Public Health Engineering, GLC.  1983. Paper presented to a meeting of the Institution of Mechanical Engineers, 8th June 1983</ref> (about \u00a350 billion at 2020 prices). The barrier was designed to provide a flood defence capable of resisting a once in 1000 year surge tide at a base date of 2030.\n\n=== Design and construction ===\n[[File:Thames Barrier - simple operation diagram.png|thumb|right|upright=1.2|Diagram showing how the gates work, though the barrier actually rises further than this to allow water to \"underspill\" under the barrier in a controlled fashion]]\n\nThe concept of the rising sector gates was devised by (Reginald) Charles Draper. In 1969, from his parents' house in Pellatt Grove, [[Wood Green]], London, he constructed a working model. The novel rotating cylinders were based on the design of the taps on his gas cooker. The barrier was designed by Rendel, Palmer and Tritton for the [[Greater London Council]] and the concept tested at the [[Hydraulics Research Station]], Wallingford<ref name=\":1\" />. The site at New Charlton was chosen because of the relative straightness of the banks, and because the underlying river chalk was strong enough to support the barrier. \n\nThe Thames Barrier and Flood Prevention Act, authorising construction, was passed in 1972.  In 1974 the GLC placed the two major construction contracts. Civil construction was undertaken by a [[Costain Group|Costain]]/[[Royal BAM Group|Hollandsche Beton Maatschappij]]/[[Tarmac Group|Tarmac Construction]] consortium.   Work began at the barrier site in 1974 and progressed in two phases. The southern piers (9 to 6) were built first, with river traffic diverted to the north side, then traffic routed through the completed southern spans whilst the north side piers (1 to 5) were built. During construction of the piers, precast concrete sills were built in a cofferdam on the north side of the river and floated out and sunk between the piers to form the gate recesses, with access tunnels in the upstream and downstream ends.,<ref>[http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/regions/thames/323150/335688/341764/341785/?version=1&lang=_e Environment Agency] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917221210/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/regions/thames/323150/335688/341764/341785/?version=1&lang=_e |date=17 September 2008 }}</ref> . The second major contract, for the gates and operating machinery, was placed with the Davy Cleveland Barrier Consortium, formed by Davy McKee Ltd<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Davy_McKee_(Sheffield)|title=Davy McKee (Sheffield) - Graces Guide|website=www.gracesguide.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> of Sheffield and [[Cleveland Bridge & Engineering Company|Cleveland Bridge UK Ltd]]<ref>[http://www.al-rushaid.com/engineering06.htm Cleveland Bridge UK projects: Thames Barrier] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619202806/http://www.al-rushaid.com/engineering06.htm |date=19 June 2012 }}</ref>.  The gates of the Barrier were fabricated in sections at Cleveland Bridge's Darlington works and assembled  at Port Clarence on the [[River Tees]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.benring.co.uk/ |title=Benring limited: Thames Barrier \u2013 subcontracted to Cleveland Bridge UK Ltd |publisher=Benring.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref> The gates, gate arms and rocking beams were transported from the Tees to the Thames by barge and lifted into position by two very large floating cranes operated by Neptun of Hamburg (now part of SMIT).<ref>Manufacture and Installation of the Barrier Gates and Operating Machinery - P F Harvey, Davy Cleveland Barrier Consortium - Institution of Mechanical Engineers - Paper presented at a meeting on 8th June 1983.</ref>\u00a0 The mechanical and hydraulic machinery was built by Davy Loewy, Henry Berry and Vickers and trial assembled in Davy\u2019s Darnall works. \u00a0Delays to the civil works required changes to the construction and installation sequence, but commissioning was relatively uneventful and the first trial operation of all the gates together was carried out on 31<sup>st</sup> October 1982.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/archive/frame/article/1982-11-04/3/1.html|title=Archive Page Viewer {{!}} November 4, 1982 {{!}} The Times|access-date=2020-04-14|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the barrier, the flood defences for {{convert| 11|mi|order=flip}} down river were raised and strengthened. The barrier was officially opened on 8 May 1984 by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]].<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news | title = Better way to turn the tide | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | date = 1984-05-09 | page = 2 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/259609689/ | access-date = 6 August 2019}}{{subscription required|via=newspapers.com}}</ref> The barrier cost \u00a3{{Format price|461000000}} (\u00a3{{Format price|{{Inflation|UK-GDP|461000000|1984}}}} now).<ref name=Guardian />{{Inflation/fn|UK-GDP}} Total construction cost was around \u00a3534 million (\u00a31.6 billion at 2016 prices) with an additional \u00a3100 million for river defences.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\nBuilt across a {{convert|520|m|ft|adj=on}} wide stretch of the river, the barrier divides the river into four {{convert|61|m|ft|adj=on}} and two approximately 30-metre (100&nbsp;ft) navigable spans. There are also four smaller non-navigable channels between nine concrete piers and two abutments. The flood gates across the openings are [[circular segment]]s in cross section, and they operate by rotating, raised to allow \"underspill\" to allow operators to control upstream levels and a complete 180 degree rotation for maintenance. All the gates are hollow and made of steel up to {{convert|40|mm|in}} thick. The gates are filled with water when submerged and empty as they emerge from the river. The four large central gates are {{convert|20.1|m|ft}} high and weigh 3,700 [[tonne]]s each.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/Thames_Barrier_2010_project_pack.pdf |title= The Thames Barrier project pack 2010 |publisher= Environment Agency |format= PDF |accessdate= 17 October 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110812172600/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/Thames_Barrier_2010_project_pack.pdf |archivedate= 12 August 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Four radial gates by the river banks, also about 30 metres (100&nbsp;ft) wide, can be lowered. These gate openings, unlike the main six, are non-navigable.\n\n=== Predictions for operation ===\nA Thames Barrier flood defence closure is triggered when a combination of high tides forecast in the North Sea and high river flows at the [[tidal limit]] at [[Teddington Lock|Teddington weir]] indicate that water levels would exceed {{convert|4.87|m|ft}} in central London. Though Teddington marks the [[Normal Tidal Limit]], in periods of very high fluvial flow the tidal influence can be seen as far upstream as [[East Molesey]] on the Thames.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tom de Castella |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-26133660 |title=How does the Thames Barrier stop London flooding? |work=BBC News |date=11 February 2014 |accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Thames Barrier, London, England - Feb 2010.jpg|900px|The barrier from [[Silvertown]] on the north bank of the river during normal operation looking across to [[New Charlton]].}}\n\n=== Barrier closures and incidents ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right; float:right; margin:0 0 1em 1em;\"\n|+Closures per season\n|-\n! Season<br /> (Sep\u2013Apr)\n! style=\"width:40pt;\"| From tidal flooding\n! style=\"width:40pt;\"| From fluvial flooding\n!Total<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/the-thames-barrier |title=The Thames Barrier |author=[[Environment Agency]] |publisher=Environment Agency |date=20 December 2018 |accessdate=31 December 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|1982\u201383\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|1983\u201384\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|1984\u201385\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|1985\u201386\n|0\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|1986\u201387\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|1987\u201388\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|1988\u201389\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|1989\u201390\n|1\n|3\n|4\n|-\n|1990\u201391\n|2\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|1991\u201392\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|1992\u201393\n|4\n|0\n|4\n|-\n|1993\u201394\n|3\n|4\n|7\n|-\n|1994\u201395\n|2\n|2\n|4\n|-\n|1995\u201396\n|4\n|0\n|4\n|-\n|1996\u201397\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|1997\u201398\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|1998\u201399\n|2\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|1999\u201300\n|3\n|3\n|6\n|-\n|2000\u201301\n|16\n|8\n|24\n|-\n|2001\u201302\n|3\n|1\n|4\n|-\n|2002\u201303\n|8\n|12\n|20\n|-\n|2003\u201304\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|2004\u201305\n|4\n|0\n|4\n|-\n|2005\u201306\n|3\n|0\n|3\n|-\n|2006\u201307\n|8\n|0\n|8\n|-\n|2007\u201308\n|6\n|0\n|6\n|-\n|2008\u201309\n|1\n|4\n|5\n|-\n|2009\u201310\n|2\n|3\n|5\n|-\n|2010\u201311\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|2011\u201312\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|2012\u201313\n|0\n|5\n|5\n|-\n|2013\u201314\n|9\n|41\n|50\n|-\n|2014\u201315\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|2015\u201316\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|2016\u201317\n|2\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|3\n|0\n|3\n|-\n|2018\u201319\n|2\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|2019\u201320\n|8\n|0\n|8\n|-\n|'''Totals'''\n|'''105'''\n|'''87'''\n|'''192'''\n|}\n\nDuring the barrier's entire history up to March 2020, there have been 192 flood defence closures. The barrier was closed twice on 9 November 2007 after a [[North Sea flood of 2007|storm surge]] in the North Sea which was compared to the one in 1953.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/7086175.stm BBC report], accessed 8 December 2007</ref> The main danger of flooding from the surge was on the coast above the Thames Barrier, where evacuations took place, but the winds abated a little and, at the Thames Barrier, the 9 November 2007 storm surge did not completely coincide with high tide.<ref>[http://www.pol.ac.uk/home/news/2007-11stormsurge.html ''Surge of 9 November 2007''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221223805/http://www.pol.ac.uk/home/news/2007-11stormsurge.html |date=21 February 2012 }} The Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory (POL), (a part of the Natural Environment Research Council)</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 1989, hours after the [[Marchioness disaster|''Marchioness'' disaster]], the barrier was closed against a spring tide for 16 hours \"to assist the diving and salvage operations\".<ref name=\"maib-marchioness-3\">{{cite report | url=http://www.maib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/marchioness%20and%20bowbelle%20part%20III.pdf | title=Report of the Chief Inspector of Marine Accidents into the collision between the passenger launch ''Marchioness'' and MV ''Bowbelle'' with loss of life on the River Thames on 20 August 1989|date=5 June 1990|publisher=UK Department of Transport Marine Accident Investigation Branch|section=Part III|accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe barrier has survived 15 boat collisions without serious damage.<ref name=telegraph-20140218>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/topics/weather/10646439/The-Thames-Barrier-has-saved-London-but-is-it-time-for-TB2.html |title=The Thames Barrier has saved London \u2013 but is it time for TB2? |first=Michael |last=Hanlon |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=18 February 2014 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 October 1997, the barrier was damaged when the [[dredger]] MV ''Sand Kite'', operating in thick fog, hit one of the Thames Barrier's piers. As the ship started to sink she dumped her 3,300-tonne load of aggregate, finally sinking by the bow on top of one of the barrier's gates where she lay for several days. Initially the gate could not be closed as it was covered in a thick layer of gravel. A longer-term problem was the premature loss of paint on the flat side of the gate caused by abrasion. The vessel was refloated in mid-November 1997.<ref name=\"maib-sand-kite\">{{cite report | url=http://www.maib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/sandkite_pub_1999.pdf | title=Report of the Inspector's Inquiry into the collision of MV ''Sand Kite'' with the Thames Flood Barrier on 27 October 1997| date=April 1999 | publisher=UK [[Secretary of State for the Environment, Transport and the Regions|DETR]] Marine Accident Investigation Branch|accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe annual full test closure in 2012 was scheduled for 3 June to coincide with the [[Thames Diamond Jubilee Pageant|Thames pageant]] celebrating [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II's Diamond Jubilee]]. Flood risk manager Andy Batchelor said the pageant gave the Environment Agency \"a unique opportunity to test its design for a longer period than we would normally be able to\", and that the more stable tidal conditions in central London that resulted would help the vessels taking part.<ref name=\"bbc-test-closure\">{{Cite news|title=Thames Barrier test closure to be on Jubilee pageant day|date=6 March 2012|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-17266139|accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Ownership and operating authority ===\nThe barrier was originally commissioned by the [[Greater London Council]] under the guidance of Ray Horner. After the 1986 abolition of the GLC it was operated successively by [[Thames Water]] Authority and then the [[National Rivers Authority]] until April 1996 when it passed to the [[Environment Agency]].\n\n== Future ==\nThe barrier was originally designed to protect London against a very high flood level (with an estimated [[return period]] of one hundred years) up to the year 2030, after which the protection would decrease, while remaining within acceptable limits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/homeandleisure/floods/105205.aspx|title=[ARCHIVED CONTENT] UK Government Web Archive \u2013 The National Archives|first=Internet Memory|last=Foundation|website=webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090606062958/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/homeandleisure/floods/105205.aspx|archivedate=6 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the time of its construction, the barrier was expected to be used 2\u20133 times per year. By the mid-2000s it was being operated 6\u20137 times a year.<ref>\"Predicting and Managing the Effects of Climate Change on World Heritage, A joint report from the World Heritage Centre, its Advisory Bodies, and a broad group of experts to the 30th session of the World Heritage Committee\" (Vilnius, 2006) UNESCO, p. 29</ref> in the 2010s, the barrier was generally closed twice a year but the average is still 6-7 due to the barrier being raised 50 times in 2013\u201314.\n\nThis defence level included long-term changes in sea and land levels as understood at that time (c. 1970). Despite global warming and a consequently greater predicted rate of [[sea level rise]], recent analysis extended the working life of the barrier until around 2060\u20132070.{{Citation needed|reason=out-of-date|date=July 2019}} From 1982 until 19 March 2007, the barrier was raised one hundred times to prevent flooding. It is also raised monthly for testing,<ref name=\"ThamesWeb144\">[http://www.thamesweb.com/news_story.php?news_id=144 ThamesWeb] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223120826/http://www.thamesweb.com/news_story.php?news_id=144 |date=23 December 2008 }}</ref> with a full test closure over high tide once a year.<ref name=\"bbc-test-closure\" />\n\nReleased in 2005, a study by four academics contained a proposal to supersede the Thames Barrier with a more ambitious 16&nbsp;km (10&nbsp;mi) long barrier across the Thames Estuary from [[Sheerness]] in [[Kent]] to [[Southend-on-Sea|Southend]] in [[Essex]].<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article410118.ece Times Online] 9 January 2005</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, a new Thames Barrier, further downstream at Lower Hope between [[East Tilbury]] in Essex and [[Cliffe, Kent|Cliffe]] in Kent, was proposed as part of the [[Thames Hub integrated infrastructure vision]]. The barrier would incorporate [[Tidal power|hydropower]] turbines to generate renewable energy and include road and rail tunnels, providing connections from Essex to a major new [[Thames Estuary Airport|hub airport]] on the [[Isle of Grain]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Thames Hub: An integrated vision for Britain |work=Thames Hub: An integrated vision for Britain |publisher=Foster+Partners, Halcrow, Volterra |url=http://www.halcrow.com/Thames-Hub/PDF/Thames_Hub_vision.pdf |accessdate=6 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110074451/http://www.halcrow.com/Thames-Hub/PDF/Thames_Hub_vision.pdf |archivedate=10 November 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, in a letter to ''[[The Times]]'', a former member of the Thames Barrier Project Management Team, Dr Richard Bloore, stated that the flood barrier was not designed with increased storminess and sea level rises in mind, and called for a new barrier to be looked into immediately.<ref>{{cite news |title=Letters to the Editor: Thames Barrier |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/letters/article3646129.ece|accessdate=13 January 2013 |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=3 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Thames Barrier engineer says second defence needed |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-20904885 |accessdate=13 January 2013 |work=BBC News |date=5 January 2013}}</ref> The Environment Agency responded that it does not plan to replace the Thames Barrier before 2070,<ref>{{cite news|last=Cole|first=Margo|title=Environment Agency rejects calls for new Thames Barrier|url=http://www.nce.co.uk/news/water/environment-agency-rejects-calls-for-new-thames-barrier/8640896.article?blocktitle=Most-commented&contentID=-1|accessdate=13 January 2013|newspaper=New Civil Engineer|date=10 January 2013}}</ref> as the barrier was designed with an allowance for sea level rise of {{cvt|8|mm}} per year until 2030, which has not been realised in the intervening years.<ref name=\"TBPP\">{{cite web|title=Thames Barrier Project Pack 2012|url=http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/Thames_Barrier_Project_pack_2012.pdf|publisher=Environment Agency|accessdate=2 September 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825053943/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/Thames_Barrier_Project_pack_2012.pdf|archivedate=25 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The barrier is around halfway through its designed lifespan. The standard of protection it provides will gradually decline over time after 2030, from a 1-in-1000-year event. The Environment Agency are examining the Thames Barrier for its potential design life under climate change, with early indications being that subject to appropriate modification, the Thames Barrier will be capable of providing continued protection to London against rising sea levels until at least 2070.<ref name=telegraph-20140218 /><ref name=\"TBPP\" />\n\nIn June 2019 architects [[Lifschutz Davidson Sandilands]] and marine engineers Beckett Rankine launched a proposal for a pedestrian and cycle bridge located next to the Thames Barrier; the scheme, called the Thames Barrier Bridge, was promoted as the only location in east London where a low-level opening bridge across the Thames could have relatively moderate opening spans of circa {{cvt|60|m}}.<ref>[https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/thames-barrier-bridge-proposal-revealed/10042851.article New Civil Engineer] 3 June 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/lifschutz-davidson-sandilands-reveals-thames-barrier-bridge-plans/10042855.article Architects Journal] 3 June 2019</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Thames Barrier Bridge |publisher=Lifschutz Davidson Sandilands, Beckett Rankine |url= https://www.thamesbarrierbridge.com/ |accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\n{{in popular culture|date=December 2018}}\n* ''[[McCallum Best]]'', a British television series that was produced by STV Productions (Scottish Television) and ran from 1995 to 1998 showed an aerial flyover of the Thames Barrier at night, during the opening and closing credits.\n* The 1986 rock music video for \"Cross That Bridge\" by UK Band [[The Ward Brothers]] was filmed both inside and outside Thames Barrier #1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6SRMMNsdIus|title=The Ward Brothers \u2013 Cross That Bridge (1986)|first=|last=Eduardo Montenegro|date=18 August 2014|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n*In the 1982 [[Alexei Sayle]] track \"[['Ullo John! Gotta New Motor?]]\" the barrier is mentioned in the lyrics, \"He works on the Thames barrier \u2013 he works on the Thames barrier!\"\n*The climax of [[Lois McMaster Bujold]]'s 1989 novel ''[[Brothers in Arms (Bujold novel)|Brothers in Arms]]'' takes place in and near a far future version of the Thames Barrier, one which is designed to protect against daily high tides which would otherwise flood London (the novel assumes a far future sea level rise). The barrier in the novel is known colloquially as the \"[[King Canute and the tide|King Canute]] Memorial\".\n*In series 5 episode 7 (1992) of firefighting drama ''[[London's Burning (TV series)|London's Burning]]'', Blue Watch are called to the Thames Barrier to rescue a maintenance worker.\n*In the tenth episode of [[Spooks (series 5)|Series 5]] of ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]'', broadcast in 2006, an environmental group threatens to blow up the Thames Barrier.\n*The Thames Barrier appears in the 2006 ''[[Doctor Who]]'' Christmas special, \"[[The Runaway Bride (Doctor Who)|The Runaway Bride]]\". [[Doctor (Doctor Who)|The Doctor]] and his companion [[Donna Noble]] emerge from the barrier after defeating the Empress of the [[Racnoss]] and her children by flooding her secret underground lair, only to find out that they have accidentally drained the Thames.\n*In 2007, in season 10, episode 5 of ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'' co-host [[Jeremy Clarkson]] drives a racing boat through the Thames Barrier while racing [[James May]], [[Richard Hammond]], and [[The Stig]] to [[London City Airport]].\n*The barrier features as one of the main locations of [[Flood (film)|''Flood'']], a 2007 British [[disaster film]], directed by [[Tony Mitchell (director)|Tony Mitchell]]. It features [[Robert Carlyle]], [[Jessalyn Gilsig]], [[David Suchet]] and [[Tom Courtenay]]. It is based on the 2002 [[Flood (Doyle novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Richard Doyle (author)|Richard Doyle]].<ref name=\"Phase9\">[http://www.phase9.tv/movies/flood.shtml Phase 9 Entertainment, \"Flood\" production details] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309043829/http://www.phase9.tv/movies/flood.shtml |date=9 March 2013 }}. Retrieved 11 January 2011</ref>\n*The barrier features near the end of the music video for [[Take That]]'s 2010 hit single, \"[[The Flood (Take That song)|The Flood]]\".\n*The book \"Flash Flood\" by [[Chris Ryan]] is based around a fictional failure of the Thames Barrier and what happens to the city during such a failure.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<div align=center>\n<gallery widths=\"220px\" heights=\"180px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Thames Barrier Gate Closing.JPG|One of the gates in underspill\nFile:thames.barrier.6.london.arp.jpg|Thames Barrier Pier 6\nFile:thames.barrier.3.london.arp.jpg|Gate in maintenance\nFile:thames.barrier.4.london.arp.jpg|Maintenance close up\nFile:thames.barrier.7.london.arp.jpg|Pier close up\nFile:Thames Barrier tunnel.jpg|Tunnel underneath the Thames Barrier between piers\nFile:Environment Agency 170114 103858a.jpg|Aerial view of the barrier (lowered)\nFile:Environment Agency 170114 133831.jpg|Aerial view of the barrier (raised)\n</gallery>\n</div>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|London}}\n*[[Barrier Gardens Pier]]\n*[[Crossings of the River Thames]]\n*[[Delta Works]] with the [[Oosterscheldekering]]\n*[[Floodgate]]\n*[[MOSE Project]]\n*[[Saint Petersburg Dam]] Flood Prevention Facility Complex\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Stuart Gilbert and Ray Horner. ''The Thames Barrier'' Telford 1984 {{ISBN|0-7277-0249-1}}\n*S Gilbert. ''The Thames Barrier''.  Thomas Telford Ltd. 30 June 1986. 216 pages. {{ISBN|0-7277-0249-1}}.\n* Ken Wilson. ''The Story of the Thames Barrier''. Lanthorn. 1984. 32 pages. {{ISBN|0-947987-05-3}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Thames Barrier}}\n*[http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/homeandleisure/floods/38353.aspx Thames Barrier page at the Environment Agency]\n*[http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/homeandleisure/floods/117704.aspx Animation] showing how the Barrier works\n*{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/topics/weather/10551766/UK-weather-time-lapse-shows-flooding-near-Thames-Barrier.html |title=Time-lapse video showing Thames Barrier operating in flood conditions |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |date=5 January 2014}}\n*[http://www.streetmap.co.uk/newmap.srf?x=541250&y=179750&z=0&sv=541250,179750&st=4&mapp=newmap.srf&searchp=newsearch.srf Streetmap of Thames Barrier]\n*[http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/homeandleisure/floods/38375.aspx Thames Barrier Information and Learning Centre] \u2013 on south side of the Thames\n*[http://www.london.gov.uk/priorities/housing/housing-and-land/thames-barrier-park Thames Barrier Park] \u2013 park by the Barrier on north side of the Thames\n*[http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/homeandleisure/floods/105437.aspx Londons flood defence system]\n*[http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/TB_and_Associated_Gates_2.pdf Map of associated flood barriers]\n*''[http://risques.tv/video.php?id_DTvideo=269 Risques VS Fictions n\u00b08]'', filmed interview (subtitled in French) with Steve East, technical support team leader of the real barrier about the depiction of the barrier and scientific accuracy of [[Flood (film)|''Flood'']].\n*[https://www.pbs.org/video/sinking-cities-london-jzqg22 Sinking Cities: London] 55min. [[PBS]]\n\n{{ThamesCrossings | west= [[Emirates Air Line (cable car)|Emirates Air Line]] | east=[[Woolwich Ferry]] }}\n{{London landmarks}}\n{{LB Newham}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 1984]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the Royal Borough of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the London Borough of Newham]]\n[[Category:Charlton, London]]\n[[Category:Coastal construction]]\n[[Category:Flood barriers]]\n[[Category:Flood control in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Geography of the River Thames|Barrier]]\n[[Category:Infrastructure in London]]\n[[Category:Port of London]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the Royal Borough of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the London Borough of Newham]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox dam\n| name = Thames Barrier\n| name_official = \n| image = Thames Barrier 03.jpg\n| image_size = \n| image_caption = View of the barrier gates, which are closed when a flood warning is issued\n| image_alt = \n| location_map = \n| location_map_size = \n| location_map_caption = \n| location_map_alt = \n| coordinates = {{coord|51|29|49|N|0|2|12|E|display=inline,title}}\n| country = United Kingdom\n| location = [[London]]\n| purpose = F\n| status = O\n| construction_began = 1974\n| opening = 1982\n| cost = \u00a3534 million\n| builder = {{plainlist|\n*[[Costain Group|Costain]]\n*[[Royal BAM Group|Hollandsche Beton Maatschappij]]\n*[[Tarmac Limited|Tarmac Construction]]\n*[[Cleveland Bridge & Engineering Company|Cleveland Bridge & Engineering]]}}\n| owner = \n| operator = [[Greater London Council]]\n| dam_type = B\n| dam_crosses = River Thames\n| dam_height_foundation = \n| dam_height_thalweg = 20.1 [[metre]]s\n| dam_length = 520 [[metre]]s\n| dam_elevation_crest = \n| dam_width_crest = \n| dam_width_base = \n| dam_volume = \n| spillway_count = \n| spillway_type = \n| spillway_capacity = \n| res_name = \n| res_capacity_total = \n| res_capacity_active = \n| res_capacity_inactive = \n| res_catchment = \n| res_surface = \n| res_max_length = \n| res_max_width = \n| res_max_depth = \n| res_elevation = \n| res_tidal_range = \n| plant_name = \n| plant_coordinates = \n| plant_operator = [[Environment Agency]]\n| plant_commission = \n| plant_decommission = \n| plant_type = \n| plant_hydraulic_head = \n| plant_turbines = 0\n| plant_capacity = \n| plant_capacity_factor = \n| plant_annual_gen = \n| website = [https://www.gov.uk/guidance/the-thames-barrier gov.uk Guidance: The Thames Barrier]\n| extra = \n}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n[[File:Thames Barrier London.jpg|thumb|300px|Far view of the River Thames Flood Barrier]]\nThe '''Thames Barrier''' is a movable barrier system that is designed to prevent the [[floodplain]] of most of [[Greater London]] from being flooded by exceptionally high [[tide]]s and [[storm surge]]s moving up from the [[North Sea]]. It has been operational since 1982. When needed, it is closed (raised) during high tide; at low tide it can be opened to restore the river's flow towards the sea. Built approximately {{convert|3|km|mi|abbr=on|}} due east of the [[Isle of Dogs]], its northern bank is in [[Silvertown]] in the [[London Borough of Newham]] and its southern bank is in the [[New Charlton]] area of the [[Royal Borough of Greenwich]].\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Background ===\nFlooding in London has been a problem since the city was first established in Roman times.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite journal|last=Kendrick|first=Mary|date=1988|title=The Thames Barrier|url=|journal=Landscape and Urban Planning|volume=16|pages=57-68|via=ScienceDirect}}</ref>\u00a0In 1954 the Waverley Committee, established to investigate the serious [[North Sea flood of 1953]] which affected parts of the Thames Estuary and parts of London, recommended that \"''as an alternative to raising the banks, the possibility and cost of erecting a structure across the Thames which could be closed in a surge should be urgently investigated''\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://api.parliament.uk/historic-hansard/written-answers/1954/jun/03/coastal-flooding-committees-report|title=Coastal Flooding (Committee's Report) (Hansard, 3 June 1954)|website=api.parliament.uk|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> A large number of designs were put forward, ranging from a huge road viaduct with two 500 foot sluice gates crossing the Thames at Crayfordness to flap gates lying on the river bed and floated up by compressed air.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Gilbert, Stuart (Stuart K.)|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/11594001|title=The Thames barrier|date=1984|publisher=T. Telford|others=Horner, Ray.|isbn=0-7277-0182-7|location=London|oclc=11594001}}</ref>\u00a0By 1965, when the Greater London Council (GLC) took over responsibility, two major schemes were under consideration, costed at \u00a324 million and \u00a341 million respectively:<ref name=\":0\" /> (\u00a3500 million and 800 million at 2020 prices).\n\nIn 1966 [[Hermann Bondi|Sir Hermann Bondi]] was asked to take an independent view of the situation. He considered the estimated construction costs and the probability of a flood and of damage if the barrier was not built.\u00a0He strongly recommended that a barrier should be built in order to avoid the catastrophe of flooding central London, and a site was agreed at Woolwich.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe barrier protects central London against a storm surge, caused when a deep depression forms to the north of Scotland and progresses across the North Sea and south-easterly towards southern Scandinavia. When such a surge coincides with a high [[spring tide]], the high winds associated with the depression can funnel the water up the Thames Estuary and cause surges of up to 3.5 metres. The planners assessed that in the absence of a barrier, such a surge could inundate 45 square miles (117 km<sup>2</sup>) of land, put hospitals, powers stations and the London Underground out of action and cause damage estimated in 1966 at \u00a32.0 billion:<ref>The Thames Barrier:  The Background and Basic Engineering Requirements.  D Ayres Director of Public Health Engineering, GLC.  1983. Paper presented to a meeting of the Institution of Mechanical Engineers, 8th June 1983</ref> (about \u00a350 billion at 2020 prices). The barrier was designed to provide a flood defence capable of resisting a once in 1000 year surge tide at a base date of 2030.\n\n=== Design and construction ===\n[[File:Thames Barrier - simple operation diagram.png|thumb|right|upright=1.2|Diagram showing how the gates work, though the barrier actually rises further than this to allow water to \"underspill\" under the barrier in a controlled fashion]]\n\nThe concept of the rising sector gates was devised by (Reginald) Charles Draper. In 1969, from his parents' house in Pellatt Grove, [[Wood Green]], London, he constructed a working model. The novel rotating cylinders were based on the design of the taps on his gas cooker. The barrier was designed by Rendel, Palmer and Tritton for the [[Greater London Council]] and the concept tested at the [[Hydraulics Research Station]], Wallingford<ref name=\":1\" />. The site at New Charlton was chosen because of the relative straightness of the banks, and because the underlying river chalk was strong enough to support the barrier. \n\nThe Thames Barrier and Flood Prevention Act, authorising construction, was passed in 1972.  In 1974 the GLC placed the two major construction contracts. Civil construction was undertaken by a [[Costain Group|Costain]]/[[Royal BAM Group|Hollandsche Beton Maatschappij]]/[[Tarmac Group|Tarmac Construction]] consortium.   Work began at the barrier site in 1974 and progressed in two phases. The southern piers (9 to 6) were built first, with river traffic diverted to the north side, then traffic routed through the completed southern spans whilst the north side piers (1 to 5) were built. During construction of the piers, precast concrete sills were built in a cofferdam on the north side of the river and floated out and sunk between the piers to form the gate recesses, with access tunnels in the upstream and downstream ends.,<ref>[http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/regions/thames/323150/335688/341764/341785/?version=1&lang=_e Environment Agency] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917221210/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/regions/thames/323150/335688/341764/341785/?version=1&lang=_e |date=17 September 2008 }}</ref> . The second major contract, for the gates and operating machinery, was placed with the Davy Cleveland Barrier Consortium, formed by Davy McKee Ltd<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Davy_McKee_(Sheffield)|title=Davy McKee (Sheffield) - Graces Guide|website=www.gracesguide.co.uk|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref> of Sheffield and [[Cleveland Bridge & Engineering Company|Cleveland Bridge UK Ltd]]<ref>[http://www.al-rushaid.com/engineering06.htm Cleveland Bridge UK projects: Thames Barrier] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619202806/http://www.al-rushaid.com/engineering06.htm |date=19 June 2012 }}</ref>.  The gates of the Barrier were fabricated in sections at Cleveland Bridge's Darlington works and assembled  at Port Clarence on the [[River Tees]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.benring.co.uk/ |title=Benring limited: Thames Barrier \u2013 subcontracted to Cleveland Bridge UK Ltd |publisher=Benring.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2 May 2013}}</ref> The gates, gate arms and rocking beams were transported from the Tees to the Thames by barge and lifted into position by two very large floating cranes operated by Neptun of Hamburg (now part of SMIT).<ref>Manufacture and Installation of the Barrier Gates and Operating Machinery - P F Harvey, Davy Cleveland Barrier Consortium - Institution of Mechanical Engineers - Paper presented at a meeting on 8th June 1983.</ref>\u00a0 The mechanical and hydraulic machinery was built by Davy Loewy, Henry Berry and Vickers and trial assembled in Davy\u2019s Darnall works. \u00a0Delays to the civil works required changes to the construction and installation sequence, but commissioning was relatively uneventful and the first trial operation of all the gates together was carried out on 31<sup>st</sup> October 1982.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/archive/frame/article/1982-11-04/3/1.html|title=Archive Page Viewer {{!}} November 4, 1982 {{!}} The Times|access-date=2020-04-14|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the barrier, the flood defences for {{convert| 11|mi|order=flip}} down river were raised and strengthened. The barrier was officially opened on 8 May 1984 by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]].<ref name=Guardian>{{cite news | title = Better way to turn the tide | newspaper = [[The Guardian]] | date = 1984-05-09 | page = 2 | url = https://www.newspapers.com/image/259609689/ | access-date = 6 August 2019}}{{subscription required|via=newspapers.com}}</ref> The barrier cost \u00a3{{Format price|461000000}} (\u00a3{{Format price|{{Inflation|UK-GDP|461000000|1984}}}} now).<ref name=Guardian />{{Inflation/fn|UK-GDP}} Total construction cost was around \u00a3534 million (\u00a31.6 billion at 2016 prices) with an additional \u00a3100 million for river defences.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\nBuilt across a {{convert|520|m|ft|adj=on}} wide stretch of the river, the barrier divides the river into four {{convert|61|m|ft|adj=on}} and two approximately 30-metre (100&nbsp;ft) navigable spans. There are also four smaller non-navigable channels between nine concrete piers and two abutments. The flood gates across the openings are [[circular segment]]s in cross section, and they operate by rotating, raised to allow \"underspill\" to allow operators to control upstream levels and a complete 180 degree rotation for maintenance. All the gates are hollow and made of steel up to {{convert|40|mm|in}} thick. The gates are filled with water when submerged and empty as they emerge from the river. The four large central gates are {{convert|20.1|m|ft}} high and weigh 3,700 [[tonne]]s each.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/Thames_Barrier_2010_project_pack.pdf |title= The Thames Barrier project pack 2010 |publisher= Environment Agency |format= PDF |accessdate= 17 October 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110812172600/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/Thames_Barrier_2010_project_pack.pdf |archivedate= 12 August 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Four radial gates by the river banks, also about 30 metres (100&nbsp;ft) wide, can be lowered. These gate openings, unlike the main six, are non-navigable.\n\n=== Predictions for operation ===\nA Thames Barrier flood defence closure is triggered when a combination of high tides forecast in the North Sea and high river flows at the [[tidal limit]] at [[Teddington Lock|Teddington weir]] indicate that water levels would exceed {{convert|4.87|m|ft}} in central London. Though Teddington marks the [[Normal Tidal Limit]], in periods of very high fluvial flow the tidal influence can be seen as far upstream as [[East Molesey]] on the Thames.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tom de Castella |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-26133660 |title=How does the Thames Barrier stop London flooding? |work=BBC News |date=11 February 2014 |accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Thames Barrier, London, England - Feb 2010.jpg|900px|The barrier from [[Silvertown]] on the north bank of the river during normal operation looking across to [[New Charlton]].}}\n\n=== Barrier closures and incidents ===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right; float:right; margin:0 0 1em 1em;\"\n|+Closures per season\n|-\n! Season<br /> (Sep\u2013Apr)\n! style=\"width:40pt;\"| From tidal flooding\n! style=\"width:40pt;\"| From fluvial flooding\n!Total<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/the-thames-barrier |title=The Thames Barrier |author=[[Environment Agency]] |publisher=Environment Agency |date=20 December 2018 |accessdate=31 December 2018 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n|-\n|1982\u201383\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|1983\u201384\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|1984\u201385\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|1985\u201386\n|0\n|1\n|1\n|-\n|1986\u201387\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|1987\u201388\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|1988\u201389\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|1989\u201390\n|1\n|3\n|4\n|-\n|1990\u201391\n|2\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|1991\u201392\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|1992\u201393\n|4\n|0\n|4\n|-\n|1993\u201394\n|3\n|4\n|7\n|-\n|1994\u201395\n|2\n|2\n|4\n|-\n|1995\u201396\n|4\n|0\n|4\n|-\n|1996\u201397\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|1997\u201398\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|1998\u201399\n|2\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|1999\u201300\n|3\n|3\n|6\n|-\n|2000\u201301\n|16\n|8\n|24\n|-\n|2001\u201302\n|3\n|1\n|4\n|-\n|2002\u201303\n|8\n|12\n|20\n|-\n|2003\u201304\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|2004\u201305\n|4\n|0\n|4\n|-\n|2005\u201306\n|3\n|0\n|3\n|-\n|2006\u201307\n|8\n|0\n|8\n|-\n|2007\u201308\n|6\n|0\n|6\n|-\n|2008\u201309\n|1\n|4\n|5\n|-\n|2009\u201310\n|2\n|3\n|5\n|-\n|2010\u201311\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|2011\u201312\n|0\n|0\n|0\n|-\n|2012\u201313\n|0\n|5\n|5\n|-\n|2013\u201314\n|9\n|41\n|50\n|-\n|2014\u201315\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|2015\u201316\n|1\n|0\n|1\n|-\n|2016\u201317\n|2\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|2017\u201318\n|3\n|0\n|3\n|-\n|2018\u201319\n|2\n|0\n|2\n|-\n|2019\u201320\n|8\n|0\n|8\n|-\n|'''Totals'''\n|'''105'''\n|'''87'''\n|'''192'''\n|}\n\nDuring the barrier's entire history up to March 2020, there have been 192 flood defence closures. The barrier was closed twice on 9 November 2007 after a [[North Sea flood of 2007|storm surge]] in the North Sea which was compared to the one in 1953.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/7086175.stm BBC report], accessed 8 December 2007</ref> The main danger of flooding from the surge was on the coast above the Thames Barrier, where evacuations took place, but the winds abated a little and, at the Thames Barrier, the 9 November 2007 storm surge did not completely coincide with high tide.<ref>[http://www.pol.ac.uk/home/news/2007-11stormsurge.html ''Surge of 9 November 2007''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120221223805/http://www.pol.ac.uk/home/news/2007-11stormsurge.html |date=21 February 2012 }} The Proudman Oceanographic Laboratory (POL), (a part of the Natural Environment Research Council)</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 1989, hours after the [[Marchioness disaster|''Marchioness'' disaster]], the barrier was closed against a spring tide for 16 hours \"to assist the diving and salvage operations\".<ref name=\"maib-marchioness-3\">{{cite report | url=http://www.maib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/marchioness%20and%20bowbelle%20part%20III.pdf | title=Report of the Chief Inspector of Marine Accidents into the collision between the passenger launch ''Marchioness'' and MV ''Bowbelle'' with loss of life on the River Thames on 20 August 1989|date=5 June 1990|publisher=UK Department of Transport Marine Accident Investigation Branch|section=Part III|accessdate=9 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe barrier has survived 15 boat collisions without serious damage.<ref name=telegraph-20140218>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/topics/weather/10646439/The-Thames-Barrier-has-saved-London-but-is-it-time-for-TB2.html |title=The Thames Barrier has saved London \u2013 but is it time for TB2? |first=Michael |last=Hanlon |newspaper=Daily Telegraph |location=London |date=18 February 2014 |accessdate=3 March 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 October 1997, the barrier was damaged when the [[dredger]] MV ''Sand Kite'', operating in thick fog, hit one of the Thames Barrier's piers. As the ship started to sink she dumped her 3,300-tonne load of aggregate, finally sinking by the bow on top of one of the barrier's gates where she lay for several days. Initially the gate could not be closed as it was covered in a thick layer of gravel. A longer-term problem was the premature loss of paint on the flat side of the gate caused by abrasion. The vessel was refloated in mid-November 1997.<ref name=\"maib-sand-kite\">{{cite report | url=http://www.maib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/sandkite_pub_1999.pdf | title=Report of the Inspector's Inquiry into the collision of MV ''Sand Kite'' with the Thames Flood Barrier on 27 October 1997| date=April 1999 | publisher=UK [[Secretary of State for the Environment, Transport and the Regions|DETR]] Marine Accident Investigation Branch|accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe annual full test closure in 2012 was scheduled for 3 June to coincide with the [[Thames Diamond Jubilee Pageant|Thames pageant]] celebrating [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II's Diamond Jubilee]]. Flood risk manager Andy Batchelor said the pageant gave the Environment Agency \"a unique opportunity to test its design for a longer period than we would normally be able to\", and that the more stable tidal conditions in central London that resulted would help the vessels taking part.<ref name=\"bbc-test-closure\">{{Cite news|title=Thames Barrier test closure to be on Jubilee pageant day|date=6 March 2012|work=BBC News|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-17266139|accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref>\n\n=== Ownership and operating authority ===\nThe barrier was originally commissioned by the [[Greater London Council]] under the guidance of Ray Horner. After the 1986 abolition of the GLC it was operated successively by [[Thames Water]] Authority and then the [[National Rivers Authority]] until April 1996 when it passed to the [[Environment Agency]].\n\n== Future ==\nThe barrier was originally designed to protect London against a very high flood level (with an estimated [[return period]] of one hundred years) up to the year 2030, after which the protection would decrease, while remaining within acceptable limits.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/homeandleisure/floods/105205.aspx|title=[ARCHIVED CONTENT] UK Government Web Archive \u2013 The National Archives|first=Internet Memory|last=Foundation|website=webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20090606062958/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/homeandleisure/floods/105205.aspx|archivedate=6 June 2009|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the time of its construction, the barrier was expected to be used 2\u20133 times per year. By the mid-2000s it was being operated 6\u20137 times a year.<ref>\"Predicting and Managing the Effects of Climate Change on World Heritage, A joint report from the World Heritage Centre, its Advisory Bodies, and a broad group of experts to the 30th session of the World Heritage Committee\" (Vilnius, 2006) UNESCO, p. 29</ref> in the 2010s, the barrier was generally closed twice a year but the average is still 6-7 due to the barrier being raised 50 times in 2013\u201314.\n\nThis defence level included long-term changes in sea and land levels as understood at that time (c. 1970). Despite global warming and a consequently greater predicted rate of [[sea level rise]], recent analysis extended the working life of the barrier until around 2060\u20132070.{{Citation needed|reason=out-of-date|date=July 2019}} From 1982 until 19 March 2007, the barrier was raised one hundred times to prevent flooding. It is also raised monthly for testing,<ref name=\"ThamesWeb144\">[http://www.thamesweb.com/news_story.php?news_id=144 ThamesWeb] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223120826/http://www.thamesweb.com/news_story.php?news_id=144 |date=23 December 2008 }}</ref> with a full test closure over high tide once a year.<ref name=\"bbc-test-closure\" />\n\nReleased in 2005, a study by four academics contained a proposal to supersede the Thames Barrier with a more ambitious 16&nbsp;km (10&nbsp;mi) long barrier across the Thames Estuary from [[Sheerness]] in [[Kent]] to [[Southend-on-Sea|Southend]] in [[Essex]].<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article410118.ece Times Online] 9 January 2005</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, a new Thames Barrier, further downstream at Lower Hope between [[East Tilbury]] in Essex and [[Cliffe, Kent|Cliffe]] in Kent, was proposed as part of the [[Thames Hub integrated infrastructure vision]]. The barrier would incorporate [[Tidal power|hydropower]] turbines to generate renewable energy and include road and rail tunnels, providing connections from Essex to a major new [[Thames Estuary Airport|hub airport]] on the [[Isle of Grain]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Thames Hub: An integrated vision for Britain |work=Thames Hub: An integrated vision for Britain |publisher=Foster+Partners, Halcrow, Volterra |url=http://www.halcrow.com/Thames-Hub/PDF/Thames_Hub_vision.pdf |accessdate=6 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111110074451/http://www.halcrow.com/Thames-Hub/PDF/Thames_Hub_vision.pdf |archivedate=10 November 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, in a letter to ''[[The Times]]'', a former member of the Thames Barrier Project Management Team, Dr Richard Bloore, stated that the flood barrier was not designed with increased storminess and sea level rises in mind, and called for a new barrier to be looked into immediately.<ref>{{cite news |title=Letters to the Editor: Thames Barrier |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/opinion/letters/article3646129.ece|accessdate=13 January 2013 |newspaper=The Times |location=London |date=3 January 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Thames Barrier engineer says second defence needed |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-20904885 |accessdate=13 January 2013 |work=BBC News |date=5 January 2013}}</ref> The Environment Agency responded that it does not plan to replace the Thames Barrier before 2070,<ref>{{cite news|last=Cole|first=Margo|title=Environment Agency rejects calls for new Thames Barrier|url=http://www.nce.co.uk/news/water/environment-agency-rejects-calls-for-new-thames-barrier/8640896.article?blocktitle=Most-commented&contentID=-1|accessdate=13 January 2013|newspaper=New Civil Engineer|date=10 January 2013}}</ref> as the barrier was designed with an allowance for sea level rise of {{cvt|8|mm}} per year until 2030, which has not been realised in the intervening years.<ref name=\"TBPP\">{{cite web|title=Thames Barrier Project Pack 2012|url=http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/Thames_Barrier_Project_pack_2012.pdf|publisher=Environment Agency|accessdate=2 September 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120825053943/http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/static/documents/Leisure/Thames_Barrier_Project_pack_2012.pdf|archivedate=25 August 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The barrier is around halfway through its designed lifespan. The standard of protection it provides will gradually decline over time after 2030, from a 1-in-1000-year event. The Environment Agency are examining the Thames Barrier for its potential design life under climate change, with early indications being that subject to appropriate modification, the Thames Barrier will be capable of providing continued protection to London against rising sea levels until at least 2070.<ref name=telegraph-20140218 /><ref name=\"TBPP\" />\n\nIn June 2019 architects [[Lifschutz Davidson Sandilands]] and marine engineers Beckett Rankine launched a proposal for a pedestrian and cycle bridge located next to the Thames Barrier; the scheme, called the Thames Barrier Bridge, was promoted as the only location in east London where a low-level opening bridge across the Thames could have relatively moderate opening spans of circa {{cvt|60|m}}.<ref>[https://www.newcivilengineer.com/latest/thames-barrier-bridge-proposal-revealed/10042851.article New Civil Engineer] 3 June 2019</ref><ref>[https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/news/lifschutz-davidson-sandilands-reveals-thames-barrier-bridge-plans/10042855.article Architects Journal] 3 June 2019</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Thames Barrier Bridge |publisher=Lifschutz Davidson Sandilands, Beckett Rankine |url= https://www.thamesbarrierbridge.com/ |accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\n{{in popular culture|date=December 2018}}\n* ''[[McCallum Best]]'', a British television series that was produced by STV Productions (Scottish Television) and ran from 1995 to 1998 showed an aerial flyover of the Thames Barrier at night, during the opening and closing credits.\n* The 1986 rock music video for \"Cross That Bridge\" by UK Band [[The Ward Brothers]] was filmed both inside and outside Thames Barrier #1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6SRMMNsdIus|title=The Ward Brothers \u2013 Cross That Bridge (1986)|first=|last=Eduardo Montenegro|date=18 August 2014|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n*In the 1982 [[Alexei Sayle]] track \"[['Ullo John! Gotta New Motor?]]\" the barrier is mentioned in the lyrics, \"He works on the Thames barrier \u2013 he works on the Thames barrier!\"\n*The climax of [[Lois McMaster Bujold]]'s 1989 novel ''[[Brothers in Arms (Bujold novel)|Brothers in Arms]]'' takes place in and near a far future version of the Thames Barrier, one which is designed to protect against daily high tides which would otherwise flood London (the novel assumes a far future sea level rise). The barrier in the novel is known colloquially as the \"[[King Canute and the tide|King Canute]] Memorial\".\n*In series 5 episode 7 (1992) of firefighting drama ''[[London's Burning (TV series)|London's Burning]]'', Blue Watch are called to the Thames Barrier to rescue a maintenance worker.\n*In the tenth episode of [[Spooks (series 5)|Series 5]] of ''[[Spooks (TV series)|Spooks]]'', broadcast in 2006, an environmental group threatens to blow up the Thames Barrier.\n*The Thames Barrier appears in the 2006 ''[[Doctor Who]]'' Christmas special, \"[[The Runaway Bride (Doctor Who)|The Runaway Bride]]\". [[Doctor (Doctor Who)|The Doctor]] and his companion [[Donna Noble]] emerge from the barrier after defeating the Empress of the [[Racnoss]] and her children by flooding her secret underground lair, only to find out that they have accidentally drained the Thames.\n*In 2007, in season 10, episode 5 of ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]'' co-host [[Jeremy Clarkson]] drives a racing boat through the Thames Barrier while racing [[James May]], [[Richard Hammond]], and [[The Stig]] to [[London City Airport]].\n*The barrier features as one of the main locations of [[Flood (film)|''Flood'']], a 2007 British [[disaster film]], directed by [[Tony Mitchell (director)|Tony Mitchell]]. It features [[Robert Carlyle]], [[Jessalyn Gilsig]], [[David Suchet]] and [[Tom Courtenay]]. It is based on the 2002 [[Flood (Doyle novel)|novel of the same name]] by [[Richard Doyle (author)|Richard Doyle]].<ref name=\"Phase9\">[http://www.phase9.tv/movies/flood.shtml Phase 9 Entertainment, \"Flood\" production details] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130309043829/http://www.phase9.tv/movies/flood.shtml |date=9 March 2013 }}. Retrieved 11 January 2011</ref>\n*The barrier features near the end of the music video for [[Take That]]'s 2010 hit single, \"[[The Flood (Take That song)|The Flood]]\".\n*The book \"Flash Flood\" by [[Chris Ryan]] is based around a fictional failure of the Thames Barrier and what happens to the city during such a failure.\n\n== Gallery ==\n<div align=center>\n<gallery widths=\"220px\" heights=\"180px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Thames Barrier Gate Closing.JPG|One of the gates in underspill\nFile:thames.barrier.6.london.arp.jpg|Thames Barrier Pier 6\nFile:thames.barrier.3.london.arp.jpg|Gate in maintenance\nFile:thames.barrier.4.london.arp.jpg|Maintenance close up\nFile:thames.barrier.7.london.arp.jpg|Pier close up\nFile:Thames Barrier tunnel.jpg|Tunnel underneath the Thames Barrier between piers\nFile:Environment Agency 170114 103858a.jpg|Aerial view of the barrier (lowered)\nFile:Environment Agency 170114 133831.jpg|Aerial view of the barrier (raised)\n</gallery>\n</div>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|London}}\n*[[Barrier Gardens Pier]]\n*[[Crossings of the River Thames]]\n*[[Delta Works]] with the [[Oosterscheldekering]]\n*[[Floodgate]]\n*[[MOSE Project]]\n*[[Saint Petersburg Dam]] Flood Prevention Facility Complex\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Stuart Gilbert and Ray Horner. ''The Thames Barrier'' Telford 1984 {{ISBN|0-7277-0249-1}}\n*S Gilbert. ''The Thames Barrier''.  Thomas Telford Ltd. 30 June 1986. 216 pages. {{ISBN|0-7277-0249-1}}.\n* Ken Wilson. ''The Story of the Thames Barrier''. Lanthorn. 1984. 32 pages. {{ISBN|0-947987-05-3}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Thames Barrier}}\n*[http://www.environment-agency.gov.uk/homeandleisure/floods/38353.aspx