gory:Geography of the River Thames|Barrier]]\n[[Category:Infrastructure in London]]\n[[Category:Port of London]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the Royal Borough of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in the London Borough of Newham]]\n", "name_user": "Ehrenkater", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thames_Barrier"}
{"title_page": "Saturday Night Live at Home", "text_new": "{{short description|Television special}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title = ''Saturday Night Live at Home''\n| series = [[Saturday Night Live]]\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| season = 45\n| episode = \n| director = \n| narrator = \n| music = {{ubl|[[Chris Martin]] covering \"[[Shelter from the Storm]]\"|A variety of ''SNL'' cast performing \"[[Perfect Day (Lou Reed song)|Perfect Day]]\"}}\n| producer = [[Lorne Michaels]]\n| airdate = {{Start date|2020|04|11}}\n| length = 90 minutes\n| presenter = [[Tom Hanks]]\n| guests = {{ubl|[[Fred Armisen]]|[[Alec Baldwin]] as [[Donald Trump]]|[[Larry David]] as [[Bernie Sanders]]|[[Rachel Dratch]]|[[Tina Fey]]|[[Ana Gasteyer]]|[[Bill Hader]]|[[Chris Martin]]|[[John Mulaney]]|[[Paula Pell]]|[[Amy Poehler]]|[[Maya Rudolph]]|[[Molly Shannon]]|[[Adam Sandler]]|[[Emily Spivey]]}}\n| awards = \n}}\n\n'''''Saturday Night Live at Home''''' is a television special that aired on April 11, 2020 as part of the [[Saturday Night Live (season 45)|45th season]] of the late night comedy program ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''.<ref name=\"tvg\" /> The episode was recorded with several remote segments due to the [[impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]; none of them were aired live.<ref name=\"lat\" /> It also served as a tribute to long-time music producer [[Hal Willner]], who died of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]. It was received positively by critics.\n\n==Sketches==\n* The cold open is simply the cast members turning on their [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] and doing a variation of the \"[[Live from New York, it's Saturday Night!|Live from New York...]]\" quote.\n* The opening credits music is then performed by [[Lenny Pickett]] and the band, who all perform from the comfort of their homes, with the cast recreating their opening credits shots from their homes.\n* [[Tom Hanks]] does his opening monologue, opening up about coping with COVID-19. He also takes questions from the \"audience\" (actually Hanks dressed as a Frenchman and an Australian man).\n* [[Pete Davidson]] does a generic [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] song parody from his mother's basement.\n* [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]] ([[Kate McKinnon]]) shows her workout regimen from her home.\n* Some office co-workers attempt to conduct a meeting through Zoom, but two receptionists (McKinnon and [[Aidy Bryant]]) have some difficulty.\n* [[Bernie Sanders]] ([[Larry David]]) explains why he has decided to drop out of the [[2020 United States Presidential election]].\n* A parody ad for [[MasterClass]]: Quarantine Edition, featuring [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]], [[JoJo Siwa]] and [[Carole Baskin]] (all portrayed by [[Chloe Fineman]].)\n* Hanks introduces [[Chris Martin]], who does a cover of [[Bob Dylan]]'s \"[[Shelter from the Storm]]\" from his studio, made to look like the [[Studio 8H]] stage.\n* [[Colin Jost]] and [[Michael Che]] do \"[[Weekend Update]]\", alongside some Zoom audience members. They do a phone interview with [[Donald Trump]] ([[Alec Baldwin]]), and Che does a tribute to his grandmother, who lost her life to COVID-19.\n* Bailey at the Movies ([[Heidi Gardner]]) does a new [[YouTube]] video reviewing movies that were out before the quarantine.\n* An animated sketch parodying ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (1987 TV series)|Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]]'' that shows the turtles in their middle-age.\n* Cam Playz Dat ([[Mikey Day]]) shows how bad he is at playing video games on [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]].\n* British sportscaster Bob Tisdale ([[Alex Moffat (comedian)|Alex Moffat]]) does commentary on mundane things to make up for sports cancellations.\n* [[Kyle Mooney]], [[Beck Bennett]] and [[Fred Armisen]] remix their [[FaceTime]] chats.\n* Bryant leads a \"visualizations\" seminar.\n* A game show parody that showcases dating in the age of quarantine.\n* [[Ego Nwodim]] does a makeup tutorial using only [[Crayola]] markers.\n* Davidson does another hip-hop video parody showcasing his $2,000 in cash, and calling himself \"[[Andre 3000|Andre 2000]]\".\n* Past and present ''SNL'' cast members and writers, including Armisen, [[Rachel Dratch]], [[Tina Fey]], [[Ana Gasteyer]], [[Bill Hader]], [[John Mulaney]], [[Paula Pell]], [[Amy Poehler]], [[Maya Rudolph]], [[Molly Shannon]], [[Adam Sandler]], and [[Emily Spivey]], pay tribute to longtime music producer for the show, [[Hal Willner]], who passed away from COVID-19, by sharing stories about him, and singing [[Lou Reed]]'s \"[[Perfect Day (Lou Reed song)|Perfect Day]]\".\n* Hanks bids the audience goodnight and tells everyone to stay safe, as the credits roll over a still photograph of the empty Studio 8H.\n\n==Production==\n{{seealso|Saturday Night Live (season 45)|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York City}}\nAt the time that the [[World Health Organization]] announced the beginning of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]], the show was in a previously scheduled two-week production hiatus. On March 16, in the midst of break, production of the show was temporarily suspended. The suspension impacted three previously announced episodes: March 28, April 4, and April 11. The host and musical guest for the March 28 episode had been previously announced as [[John Krasinski]] and [[Dua Lipa]] respectively. The episode would have been Krasinski's first hosting appearance and Lipa's second musical guest appearance since [[Saturday Night Live (season 43)|2018]].<ref name=\"stop\" /> The March 28 and April 4 episodes were replaced by reruns. It was announced in early April that the show was scheduled to resume production on April 11, with cast members remotely appearing from their individual homes.<ref name=\"announce\" /> ''SNL'' returned with this remote set-up after almost all American late night programs had already made accommodations to return to air.<ref name=\"slash\" />\n\nLong-time music producer [[Hal Willner]] died of the disease during the hiatus.<ref name=\"rs\" /><ref name=\"var\" /> Additionally, host [[Tom Hanks]] and his wife [[Rita Wilson]] had also been infected by coronavirus but recovered.<ref name=\"hr\" />\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\nWriting for ''[[The A. V. Club]]'', Dennis Perkins gave the special a B\u2212 for the effort put into the episode, [[Chris Martin]]'s performance of \"[[Shelter from the Storm]]\", [[John Mulaney]]'s tribute to Willner, and the creativity of several of the skits, summing up this \"outlier\" episode by writing, \"There wasn\u2019t anything revelatory, or even especially memorable about it, except that it existed... In fact, this version of the show seems constitutionally preordained to settle precisely in the middle, no matter how long ''SNL'' eventually runs. But we could all use some reliable institutions right now, and having ''SNL'' back\u2014even if the future of this season, like so many other things, is deeply uncertain\u2014was surprisingly affecting.\"<ref name=\"avc\" /> Travis Andrews of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' praised the experiment, summing up his overview of the special, \"The inventive episode, born of necessity, gave us much more than [something to do for a little while]. It gave us both the opportunity and excuse to turn off the news and laugh\u2014even if just for a bit.\"<ref name=\"wapo\" /> Both Andrews and Bill Keveney of ''[[USA Today]]'' positioned ''Saturday Night Live'' as a unique television institution that has helped America process national tragedies such as the coronavirus pandemic or [[September 11, 2001 attacks]]; he characterized it as \"strange\" but offering comfort.<ref name=\"ut\" /> Andy Hoglund of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' said the episode was \"an interesting cultural footnote\u2014both in the history of the show, as well as for the historians taking stock of how the U.S. coped during the 2020 global pandemic,\" adding the show's limitations allowed them to go \"full TikTok this episode. Not a bad thing. The show has been addicted to its high production values/capabilities for a while\u2014this liberates the cast to just be weird.\"<ref name=\"ew\" /> Matthew Dessem of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' praised the episode for the sentiment in Willner's tribute and how well several of the sketches worked logistically.<ref name=\"slate\" /> Ethan Anderson of ''[[/Film]]'' wrote that many of the sketches worked, with only three failing, \"a tear of joy came to [his] eyes\" at several points.<ref name=\"slash\" />\n\nWriting for [[NPR]], Eric Deggans conceded that while \"there weren't many laugh-out-loud moments during\" the episode, the effort put into the production and risk-taking made up for some of the weaker content, and particularly praised Martin's performance and the musical ode to Willner.<ref name=\"npr\" /> Several other reviewers noted the uneven comedy but were happy to have the show return as a tribute to Willner and an attempt at normalcy: [[IndieWire]]'s LaToya Ferguson characterized the special as a \"rocky return, despite timely humor and a touching tribute\"<ref name=\"iw\" /> and Judy Berman of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' called it a \"weaker-than-average episode{{nbsp}}... Yet, as I watched what the cast and writers managed to put together, prepared to be disappointed by ''SNL'' as usual, an unexpected sense of gratitude blindsided me.\"<ref name=\"time\" /> For ''[[The Verge]]'', Julia Alexander noted that, while not every segment worked, the series \"rarely produces a show with nothing but outstanding sketches\".<ref name=\"verge\" /> Robert Lloyd of ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote that it was \"pretty good\" all things considered but \"all things not considered, it was pretty good, too\", summing up, \"it\u2019s good to have it there, being more or less itself\".<ref name=\"lat\" /> ''[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]''{{'}}s Matthew Lowe went even further, calling ''Saturday Night Live'' \"as much a public service as it is a show\", writing that this episode was \"less a risk than a gesture of solidarity\".<ref name=\"v\" /> In ''[[The Guardian]]'', Zach Vasquez called parts of the special silly and endearing, summing up that it was a \"valiant effort and a welcome distraction from the larger troubles of the world\".<ref name=\"guard\" />\n\n===Ratings===\nThis was the second highest-rated episode of [[Saturday Night Live (season 45)|season 45]], after the [[Eddie Murphy]]-hosted December 21, 2019 edition, with an average 6.7 million total viewers and a 1.46 [[Audience measurement|rating]], winning the night for broadcast television networks in its time slot.<ref name=\"tvl\" /> This special won the 18\u201349 demographic among broadcast networks with a 2.1 in 25 markets with local people meters and a 4.6 Live+Same Day household rating in the 44 local metered markets.<ref name=\"dlratings\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[2020 in American television]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"announce\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/09/media/snl-saturday-night-live-coronavirus/index.html |date=April 9, 2020 |title=''Saturday Night Live'' Will Be Back This Weekend |first=Frank |last=Pallotta |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"avc\">{{Cite web |last=Perkins |first=Dennis |title=The Cast and Tom Hanks Cobble Together a Scattershot But Welcome ''Saturday Night Live'' Return |publisher=[[The A. V. Club]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |url=https://tv.avclub.com/the-cast-and-tom-hanks-cobble-together-a-scattershot-bu-1842814009}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"dlratings\">{{Cite web |publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/saturday-night-live-ratings-at-home-edition-1202906552/ |title=''Saturday Night Live'' Scores Strong Ratings in Return with at Home Edition}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ew\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/recaps/saturday-night-live-season-45-episode-16/ |last=Hoglund |first=Andy |date=April 11, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |title=''Saturday Night Live'' Recap: Tom Hanks Kicks Off First At-Home Episode}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"guard\">{{Cite web |last=Vazquez |first=Zach |title=''Saturday Night Live at Home'': Tom Hanks Hosts Coronavirus Comedy |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/apr/12/saturday-night-live-at-home-coronavirus-comedy}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"hr\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/tom-hanks-hosts-special-remote-episode-saturday-night-live-at-home-1289919 |title=Tom Hanks Hosts Special Remote Episode of ''Saturday Night Live at Home'' |last=Upadhyaya |first=Kayla Kumari |date=April 11, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"iw\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/04/snl-review-at-home-tom-hanks-1202224454/ |last=Ferguson |first=LaToya |publisher=[[IndieWire]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |title=''Saturday Night Live'' Review: ''SNL at Home'' Is a Rocky Return, Despite Timely Humor and a Touching Tribute}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"lat\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/tv/story/2020-04-12/saturday-night-live-remote-from-home-review-tom-hanks-chris-martin |work=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |last=Lloyd |first=Robert |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |title=Review: ''Saturday Night Live'' Returns in a Remote-from-Home Coronavirus Quarantine Episode}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"npr\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/12/832698515/cast-and-audience-both-do-saturday-night-live-at-home |last=Deggans |first=Eric |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |publisher=[[NPR]] |title=Cast and Audience Both Do ''Saturday Night Live at Home''}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite web |url=https://