 Eddie Murphy |last=Webb |first=Matt |url=https://tvline.com/2020/04/12/tv-ratings-saturday-night-live-at-home-tom-hanks-host/}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"var\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/music/obituaries-people-news/hal-willner-dead-dies-music-producer-saturday-night-live-1234573202/ |title=Hal Willner, Music Producer and ''SNL'' Veteran, Dies of Coronavirus at 64 |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=April 7, 2020 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"verge\">{{Cite web |work=[[The Verge]] |last=Alexander |first=Julia |title=Zoom Became ''Saturday Night Live''{{\u2019}}s Breakout Star in historic All Digital, Remote Episode |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/4/12/21218052/saturday-night-live-remote-digital-episode-zoom-tom-hanks-kate-mckinnon-aidy-bryant}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ut\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/04/11/tom-hanks-hosted-return-saturday-night-live-his-kitchen/2978085001/ |last=Keveney |first=Bill |work=[[USA Today]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |title=''SNL'' Recap: Remote Edition Looked Strange, But Host Tom Hanks Offered the Comfort We Need}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"v\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/snl-at-home-recap-season-45-episode-16.html |work=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |last=Lowe |first=Matthew |title=''Saturday Night Live at Home'' Recap: No-Contact Comedy}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"wapo\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2020/04/12/tom-hanks-hosts-saturday-night-live-home-shows-first-remote-episode-history/ |last=Andrews |first=Travis M. |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |title=Tom Hanks Hosts ''Saturday Night Live at Home'', the Show\u2019s First Remote Episode in History}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official}}\n*[https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/saturday_night_live/s45/e17 Review aggregate] by [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n{{Tom Hanks}}\n{{Saturday Night Live}}\n\n[[Category:2020 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:2020 television specials]]\n[[Category:2020s American television specials]]\n[[Category:NBC television specials]]\n[[Category:Saturday Night Live in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Tom Hanks]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Television special}}\n{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title = ''Saturday Night Live at Home''\n| series = [[Saturday Night Live]]\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| season = 45\n| episode = \n| director = \n| narrator = \n| music = {{ubl|[[Chris Martin]] covering \"[[Shelter from the Storm]]\"|A variety of ''SNL'' cast performing \"[[Perfect Day (Lou Reed song)|Perfect Day]]\"}}\n| producer = [[Lorne Michaels]]\n| airdate = {{Start date|2020|04|11}}\n| length = 90 minutes\n| presenter = [[Tom Hanks]]\n| guests = {{ubl|[[Fred Armisen]]|[[Alec Baldwin]] as [[Donald Trump]]|[[Larry David]] as [[Bernie Sanders]]|[[Rachel Dratch]]|[[Tina Fey]]|[[Ana Gasteyer]]|[[Bill Hader]]|[[Chris Martin]]|[[John Mulaney]]|[[Paula Pell]]|[[Amy Poehler]]|[[Maya Rudolph]]|[[Molly Shannon]]|[[Adam Sandler]]|[[Emily Spivey]]}}\n| awards = \n}}\n\n'''''Saturday Night Live at Home''''' is a television special that aired on April 11, 2020 as part of the [[Saturday Night Live (season 45)|45th season]] of the late night comedy program ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''.<ref name=\"tvg\" /> The episode was recorded with several remote segments due to the [[impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]; none of them were aired live.<ref name=\"lat\" /> It also served as a tribute to long-time music producer [[Hal Willner]], who died of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]. It was received positively by critics.\n\n==Sketches==\n* The cold open is simply the cast members turning on their [[Zoom Video Communications|Zoom]] and doing a variation of the \"[[Live from New York, it's Saturday Night!|Live from New York...]]\" quote.\n* The opening credits music is then performed by [[Lenny Pickett]] and the band, who all perform from the comfort of their homes, with the cast recreating their opening credits shots from their homes.\n* [[Tom Hanks]] does his opening monologue, opening up about coping with COVID-19. He also takes questions from the \"audience\" (actually Hanks dressed as a Frenchman and an Australian man).\n* [[Pete Davidson]] does a generic [[Drake (musician)|Drake]] song parody from his mother's basement.\n* [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]] ([[Kate McKinnon]]) shows her workout regimen from her home.\n* Some office co-workers attempt to conduct a meeting through Zoom, but two receptionists (McKinnon and [[Aidy Bryant]]) have some difficulty.\n* [[Bernie Sanders]] ([[Larry David]]) explains why he has decided to drop out of the [[2020 United States Presidential election]].\n* A parody ad for [[MasterClass]]: Quarantine Edition, featuring [[Timoth\u00e9e Chalamet]], [[JoJo Siwa]] and [[Carole Baskin]] (all portrayed by [[Chloe Fineman]].)\n* Hanks introduces [[Chris Martin]], who does a cover of [[Bob Dylan]]'s \"[[Shelter from the Storm]]\" from his studio, made to look like the [[Studio 8H]] stage.\n* [[Colin Jost]] and [[Michael Che]] do \"[[Weekend Update]]\", alongside some Zoom audience members. They do a phone interview with [[Donald Trump]] ([[Alec Baldwin]]), and Che does a tribute to his grandmother, who lost her life to COVID-19.\n* Bailey at the Movies ([[Heidi Gardner]]) does a new [[YouTube]] video reviewing movies that were out before the quarantine.\n* An animated sketch parodying ''[[Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles (1987 TV series)|Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles]]'' that shows the turtles in their middle-age.\n* Cam Playz Dat ([[Mikey Day]]) shows how bad he is at playing video games on [[Twitch (service)|Twitch]].\n* British sportscaster Bob Tisdale ([[Alex Moffat (comedian)|Alex Moffat]]) does commentary on mundane things to make up for sports cancellations.\n* [[Kyle Mooney]], [[Beck Bennett]] and [[Fred Armisen]] remix their [[FaceTime]] chats.\n* Bryant leads a \"visualizations\" seminar.\n* A game show parody that showcases dating in the age of quarantine.\n* [[Ego Nwodim]] does a makeup tutorial using only [[Crayola]] markers.\n* Davidson does another hip-hop video parody showcasing his $2,000 in cash, and calling himself \"[[Andre 3000|Andre 2000]]\".\n* Past and present ''SNL'' cast members and writers, including Armisen, [[Rachel Dratch]], [[Tina Fey]], [[Ana Gasteyer]], [[Bill Hader]], [[John Mulaney]], [[Paula Pell]], [[Amy Poehler]], [[Maya Rudolph]], [[Molly Shannon]], [[Adam Sandler]], and [[Emily Spivey]], pay tribute to longtime music producer for the show, [[Hal Willner]], who passed away from COVID-19, by sharing stories about him, and singing [[Lou Reed]]'s \"[[Perfect Day (Lou Reed song)|Perfect Day]]\".\n* Hanks bids the audience goodnight and tells everyone to stay safe, as the credits roll over a still photograph of the empty Studio 8H.\n\n==Production==\n{{seealso|Saturday Night Live (season 45)|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York City}}\nAt the time that the [[World Health Organization]] announced the beginning of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]], the show was in a previously scheduled two-week production hiatus. On March 16, in the midst of break, production of the show was temporarily suspended. The suspension impacted three previously announced episodes: March 28, April 4, and April 11. The host and musical guest for the March 28 episode had been previously announced as [[John Krasinski]] and [[Dua Lipa]] respectively. The episode would have been Krasinski's first hosting appearance and Lipa's second musical guest appearance since [[Saturday Night Live (season 43)|2018]].<ref name=\"stop\" /> The March 28 and April 4 episodes were replaced by reruns. It was announced in early April that the show was scheduled to resume production on April 11, with cast members remotely appearing from their individual homes.<ref name=\"announce\" /> ''SNL'' returned with this remote set-up after almost all American late night programs had already made accommodations to return to air.<ref name=\"slash\" />\n\nLong-time music producer [[Hal Willner]] died of the disease during the hiatus.<ref name=\"rs\" /><ref name=\"var\" /> Additionally, host [[Tom Hanks]] and his wife [[Rita Wilson]] had also been infected by coronavirus but recovered.<ref name=\"hr\" />\n\n==Reception==\n===Critical reception===\nWriting for ''[[The A. V. Club]]'', Dennis Perkins gave the special a B\u2212 for the effort put into the episode, [[Chris Martin]]'s performance of \"[[Shelter from the Storm]]\", [[John Mulaney]]'s tribute to Willner, and the creativity of several of the skits, summing up this \"outlier\" episode by writing, \"There wasn\u2019t anything revelatory, or even especially memorable about it, except that it existed... In fact, this version of the show seems constitutionally preordained to settle precisely in the middle, no matter how long ''SNL'' eventually runs. But we could all use some reliable institutions right now, and having ''SNL'' back\u2014even if the future of this season, like so many other things, is deeply uncertain\u2014was surprisingly affecting.\"<ref name=\"avc\" /> Travis Andrews of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' praised the experiment, summing up his overview of the special, \"The inventive episode, born of necessity, gave us much more than [something to do for a little while]. It gave us both the opportunity and excuse to turn off the news and laugh\u2014even if just for a bit.\"<ref name=\"wapo\" /> Both Andrews and Bill Keveney of ''[[USA Today]]'' positioned ''Saturday Night Live'' as a unique television institution that has helped America process national tragedies such as the coronavirus pandemic or [[September 11, 2001 attacks]]; he characterized it as \"strange\" but offering comfort.<ref name=\"ut\" /> Andy Hoglund of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' said the episode was \"an interesting cultural footnote\u2014both in the history of the show, as well as for the historians taking stock of how the U.S. coped during the 2020 global pandemic,\" adding the show's limitations allowed them to go \"full TikTok this episode. Not a bad thing. The show has been addicted to its high production values/capabilities for a while\u2014this liberates the cast to just be weird.\"<ref name=\"ew\" /> Matthew Dessem of ''[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]'' praised the episode for the sentiment in Willner's tribute and how well several of the sketches worked logistically.<ref name=\"slate\" /> Ethan Anderson of ''[[/Film]]'' wrote that many of the sketches worked, with only three failing, \"a tear of joy came to [his] eyes\" at several points.<ref name=\"slash\" />\n\nWriting for [[NPR]], Eric Deggans conceded that while \"there weren't many laugh-out-loud moments during\" the episode, the effort put into the production and risk-taking made up for some of the weaker content, and particularly praised Martin's performance and the musical ode to Willner.<ref name=\"npr\" /> Several other reviewers noted the uneven comedy but were happy to have the show return as a tribute to Willner and an attempt at normalcy: [[IndieWire]]'s LaToya Ferguson characterized the special as a \"rocky return, despite timely humor and a touching tribute\"<ref name=\"iw\" /> and Judy Berman of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' called it a \"weaker-than-average episode{{nbsp}}... Yet, as I watched what the cast and writers managed to put together, prepared to be disappointed by ''SNL'' as usual, an unexpected sense of gratitude blindsided me.\"<ref name=\"time\" /> For ''[[The Verge]]'', Julia Alexander noted that, while not every segment worked, the series \"rarely produces a show with nothing but outstanding sketches\".<ref name=\"verge\" /> Robert Lloyd of ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' wrote that it was \"pretty good\" all things considered but \"all things not considered, it was pretty good, too\", summing up, \"it\u2019s good to have it there, being more or less itself\".<ref name=\"lat\" /> ''[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]]''{{'}}s Matthew Lowe went even further, calling ''Saturday Night Live'' \"as much a public service as it is a show\", writing that this episode was \"less a risk than a gesture of solidarity\".<ref name=\"v\" /> In ''[[The Guardian]]'', Zach Vasquez called parts of the special silly and endearing, summing up that it was a \"valiant effort and a welcome distraction from the larger troubles of the world\".<ref name=\"guard\" />\n\n===Ratings===\nThis was the second highest-rated episode of [[Saturday Night Live (season 45)|season 45]], after the [[Eddie Murphy]]-hosted December 21, 2019 edition, with an average 6.7 million total viewers and a 1.46 [[Audience measurement|rating]], winning the night for broadcast television networks in its time slot.<ref name=\"tvl\" /> This special won the 18\u201349 demographic among broadcast networks with a 2.1 in 25 markets with local people meters and a 4.6 Live+Same Day household rating in the 44 local metered markets.<ref name=\"dlratings\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[2020 in American television]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=\"announce\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/04/09/media/snl-saturday-night-live-coronavirus/index.html |date=April 9, 2020 |title=''Saturday Night Live'' Will Be Back This Weekend |first=Frank |last=Pallotta |publisher=[[CNN]] |access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"avc\">{{Cite web |last=Perkins |first=Dennis |title=The Cast and Tom Hanks Cobble Together a Scattershot But Welcome ''Saturday Night Live'' Return |publisher=[[The A. V. Club]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |url=https://tv.avclub.com/the-cast-and-tom-hanks-cobble-together-a-scattershot-bu-1842814009}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"dlratings\">{{Cite web |publisher=[[Deadline]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 14, 2020 |last=Andreeva |first=Nellie |url=https://deadline.com/2020/04/saturday-night-live-ratings-at-home-edition-1202906552/ |title=''Saturday Night Live'' Scores Strong Ratings in Return with at Home Edition}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ew\">{{Cite web |url=https://ew.com/tv/recaps/saturday-night-live-season-45-episode-16/ |last=Hoglund |first=Andy |date=April 11, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |title=''Saturday Night Live'' Recap: Tom Hanks Kicks Off First At-Home Episode}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"guard\">{{Cite web |last=Vazquez |first=Zach |title=''Saturday Night Live at Home'': Tom Hanks Hosts Coronavirus Comedy |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2020/apr/12/saturday-night-live-at-home-coronavirus-comedy}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"hr\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/tom-hanks-hosts-special-remote-episode-saturday-night-live-at-home-1289919 |title=Tom Hanks Hosts Special Remote Episode of ''Saturday Night Live at Home'' |last=Upadhyaya |first=Kayla Kumari |date=April 11, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"iw\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/04/snl-review-at-home-tom-hanks-1202224454/ |last=Ferguson |first=LaToya |publisher=[[IndieWire]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |title=''Saturday Night Live'' Review: ''SNL at Home'' Is a Rocky Return, Despite Timely Humor and a Touching Tribute}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"lat\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/tv/story/2020-04-12/saturday-night-live-remote-from-home-review-tom-hanks-chris-martin |work=[[The Los Angeles Times]] |last=Lloyd |first=Robert |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |title=Review: ''Saturday Night Live'' Returns in a Remote-from-Home Coronavirus Quarantine Episode}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"npr\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/04/12/832698515/cast-and-audience-both-do-saturday-night-live-at-home |last=Deggans |first=Eric |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |publisher=[[NPR]] |title=Cast and Audience Both Do ''Saturday Night Live at Home''}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"rs\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-news/hal-willner-obituary-979949/ |title=Hal Willner, Music Producer and Longtime ''SNL'' Music Supervisor, Dead at 64 |work=[[Rolling Stone]] |last=Browne |first=David |date=April 7, 2020 |accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"slash\">{{Cite web |publisher=[[/Film]] |url=https://www.slashfilm.com/saturday-night-live-at-home-the-best-and-worst-sketches/ |last=Anderson |first=Ethan |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |title=''Saturday Night Live at Home'' Is a Weird and Wonderful Pick-Me-Up, and Tom Hanks Joined in Too}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"slate\">{{Cite web |url=https://slate.com/culture/2020/04/snl-at-home-coronavirus-quarantine-tom-hanks.html |last=Dessem |first=Matthew |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |title=''Saturday Night Live'' Returns with a Lo-Fi Quarantine Edition Hosted by Tom Hanks}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"stop\">{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/saturday-night-live-coronavirus-1203535899/ |title=''Saturday Night Live'' Postpones Three Shows Because of Coronavirus Concerns |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |first=Kate |last=Aurthur}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"time\">{{Cite web |url=https://time.com/5819658/saturday-night-live-at-home-tom-hanks-review/ |title=''SNL at Home'' Didn\u2019t Land Every Joke\u2014But the Effort Was Unexpectedly Moving |last=Berman |first=Judy |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"tvg\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/saturday-night-live/episode-17-season-45/saturday-night-live-at-home/100385/ |title=Watch ''Saturday Night Live'' Season 45 Episode 17: Saturday Night Live at Home Online (2020) |work=[[TV Guide]] |date=April 11, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"tvl\">{{Cite web |publisher=[[TVLine]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |title=''SNL at Home'' Scores Season's Second-Best Ratings, Trailing Eddie Murphy |last=Webb |first=Matt |url=https://tvline.com/2020/04/12/tv-ratings-saturday-night-live-at-home-tom-hanks-host/}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"var\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2020/music/obituaries-people-news/hal-willner-dead-dies-music-producer-saturday-night-live-1234573202/ |title=Hal Willner, Music Producer and ''SNL'' Veteran, Dies of Coronavirus at 64 |last=Willman |first=Chris |date=April 7, 2020 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"verge\">{{Cite web |work=[[The Verge]] |last=Alexander |first=Julia |title=Zoom Became ''Saturday Night Live''{{\u2019}}s Breakout Star in historic All Digital, Remote Episode |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/4/12/21218052/saturday-night-live-remote-digital-episode-zoom-tom-hanks-kate-mckinnon-aidy-bryant}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"ut\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/04/11/tom-hanks-hosted-return-saturday-night-live-his-kitchen/2978085001/ |last=Keveney |first=Bill |work=[[USA Today]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |title=''SNL'' Recap: Remote Edition Looked Strange, But Host Tom Hanks Offered the Comfort We Need}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"v\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/04/snl-at-home-recap-season-45-episode-16.html |work=[[Vulture (website)|Vulture]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |last=Lowe |first=Matthew |title=''Saturday Night Live at Home'' Recap: No-Contact Comedy}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"wapo\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2020/04/12/tom-hanks-hosts-saturday-night-live-home-shows-first-remote-episode-history/ |last=Andrews |first=Travis M. |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=April 12, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |title=Tom Hanks Hosts ''Saturday Night Live at Home'', the Show\u2019s First Remote Episode in History}}</ref>\n}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official}}\n*[https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/saturday_night_live/s45/e17 Review aggregate] by [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n{{Tom Hanks}}\n{{Saturday Night Live}}\n\n[[Category:2020 American television episodes]]\n[[Category:2020 television specials]]\n[[Category:2020s American television specials]]\n[[Category:NBC television specials]]\n[[Category:Saturday Night Live in the 2020s]]\n[[Category:Tom Hanks]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on television]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toDeadline(link changed toDeadline Hollywood) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saturday_Night_Live_at_Home"}
{"title_page": "Jurassic Park (novel)", "text_new": "{{long plot|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Jurassic Park\n| translator    = \n| image         = Jurassicpark.jpg\n| border        = yes\n| caption       = First edition cover\n| author        = [[Michael Crichton]]\n| cover_artist  = [[Chip Kidd]]\n| country       = United States \n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = [[Science fiction]]\n| publisher     = [[Alfred A. Knopf]]\n| release_date  = November 20, 1990<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cocatalog.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?Search_Arg=Jurassic+Park+%2F+Michael+Crichton&Search_Code=TALL&PID=fRajfjITfjI0pkzSXZyc_NTa34d&SEQ=20160615102142&CNT=25&HIST=1|title=Copyright information for ''Jurassic Park''|publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]]|accessdate=June 15, 2016}}</ref>\n| media_type    = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]])\n| pages         = 448\n| isbn          = 0-394-58816-9\n| dewey= 813/.54 20\n| congress= PS3553.R48 J87 1990\n| oclc= 22511027\n| followed_by   = [[The Lost World (Crichton novel)|The Lost World]]\n}}\n'''''Jurassic Park''''' is a 1990 [[science fiction]] novel written by [[Michael Crichton]]. A [[cautionary tale]] about [[genetic engineering]], it presents the collapse of an [[amusement park]] showcasing [[Genetic engineering|genetically recreated]] [[dinosaur]]s to illustrate the mathematical concept of [[chaos theory]] and its real world implications. A sequel titled ''[[The Lost World (Crichton novel)|The Lost World]]'', also written by Crichton, was published in 1995. In 1997, both novels were re-published as a single book titled ''Michael Crichton's Jurassic World'', unrelated to the [[Jurassic World|film of the same name]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Crichton|first=Michael|title=Michael Crichton's Jurassic World|url=https://archive.org/details/michaelcrichtons00cric|url-access=registration|year=1997|publisher=[[Alfred A. Knopf|Knopf]]|ISBN=978-0375401077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/search?searchArg=9780375401077&searchCode=GKEY%5E*&searchType=0&recCount=25&sk=en_US|title=Michael Crichton's Jurassic world (information)|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|\naccessdate=2015-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/michael-crichtons-jurassic-world-michael-crichton/1120147558?ean=9780375401077|title=Michael Crichton's Jurassic World: Jurassic Park, The Lost World|publisher=[[Barnes & Noble]]|accessdate=2015-01-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, [[Steven Spielberg]] adapted the book into the blockbuster film ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]].'' The book's sequel, ''The Lost World'', was also adapted by Spielberg into a [[The Lost World: Jurassic Park|film]] in 1997. A [[Jurassic Park III|third film]], directed by [[Joe Johnston]] and released in 2001, drew several elements, themes, and scenes from both books that were ultimately not utilized in either of the previous films, such as the aviary and boat scenes.\n\nThe novel began as a [[screenplay]] Crichton wrote in 1983, about a graduate student who recreates a dinosaur.<ref>{{Cite AV media | people = Crichton, Michael | title = Michael Crichton on the Jurassic Park Phenomenon | medium = DVD | publisher = Universal | date = 2001}}</ref> Eventually, given his reasoning that genetic research is expensive and \"there is no pressing need to create a dinosaur\", Crichton concluded that it would emerge from a \"desire to entertain\", leading to a [[Wildlife refuge|wildlife park]] of extinct animals.<ref>\"Return to Jurassic Park: Dawn of a New Era\", ''Jurassic Park'' Blu-ray (2011)</ref> Originally, the story was told from the point of view of a child, but Crichton changed it as everyone who read the draft felt it would be better if told by an adult.<ref>[http://www.michaelcrichton.net/books-jurassicpark-mcnotes.html Michael Crichton's notes on Jurassic Park]</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nIn 1989, a series of strange animal attacks occur in [[Costa Rica]] and on the nearby fictional island of [[Isla Nublar]],<ref>Means approximately \"Clouded Island\" or \"Obscured Island\" in Spanish.</ref> the story's main setting, one of which is a worker severely injured on a construction project on Isla Nublar, whose employers refuse to disclose any information about. One of the species is eventually identified as a ''[[Procompsognathus]]''. [[Paleontology|Paleontologist]] [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dr. Alan Grant|Alan Grant]] and his [[Paleobotany|paleobotanist]] graduate student, [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dr. Ellen Sattler|Ellie Sattler]], are contacted to confirm the identification, but are abruptly whisked away by billionaire [[List of Jurassic Park characters#John Hammond|John Hammond]]&nbsp;\u2014 founder and chief executive officer of International Genetic Technologies, or InGen&nbsp;\u2014 for a weekend visit to a \"biological preserve\" he has established on Isla Nublar.\n\nUpon arrival, the preserve is revealed to be Jurassic Park, a [[Amusement park|theme park]] showcasing [[Cloning#Artificial cloning of organisms|cloned]] dinosaurs. The animals have been recreated using [[Ancient DNA|damaged dinosaur DNA]] found in blood inside of gnats, ticks, and mosquitoes fossilized and preserved in [[amber]]. Gaps in the genetic code have been filled in with \"compatible\" [[Reptile|reptilian]], [[Bird|avian]] or [[amphibian]] [[DNA]]. To control the population, all specimens on the island are [[lysine]]-[[Auxotrophy|deficient]] and X-Ray sterilized females. Hammond proudly touts InGen's advances in [[genetic engineering]] and shows his guests through the island's vast array of automated systems.\n\n[[File:Curva del drag\u00f3n.png|thumb|left|Ian Malcolm created [[dragon curve]]s to simulate the actions that were to take place in the park.]]\n\nRecent incidents in the park have spooked Hammond's investors. To placate them, Hammond uses Grant and Sattler as fresh consultants. They stand in counterbalance to a famous mathematician and [[Chaos theory|chaos theorist]], [[Ian Malcolm (character)|Ian Malcolm]], and a lawyer representing the investors, [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Donald Gennaro|Donald Gennaro]], who are pessimistic about the park's prospects. Malcolm, having been consulted before the park's creation, is especially emphatic in his prediction that the park will collapse, as it is an unsustainable simple structure bluntly forced upon a [[complex system]] with too many unpredictable variables, such as an uncontrollable population, attempting to contain animals with no real equivalent to extant animals with no predictable behavior patterns, and an untested computer system that continually fails to monitor and feed the population.\n\nCountering Malcolm's dire predictions with youthful energy, Hammond groups the consultants with his grandchildren, [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Timothy Murphy|Tim]] and [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Alexis Murphy|Alexis \"Lex\" Murphy]]. While touring the park, Grant finds a ''[[Velociraptor]]'' eggshell, seemingly proving Malcolm's earlier assertion that the dinosaurs have somehow been breeding against the geneticists' design.\n\nMeanwhile, the disgruntled chief programmer of Jurassic Park's controlling software, [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dennis Nedry|Dennis Nedry]], attempts [[Industrial espionage|corporate espionage]] for [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dr. Lewis Dodgson|Lewis Dodgson]], a geneticist and agent of InGen's archrival, Biosyn. By activating a [[Backdoor (computing)|backdoor]] he wrote into the park's computer system, Nedry shuts down its security systems and steals frozen embryos for each of the park's fifteen species in an attempt to smuggle them to a contact waiting at an auxiliary dock at the eastern end of the park. However, during a sudden [[Tropical cyclone#Tropical storm|tropical storm]], he exits his vehicle to get his bearings and is killed by a ''[[Dilophosaurus]]''. Without Nedry to reactivate the park's security, the electrified fences remain off and all the dinosaurs escape. The park's adult ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]'' attacks the guests on tour, with a juvenile ''T. rex'' attacking and killing Ed Regis, the park's public relations manager. In the aftermath, Grant and the children become lost in the park. Malcolm is gravely injured during the incident, but is found by Gennaro and park game warden [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Robert Muldoon|Robert Muldoon]], spending the remainder of the novel slowly dying as {{ndash}} between lucid lectures and morphine-induced rants {{ndash}} he tries to help the others understand their predicament and survive.\n\nThe park's upper management&nbsp;\u2014 engineer and park supervisor [[List of Jurassic Park characters#John Raymond Arnold|John Arnold]], [[biotechnology|biotechnologist]] [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dr. Henry Wu|Henry Wu]], Muldoon, and Hammond&nbsp;\u2014 struggle to return power to the park, while the veterinarian, [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dr. Harding|Dr. Harding]], takes care of Malcolm. They manage to temporarily get the park largely back in order, restoring the computer system by shutting down and restarting the power and resetting the system. When trying to restore the park to working order, they fail to notice that the system has been running on auxiliary power since the restart; this power soon runs out, shutting the park down a second time. The park's intelligent and aggressive raptors escape their enclosure, and kill Wu and Arnold. Meanwhile, Grant and the children slowly make their way back to the Visitor Center by rafting down the jungle river, carrying news that several young raptors were on board the island's supply ship when it departed for the mainland. After the three return to the visitor's center, they are contacted by the others, who instruct Grant to switch on the park's generators. Tim is then able to reactivate the park's main power, allowing Gennaro to force the supply ship to return.\n\nGennaro orders that the island be destroyed, but Grant rejects his authority, claiming that they must first inspect the whole situation. Grant, Sattler, Muldoon, and Gennaro set out into the park to find the wild raptor nests and compare hatched eggs with the island's revised population tally, and return unscathed. Meanwhile, Hammond, taking a walk and contemplating building a new park improving on his previous mistakes, hears a ''T. rex'' roar and, startled, falls down a hill, where he is eaten by a pack of ''Procompsognathus''.\n\nWith regard to the dinosaurs' breeding, it eventually transpires that using frog DNA to fill gaps in the dinosaurs' genetic code enabled a measure of [[Sequential hermaphroditism|dichogamy]], in which some of the female animals changed into males in response to the same-sex environment. The computer tally failed to include newborn animals, having been programmed to stop counting once the assumed correct total number of animals had been found.\n\nThe survivors are rescued by the fictitious Costa Rican Air Force, where Grant reveals that the dinosaurs have been killing people. The Costa Rican Air Force then declare the island hazardous and unsafe, and proceed to raze the island with [[napalm]]. Survivors of the incident are indefinitely detained by the United States and Costa Rican governments at a hotel. Weeks later, Grant is visited by [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dr. Martin \"Marty\" Gutierrez|Dr. Martin Guitierrez]], an American doctor who lives in Costa Rica. Guitierrez informs Grant that an unknown pack of animals has been migrating through the Costa Rican jungle, eating lysine-rich crops and chickens. He also informs Grant that none of them, with the possible exception of Tim and Lex, are going to leave any time soon.\n\n== Themes==\n{{Refimprove section|date=August 2018}}\n[[File:Tyrannosaurus skeletal diagram.jpg|thumb|1917 skeletal diagram of ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]'' published by [[Henry Fairfield Osborn]], which was the basis of the novel's cover]] \nJurassic Park critiques the dystopian potentialities of science. There are Christian undertones in the skepticism of Ian Malcolm, though Christian terminology and imagery is never used. Malcolm is the conscience that reminds John Hammond of the sacrilegious path that has been taken. The final condition of the park is epitomized by the word 'hell', which highlights the nature of Hammond's sacrilegious attempt.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://go.galegroup.com/ps/anonymous?id=GALE%7CH1100078863|title=Rediscovering the Island as Utopian Locus: Michael Crichton\u2019s Jurassic Park.|last=Gallardo-Terrano|first=Pedro|date=2000|via=Gale Academic OneFile|access-date=2018-08-02}}</ref>\n\nMichael Crichton's novel is another version of [[Mary Shelley]]'s ''[[Frankenstein]]'' tale where humanity creates without knowing. Henry Wu is unable to name the things that he creates, which alludes to Victor Frankenstein not knowing what to call his flawed imitation of God's creative powers. The immorality of these actions lead to human destruction, echoing Frankenstein.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://go.galegroup.com/ps/anonymous?id=GALE%7CH1100078866|title=Replicating a Dinosaur: Authenticity Run Amok in the Theme Parking in Michael Crichton\u2019s Jurassic Park and Julian Barnes\u2019s England, England.|last=Miracky|first=James|date=2004|via=Gale Academic OneFile|access-date=2018-08-02}}</ref>\n\nSimilar to how his other novels represent science and technology as both hazardous and life-changing, Michael Crichton's novel highlights the hypocrisy and superiority complex of the scientific community that inspired John Hammond to recreate dinosaurs and treat them as commodities, which only lead to catastrophe. The similar fears of atomic power from the Cold War are adapted by Michael Crichton onto the anxieties evoked by genetic manipulation.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia|url=https://go.galegroup.com/ps/anonymous?id=GALE%7CCX3661700048|encyclopedia=Books to Film: Cinematic Adaptations of Literary Works |title=Jurassic Park |editor-last=Grant|editor-first=Barry Keith|volume=1|last=Geraghty|first=Lincoln|date=2018|via=Gale Academic OneFile|access-date=2018-08-02}}</ref>\n\n==Dinosaurs in novel==\n\n''The list is in alphabetical order''\n\n*[[Apatosaurus]]\n*[[Cearadactylus|Cearadactyl]]                                                                \n*[[Dilophosaurus]]\n*[[Euoplocephalus]]\n*[[Hadrosaurus]]\n*[[Hypsilophodon]]\n*[[Maiasaurus|Maiasaura]]\n*[[Microceratus]]\n*[[Othnielia]]\n*[[Procompsognathus]]\n*[[Stegosaurus]]\n*[[Styracosaurus]]\n*[[Triceratops]]\n*[[Tyrannosaurus]]\n*[[Velociraptor]]\n\n== Reception ==\nThe book became a bestseller and Michael Crichton's signature novel. It also received largely favorable reviews by critics. In a review for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Christopher Lehmann-Haupt]] described it as \"a superior specimen of the [''Frankenstein''] myth\" and \"easily the best of Mr. Crichton's novels to date.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lehmann-Haupt|first1=Christopher|title=Books of The Times; Of Dinosaurs Returned And Fractals Fractured|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/15/books/books-of-the-times-of-dinosaurs-returned-and-fractals-fractured.html|accessdate=27 September 2015|work=[[New York Times]]|date=November 15, 1990}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', [[Gene Lyons]] held that the book was \"hard to beat for sheer intellectual entertainment\" largely because it was \"[f]illed with diverting, up-to-date information in easily digestible form.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lyons|first1=Gene|title=Jurassic Park|url=http://www.ew.com/article/1990/11/16/jurassic-park|accessdate=27 September 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=November 16, 1990}}</ref> Both Lyons' ''Entertainment Weekly'' piece and [[Andrew Ferguson]]'s review in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', however, criticized Crichton's [[characterization]] as heavy-handed and his characters as cliched. Ferguson further complained about Ian Malcolm's \"dime-store philosophizing\" and predicted that the film adaptation of the book would be \"undoubtedly trashy.\" He conceded that the book's \"only real virtue\" was \"its genuinely interesting discussions of dinosaurs, DNA research, paleontology and chaos theory.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ferguson|first1=Andrew|title=The Thing From the Tar Pits : JURASSIC PARK By Michael Crichton (Alfred A. Knopf: $19.95; 413 pp.)|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-11-11/books/bk-5972_1_jurassic-park|accessdate=27 September 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 11, 1990}}</ref>\n\nThe novel became even more famous following the release of the [[Jurassic Park (film)|1993 film adaptation]], which has grossed more than US$1 billion and spawned several sequels.<ref>[http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=jurassicpark.htm Jurassic Park (1993)]. Box Office Mojo (1993-09-24). Retrieved on 2013-09-17.</ref>\n\nIn 1996 it was awarded the Secondary [[BILBY Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbcaqld.org/uploads/2/6/2/2/26224528/previous_bilby_to_2014.pdf |title=Previous Winners of the BILBY Awards: 1990 \u2013 96 |website=www.cbcaqld.org |publisher=The Children's Book Council of Australia Queensland Branch |access-date=4 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119061148/http://www.cbcaqld.org/uploads/2/6/2/2/26224528/previous_bilby_to_2014.pdf |archive-date=19 November 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United States|Novels|1990s|Dinosaurs|Speculative fiction|}}\n*''[[The Cursed Earth (Judge Dredd story)|The Cursed Earth]]'', a [[Judge Dredd]] story line by [[Pat Mills]] in ''[[2000 AD (comics)|2000 AD]]'' from 1978 that introduces the idea of a dinosaur theme park, with dinosaurs cloned from DNA\n*''[[Carnosaur (novel)|Carnosaur]]'', a 1984 novel with similar themes\n*''[[Westworld (film)|Westworld]]'', Crichton's earlier 1973 film also about a malfunctioning theme park\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{Cite book |title=The Science of Jurassic Park and The Lost World. Or How to Build a Dinosaur |first=Rob |last=DeSalle |lastauthoramp=yes |first2=David |last2=Lindley |publisher=BasicBooks |location=New York |year=1997 |isbn=0-465-07379-4 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/scienceofjurassi00desa }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Jurassic Park (novel)}}  \n*[http://sites.google.com/site/HZTomassi/isla-nublar-map ''Isla Nublar novel map'']\n*{{Official website|http://www.jurassicpark.com}}\n* {{isfdb title|id=1678|title=Jurassic Park}}\n*[http://www.michaelcrichton.com/books-jurassicpark.html ''Jurassic Park''] at the official Michael Crichton website\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{s-bef | before = ''[[Looking for Alibrandi (novel)|Looking for Alibrandi]]''}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[BILBY Award#Older Readers Award|Books I Love Best Yearly: Older Readers Award]] | years = 1996}}\n{{s-aft | after = ''[[The Hobbit]]''}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Michael Crichton}}\n{{Jurassic Park}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1990 American novels]]\n[[Category:1990 science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:Techno-thriller novels]]\n[[Category:Action novels]]\n[[Category:American biopunk novels]]\n[[Category:Novels about dinosaurs]]\n[[Category:Novels set in amusement parks]]\n[[Category:Novels set on islands]]\n[[Category:Novels set on fictional islands]]\n[[Category:Novels set in zoos]]\n[[Category:Eco-thriller novels]]\n[[Category:Jurassic Park novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Michael Crichton]]\n[[Category:American novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Alfred A. Knopf books]]\n[[Category:BILBY Award-winning works]]\n[[Category:Books with cover art by Chip Kidd]]\n[[Category:Science fiction novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Costa Rica]]\n", "text_old": "{{long plot|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox book\n| name          = Jurassic Park\n| translator    = \n| image         = Jurassicpark.jpg\n| border        = yes\n| caption       = First edition cover\n| author        = [[Michael Crichton]]\n| cover_artist  = [[Chip Kidd]]\n| country       = United States \n| language      = English\n| series        =\n| genre         = [[Science fiction]]\n| publisher     = [[Alfred A. Knopf]]\n| release_date  = November 20, 1990<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cocatalog.loc.gov/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?Search_Arg=Jurassic+Park+%2F+Michael+Crichton&Search_Code=TALL&PID=fRajfjITfjI0pkzSXZyc_NTa34d&SEQ=20160615102142&CNT=25&HIST=1|title=Copyright information for ''Jurassic Park''|publisher=[[United States Copyright Office]]|accessdate=June 15, 2016}}</ref>\n| media_type    = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]])\n| pages         = 448\n| isbn          = 0-394-58816-9\n| dewey= 813/.54 20\n| congress= PS3553.R48 J87 1990\n| oclc= 22511027\n| followed_by   = [[The Lost World (Crichton novel)|The Lost World]]\n}}\n'''''Jurassic Park''''' is a 1990 [[science fiction]] novel written by [[Michael Crichton]]. A [[cautionary tale]] about [[genetic engineering]], it presents the collapse of an [[amusement park]] showcasing [[Genetic engineering|genetically recreated]] [[dinosaur]]s to illustrate the mathematical concept of [[chaos theory]] and its real world implications. A sequel titled ''[[The Lost World (Crichton novel)|The Lost World]]'', also written by Crichton, was published in 1995. In 1997, both novels were re-published as a single book titled ''Michael Crichton's Jurassic World'', unrelated to the [[Jurassic World|film of the same name]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Crichton|first=Michael|title=Michael Crichton's Jurassic World|url=https://archive.org/details/michaelcrichtons00cric|url-access=registration|year=1997|publisher=[[Alfred A. Knopf|Knopf]]|ISBN=978-0375401077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://catalog.loc.gov/vwebv/search?searchArg=9780375401077&searchCode=GKEY%5E*&searchType=0&recCount=25&sk=en_US|title=Michael Crichton's Jurassic world (information)|publisher=[[Library of Congress]]|\naccessdate=2015-01-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/michael-crichtons-jurassic-world-michael-crichton/1120147558?ean=9780375401077|title=Michael Crichton's Jurassic World: Jurassic Park, The Lost World|publisher=[[Barnes & Noble]]|accessdate=2015-01-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 1993, [[Steven Spielberg]] adapted the book into the blockbuster film ''[[Jurassic Park (film)|Jurassic Park]].'' The book's sequel, ''The Lost World'', was also adapted by Spielberg into a [[The Lost World: Jurassic Park|film]] in 1997. A [[Jurassic Park III|third film]], directed by [[Joe Johnston]] and released in 2001, drew several elements, themes, and scenes from both books that were ultimately not utilized in either of the previous films, such as the aviary and boat scenes.\n\nThe novel began as a [[screenplay]] Crichton wrote in 1983, about a graduate student who recreates a dinosaur.<ref>{{Cite AV media | people = Crichton, Michael | title = Michael Crichton on the Jurassic Park Phenomenon | medium = DVD | publisher = Universal | date = 2001}}</ref> Eventually, given his reasoning that genetic research is expensive and \"there is no pressing need to create a dinosaur\", Crichton concluded that it would emerge from a \"desire to entertain\", leading to a [[Wildlife refuge|wildlife park]] of extinct animals.<ref>\"Return to Jurassic Park: Dawn of a New Era\", ''Jurassic Park'' Blu-ray (2011)</ref> Originally, the story was told from the point of view of a child, but Crichton changed it as everyone who read the draft felt it would be better if told by an adult.<ref>[http://www.michaelcrichton.net/books-jurassicpark-mcnotes.html Michael Crichton's notes on Jurassic Park]</ref>\n\n==Plot summary==\nIn 1989, a series of strange animal attacks occur in [[Costa Rica]] and on the nearby fictional island of [[Isla Nublar]],<ref>Means approximately \"Clouded Island\" or \"Obscured Island\" in Spanish.</ref> the story's main setting, one of which is a worker severely injured on a construction project on Isla Nublar, whose employers refuse to disclose any information about. One of the species is eventually identified as a ''[[Procompsognathus]]''. [[Paleontology|Paleontologist]] [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dr. Alan Grant|Alan Grant]] and his [[Paleobotany|paleobotanist]] graduate student, [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dr. Ellen Sattler|Ellie Sattler]], are contacted to confirm the identification, but are abruptly whisked away by billionaire [[List of Jurassic Park characters#John Hammond|John Hammond]]&nbsp;\u2014 founder and chief executive officer of International Genetic Technologies, or InGen&nbsp;\u2014 for a weekend visit to a \"biological preserve\" he has established on Isla Nublar.\n\nUpon arrival, the preserve is revealed to be Jurassic Park, a [[Amusement park|theme park]] showcasing [[Cloning#Artificial cloning of organisms|cloned]] dinosaurs. The animals have been recreated using [[Ancient DNA|damaged dinosaur DNA]] found in blood inside of gnats, ticks, and mosquitoes fossilized and preserved in [[amber]]. Gaps in the genetic code have been filled in with \"compatible\" [[Reptile|reptilian]], [[Bird|avian]] or [[amphibian]] [[DNA]]. To control the population, all specimens on the island are [[lysine]]-[[Auxotrophy|deficient]] and X-Ray sterilized females. Hammond proudly touts InGen's advances in [[genetic engineering]] and shows his guests through the island's vast array of automated systems.\n\n[[File:Curva del drag\u00f3n.png|thumb|left|Ian Malcolm created [[dragon curve]]s to simulate the actions that were to take place in the park.]]\n\nRecent incidents in the park have spooked Hammond's investors. To placate them, Hammond uses Grant and Sattler as fresh consultants. They stand in counterbalance to a famous mathematician and [[Chaos theory|chaos theorist]], [[Ian Malcolm (character)|Ian Malcolm]], and a lawyer representing the investors, [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Donald Gennaro|Donald Gennaro]], who are pessimistic about the park's prospects. Malcolm, having been consulted before the park's creation, is especially emphatic in his prediction that the park will collapse, as it is an unsustainable simple structure bluntly forced upon a [[complex system]] with too many unpredictable variables, such as an uncontrollable population, attempting to contain animals with no real equivalent to extant animals with no predictable behavior patterns, and an untested computer system that continually fails to monitor and feed the population.\n\nCountering Malcolm's dire predictions with youthful energy, Hammond groups the consultants with his grandchildren, [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Timothy Murphy|Tim]] and [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Alexis Murphy|Alexis \"Lex\" Murphy]]. While touring the park, Grant finds a ''[[Velociraptor]]'' eggshell, seemingly proving Malcolm's earlier assertion that the dinosaurs have somehow been breeding against the geneticists' design.\n\nMeanwhile, the disgruntled chief programmer of Jurassic Park's controlling software, [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dennis Nedry|Dennis Nedry]], attempts [[Industrial espionage|corporate espionage]] for [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dr. Lewis Dodgson|Lewis Dodgson]], a geneticist and agent of InGen's archrival, Biosyn. By activating a [[Backdoor (computing)|backdoor]] he wrote into the park's computer system, Nedry shuts down its security systems and steals frozen embryos for each of the park's fifteen species in an attempt to smuggle them to a contact waiting at an auxiliary dock at the eastern end of the park. However, during a sudden [[Tropical cyclone#Tropical storm|tropical storm]], he exits his vehicle to get his bearings and is killed by a ''[[Dilophosaurus]]''. Without Nedry to reactivate the park's security, the electrified fences remain off and all the dinosaurs escape. The park's adult ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]'' attacks the guests on tour, with a juvenile ''T. rex'' attacking and killing Ed Regis, the park's public relations manager. In the aftermath, Grant and the children become lost in the park. Malcolm is gravely injured during the incident, but is found by Gennaro and park game warden [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Robert Muldoon|Robert Muldoon]], spending the remainder of the novel slowly dying as {{ndash}} between lucid lectures and morphine-induced rants {{ndash}} he tries to help the others understand their predicament and survive.\n\nThe park's upper management&nbsp;\u2014 engineer and park supervisor [[List of Jurassic Park characters#John Raymond Arnold|John Arnold]], [[biotechnology|biotechnologist]] [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dr. Henry Wu|Henry Wu]], Muldoon, and Hammond&nbsp;\u2014 struggle to return power to the park, while the veterinarian, [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dr. Harding|Dr. Harding]], takes care of Malcolm. They manage to temporarily get the park largely back in order, restoring the computer system by shutting down and restarting the power and resetting the system. When trying to restore the park to working order, they fail to notice that the system has been running on auxiliary power since the restart; this power soon runs out, shutting the park down a second time. The park's intelligent and aggressive raptors escape their enclosure, and kill Wu and Arnold. Meanwhile, Grant and the children slowly make their way back to the Visitor Center by rafting down the jungle river, carrying news that several young raptors were on board the island's supply ship when it departed for the mainland. After the three return to the visitor's center, they are contacted by the others, who instruct Grant to switch on the park's generators. Tim is then able to reactivate the park's main power, allowing Gennaro to force the supply ship to return.\n\nGennaro orders that the island be destroyed, but Grant rejects his authority, claiming that they must first inspect the whole situation. Grant, Sattler, Muldoon, and Gennaro set out into the park to find the wild raptor nests and compare hatched eggs with the island's revised population tally, and return unscathed. Meanwhile, Hammond, taking a walk and contemplating building a new park improving on his previous mistakes, hears a ''T. rex'' roar and, startled, falls down a hill, where he is eaten by a pack of ''Procompsognathus''.\n\nWith regard to the dinosaurs' breeding, it eventually transpires that using frog DNA to fill gaps in the dinosaurs' genetic code enabled a measure of [[Sequential hermaphroditism|dichogamy]], in which some of the female animals changed into males in response to the same-sex environment. The computer tally failed to include newborn animals, having been programmed to stop counting once the assumed correct total number of animals had been found.\n\nThe survivors are rescued by the fictitious Costa Rican Air Force, where Grant reveals that the dinosaurs have been killing people. The Costa Rican Air Force then declare the island hazardous and unsafe, and proceed to raze the island with [[napalm]]. Survivors of the incident are indefinitely detained by the United States and Costa Rican governments at a hotel. Weeks later, Grant is visited by [[List of Jurassic Park characters#Dr. Martin \"Marty\" Gutierrez|Dr. Martin Guitierrez]], an American doctor who lives in Costa Rica. Guitierrez informs Grant that an unknown pack of animals has been migrating through the Costa Rican jungle, eating lysine-rich crops and chickens. He also informs Grant that none of them, with the possible exception of Tim and Lex, are going to leave any time soon.\n\n== Themes==\n{{Refimprove section|date=August 2018}}\n[[File:Tyrannosaurus skeletal diagram.jpg|thumb|1917 skeletal diagram of ''[[Tyrannosaurus]]'' published by [[Henry Fairfield Osborn]], which was the basis of the novel's cover]] \nJurassic Park critiques the dystopian potentialities of science. There are Christian undertones in the skepticism of Ian Malcolm, though Christian terminology and imagery is never used. Malcolm is the conscience that reminds John Hammond of the sacrilegious path that has been taken. The final condition of the park is epitomized by the word 'hell', which highlights the nature of Hammond's sacrilegious attempt.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://go.galegroup.com/ps/anonymous?id=GALE%7CH1100078863|title=Rediscovering the Island as Utopian Locus: Michael Crichton\u2019s Jurassic Park.|last=Gallardo-Terrano|first=Pedro|date=2000|via=Gale Academic OneFile|access-date=2018-08-02}}</ref>\n\nMichael Crichton's novel is another version of [[Mary Shelley]]'s ''[[Frankenstein]]'' tale where humanity creates without knowing. Henry Wu is unable to name the things that he creates, which alludes to Victor Frankenstein not knowing what to call his flawed imitation of God's creative powers. The immorality of these actions lead to human destruction, echoing Frankenstein.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=https://go.galegroup.com/ps/anonymous?id=GALE%7CH1100078866|title=Replicating a Dinosaur: Authenticity Run Amok in the Theme Parking in Michael Crichton\u2019s Jurassic Park and Julian Barnes\u2019s England, England.|last=Miracky|first=James|date=2004|via=Gale Academic OneFile|access-date=2018-08-02}}</ref>\n\nSimilar to how his other novels represent science and technology as both hazardous and life-changing, Michael Crichton's novel highlights the hypocrisy and superiority complex of the scientific community that inspired John Hammond to recreate dinosaurs and treat them as commodities, which only lead to catastrophe. The similar fears of atomic power from the Cold War are adapted by Michael Crichton onto the anxieties evoked by genetic manipulation.<ref>{{Cite encyclopedia|url=https://go.galegroup.com/ps/anonymous?id=GALE%7CCX3661700048|encyclopedia=Books to Film: Cinematic Adaptations of Literary Works |title=Jurassic Park |editor-last=Grant|editor-first=Barry Keith|volume=1|last=Geraghty|first=Lincoln|date=2018|via=Gale Academic OneFile|access-date=2018-08-02}}</ref>\n\n==Dinosaurs in novel==\n\n''The list is in alphabetical order''\n\n*[[Apatosaurus]]\n*[[Cearadactylus|Cearadactyl]]                                                                \n*[[Dilophosaurus]]\n*[[Euoplocephalus]]\n*[[Hadrosaurus]]\n*[[Hypsilophodon]]\n*[[Maiasaurus]]\n*[[Microceratus|Microceratops]]\n*[[Othnielia]]\n*[[Procompsognathus]]\n*[[Stegosaurus]]\n*[[Styracosaurus]]\n*[[Triceratops]]\n*[[Tyrannosaurus]]\n*[[Velociraptor]]\n\n== Reception ==\nThe book became a bestseller and Michael Crichton's signature novel. It also received largely favorable reviews by critics. In a review for ''[[The New York Times]]'', [[Christopher Lehmann-Haupt]] described it as \"a superior specimen of the [''Frankenstein''] myth\" and \"easily the best of Mr. Crichton's novels to date.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lehmann-Haupt|first1=Christopher|title=Books of The Times; Of Dinosaurs Returned And Fractals Fractured|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/15/books/books-of-the-times-of-dinosaurs-returned-and-fractals-fractured.html|accessdate=27 September 2015|work=[[New York Times]]|date=November 15, 1990}}</ref> Writing for ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'', [[Gene Lyons]] held that the book was \"hard to beat for sheer intellectual entertainment\" largely because it was \"[f]illed with diverting, up-to-date information in easily digestible form.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lyons|first1=Gene|title=Jurassic Park|url=http://www.ew.com/article/1990/11/16/jurassic-park|accessdate=27 September 2015|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=November 16, 1990}}</ref> Both Lyons' ''Entertainment Weekly'' piece and [[Andrew Ferguson]]'s review in the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', however, criticized Crichton's [[characterization]] as heavy-handed and his characters as cliched. Ferguson further complained about Ian Malcolm's \"dime-store philosophizing\" and predicted that the film adaptation of the book would be \"undoubtedly trashy.\" He conceded that the book's \"only real virtue\" was \"its genuinely interesting discussions of dinosaurs, DNA research, paleontology and chaos theory.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ferguson|first1=Andrew|title=The Thing From the Tar Pits : JURASSIC PARK By Michael Crichton (Alfred A. Knopf: $19.95; 413 pp.)|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-11-11/books/bk-5972_1_jurassic-park|accessdate=27 September 2015|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=November 11, 1990}}</ref>\n\nThe novel became even more famous following the release of the [[Jurassic Park (film)|1993 film adaptation]], which has grossed more than US$1 billion and spawned several sequels.<ref>[http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=jurassicpark.htm Jurassic Park (1993)]. Box Office Mojo (1993-09-24). Retrieved on 2013-09-17.</ref>\n\nIn 1996 it was awarded the Secondary [[BILBY Award]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbcaqld.org/uploads/2/6/2/2/26224528/previous_bilby_to_2014.pdf |title=Previous Winners of the BILBY Awards: 1990 \u2013 96 |website=www.cbcaqld.org |publisher=The Children's Book Council of Australia Queensland Branch |access-date=4 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119061148/http://www.cbcaqld.org/uploads/2/6/2/2/26224528/previous_bilby_to_2014.pdf |archive-date=19 November 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|United States|Novels|1990s|Dinosaurs|Speculative fiction|}}\n*''[[The Cursed Earth (Judge Dredd story)|The Cursed Earth]]'', a [[Judge Dredd]] story line by [[Pat Mills]] in ''[[2000 AD (comics)|2000 AD]]'' from 1978 that introduces the idea of a dinosaur theme park, with dinosaurs cloned from DNA\n*''[[Carnosaur (novel)|Carnosaur]]'', a 1984 novel with similar themes\n*''[[Westworld (film)|Westworld]]'', Crichton's earlier 1973 film also about a malfunctioning theme park\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{Cite book |title=The Science of Jurassic Park and The Lost World. Or How to Build a Dinosaur |first=Rob |last=DeSalle |lastauthoramp=yes |first2=David |last2=Lindley |publisher=BasicBooks |location=New York |year=1997 |isbn=0-465-07379-4 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/scienceofjurassi00desa }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote|Jurassic Park (novel)}}  \n*[http://sites.google.com/site/HZTomassi/isla-nublar-map ''Isla Nublar novel map'']\n*{{Official website|http://www.jurassicpark.com}}\n* {{isfdb title|id=1678|title=Jurassic Park}}\n*[http://www.michaelcrichton.com/books-jurassicpark.html ''Jurassic Park''] at the official Michael Crichton website\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{s-bef | before = ''[[Looking for Alibrandi (novel)|Looking for Alibrandi]]''}}\n{{s-ttl | title = [[BILBY Award#Older Readers Award|Books I Love Best Yearly: Older Readers Award]] | years = 1996}}\n{{s-aft | after = ''[[The Hobbit]]''}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Michael Crichton}}\n{{Jurassic Park}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1990 American novels]]\n[[Category:1990 science fiction novels]]\n[[Category:Techno-thriller novels]]\n[[Category:Action novels]]\n[[Category:American biopunk novels]]\n[[Category:Novels about dinosaurs]]\n[[Category:Novels set in amusement parks]]\n[[Category:Novels set on islands]]\n[[Category:Novels set on fictional islands]]\n[[Category:Novels set in zoos]]\n[[Category:Eco-thriller novels]]\n[[Category:Jurassic Park novels]]\n[[Category:Novels by Michael Crichton]]\n[[Category:American novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Alfred A. Knopf books]]\n[[Category:BILBY Award-winning works]]\n[[Category:Books with cover art by Chip Kidd]]\n[[Category:Science fiction novels adapted into films]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Costa Rica]]\n", "name_user": "ConradVdE", "label": "safe", "comment": "A little bit!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jurassic_Park_(novel)"}
{"title_page": "Leave a Light On (Grey's Anatomy)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE: Leave a Light On (''Grey's Anatomy'')}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n|title = Leave a Light On\n|series = [[Grey's Anatomy]]\n|image =\n|image_size = 250px\n|caption = Meredith reads the letter that Alex sent her.\n|season = 16\n|episode = 16\n|length = 43 minutes\n|airdate = {{start date|2020|3|05}}\n|music = \n|writer = [[Elisabeth Finch]]\n|director = [[Debbie Allen]]\n|guests = * [[Jason George]] as Dr. Ben Warren\n*BJ Tanner as William George Bailey Jones\n| season_article = Grey's Anatomy (season 16)\n| episode_list = List of Grey's Anatomy episodes\n|prev = Snowblind\n|next = Life on Mars?\n}}\n\n'''\"Leave a Light On\"''' is the sixteenth episode of the [[Grey's Anatomy (season 16)|sixteenth season]] of the American [[medical drama]]  television series ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'' and the 358th episode  overall, which aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on March 5, 2020. The episode was written by [[Elizabeth Finch]] and directed by [[Debbie Allen]]. It marked the final appearance of [[Justin Chambers]] as [[Alex Karev]].\n\nOn January 10, 2020, it was announced that Chambers left the series, having already made his last physical appearance in the November 14, 2019 episode \"[[Grey's Anatomy (season 16)#ep350|My Shot]]\", the 350th episode revolving around the trial for Meredith's medical license.<ref name=\"last\">{{Cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/01/justin-chambers-leaving-greys-anatomy-exit-15-years-16-seasons-alex-karev-abc-1202826876/|title=Justin Chambers Leaving Grey\u2019s Anatomy After 15 Years|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=January 10, 2020|access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref> Showrunner [[Krista Vernoff]] discussed the challenge in writing Alex off without Chambers physically being there, having left the show suddenly. Vernoff said, \"It was a very careful threading of a needle, where we are giving a little bit of information and pain to Jo,\" she said, adding, \"We\u2019re, episode by episode, illuminating the story of where Alex is. And it takes us quite a few more episodes to get there and to give the audience clarity.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2020/03/05/greys-anatomy-alex-izzie-season-16-interview/|title=Grey's Boss Speaks Out in Wake of Shocking Alex Farewell Episode|work=TVLine|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe episode resolves several storylines, including the disappearance of Alex Karev after seven episodes, the disappearance of [[Izzie Stevens]] ([[Katherine Heigl]]) over ten years ago and [[Miranda Bailey]] ([[Chandra Wilson]]) choosing to take in a homeless teenager. Stevens was last seen in the episode, \"[[I Like You So Much Better When You're Naked (Grey's Anatomy)|I Like You So Much Better When You're Naked]]\" in 2010, and appears for the first time again in archive footage, as details of her current situation are revealed, along with Chambers' character. Chambers returns for the episode in voice-over, as the episode takes a retrospective approach, as he narrates much of what has happened to him since.\n\nThe episode's original broadcast was watched by 6.30 million viewers and registered the show's best ratings in six weeks, since the mid-season premiere. It received a polarizing response from fans and critics alike, who were divided on the show's handling of Alex's exit, but many largely felt it made sense given the circumstances of Chambers' abrupt departure.\n\n==Plot==\nThe episode opens with archive footage of [[Richard Webber]] ([[James Pickens Jr.]])'s speech to the original interns in the pilot episode. It features [[Meredith Grey]] ([[Ellen Pompeo]]), [[Cristina Yang]] ([[Sandra Oh]]), [[Alex Karev]] ([[Justin Chambers]]), [[Izzie Stevens]] ([[Katherine Heigl]]) and [[George O'Malley]] ([[T. R. Knight]]). Meredith Grey then provides her signature episodic [[voice-over]], telling a \"lame joke\" about a patient saying, \"Hey doc, it hurts when I go like this\" to which the doctor responds, \"Well don't go like this\" and says that while lame, \"it is nonetheless true that as human beings, we cannot help but want to follow our own instincts, guts and primal urges no matter how much it hurts\". A sequence follows, showing [[Jo Karev]] ([[Camilla Luddington]]), [[Miranda Bailey]] ([[Chandra Wilson]]) and Meredith Grey (Pompeo) receiving letters from Alex Karev (Chambers). As the three begin reading the letters, Alex (Chambers) provides voice-over of his written letters, declaring that he's not leaving, but has already left \u2015 he is gone.\n\nThe episode then provides a retrospective of landmark storylines in the series integral to Alex's whole journey, from his arrogant, smart-mouth days in the early seasons to his maturation as a successful pediatrics surgeon, devoted friend and partner to Izzie and later Jo. It also shows flashbacks of his relationship with Izzie, her cancer battle and their wedding. It also shows flashbacks of the original five interns' friendship and Meredith's growing friendship with Alex throughout all sixteen seasons. Alex explains to Meredith that the form of a letter was not the way he wanted to say goodbye. He tells Meredith that she was always the one to set him straight, and it provides flashbacks to Alex having to face up to his problems, rather than run away. Alex then says he does not want to be set straight, or for Meredith to say the right thing, because the one right thing isn't in Seattle. Alex then reveals he is with Izzie (Katherine Heigl).\n\nFollowing this revelation, flashbacks of Alex and Izzie's early relationship is shown. As this goes on, Alex reveals he contacted her during Meredith's trial to maintain her medical license for a recommendation letter. He admits the trial gave him an excuse to finally contact Izzie, to know if she was alive and well. After brief exchange on the phone, Alex says he heard little voices in the background and asked if Izzie had kids and after a silence, she revealed that she did. And it turns out they are his children.\n\n[[File:Alex16x08final.png|thumb|225px|right|[[Alex Karev]]'s ([[Justin Chambers]]) last physical appearance includes this scene in the 350th episode \"[[Grey's Anatomy (season 16)#ep350|My Shot]]\".<ref name=\"last\" />]]\n\nAlex reveals Izzie was single, wanted kids and because the cancer nuked her eggs, she could not have biological children but she had their embryos. Flashbacks from the fifth season show Alex and Izzie's scenes revolving around the embryos. Alex explains he was too freaked out to care what she did with them so he signed papers off so that she could do whatever she wanted with them, as a flashback to Alex's worries of her surviving cancer is shown. He says he is aware he should have told Jo and Meredith, but instead of telling them, he got through the trial and went to see his children. His children \u2015 twins named Alexis and Eli \u2015 are described as \"hilarious and stubborn\" like Izzie, Alexis having Izzie's eyes and Eli's smile being crooked like his, that the kids want to be doctors and they bake like Izzie, and that he lives on a farm in the middle of no-where in Kansas. He also reveals Izzie works as a surgical oncologist and has made so much progress. Alex again says she could come up and bring him back to Seattle, but he hopes she does not do that and that he is finally where he should be, and that he has never had that before. Alex says he hopes when she is ready and not mad that she can come up and meet his children.\n\nFlashbacks also show Jo and Alex's relationship, as well as Jo's own journey briefly, as Jo reads her letter from him. Alex details how deeply sorry he is, but that he is in love with Izzie as well. Alex admits the letter is the worst thing he is done, and that Jo has earned so much better, but also mentions the children he has with her. Alex tells Jo he felt he and Izzie had unfinished business and that they spoke as if no time had passed, that they were frozen in time. Alex says he needs to give the children the life he and Jo never had. Alex reveals he went to a lawyer, signed divorce papers and left her his shares at Grey Sloan.\n\nWebber, at an AA meeting, relates Alex's situation with Jo and Izzie to Ellis and Adele, and that he wishes he got to see [[Maggie Pierce]] ([[Kelly McCreary]]) grow up, so he cannot be mad at him no matter how hard he wants to be, although admits his bitterness that he could not say goodbye simply as a teacher. It finally shows another sequence of Izzie and Alex's relationship, this time through dialogue of Izzie's declarations of love and finally shows the resemblance of Izzie's children to her.\n\nBailey talks to Ben ([[Jason George]]) about Joey, and relates the situation to Alex's upbringing. They decide to keep caring for him. Meanwhile, Jo swallows her emotions and decides to continue to work casually after reading the letter as Link ([[Chris Carmack]]) calls her his hero. Jo responds, \"Mine too\". The episode ends with Meredith talking to her daughter, Zola (Aniela Gumbs) and preparing to tell her that Uncle Alex is gone, with a voice-over of Meredith to say there really is no good way to say goodbye.\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Katherine Heigl LF adjust.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Katherine Heigl]]'s long-departed character was a source of critical analysis, as Chambers' character's decision to leave his wife for her drew many wide ranging responses.]]\nThe episode was written by [[Elisabeth Finch]] and directed by [[Debbie Allen]]. Several former characters appear in the episode through archive footage such as [[Izzie Stevens]] ([[Katherine Heigl]]), Denny Duquette (Jeffrey Dean Morgan), [[George O'Malley]] ([[T. R. Knight]]), [[Cristina Yang]] ([[Sandra Oh]]), [[Derek Shepherd]] ([[Patrick Dempsey]]), Shane Ross ([[Gaius Charles]]), [[Stephanie Edwards (Grey's Anatomy)|Stephanie Edwards]] ([[Jerrika Hinton]]), [[Arizona Robbins]] ([[Jessica Capshaw]]), Helen Karev ([[Lindsay Wagner]]) and Jimmy Evans ([[James Remar]]). The only current main cast members that appeared in new scenes were [[Meredith Grey]] ([[Ellen Pompeo]]), [[Miranda Bailey]] ([[Chandra Wilson]]), [[Richard Webber]] ([[James Pickens Jr.]]), Jo Karev ([[Camilla Luddington]]) and Atticus \"Link\" Lincoln ([[Chris Carmack]]).\n\nThe episode re-visits [[Katherine Heigl]]'s character, [[Izzie Stevens]], for the first time in over ten years. Alex and Izzie's storyline was left unresolved in the [[Grey's Anatomy (season 6)|sixth season]], after Heigl departed the series abruptly during her maternity leave. In a [[I Like You So Much Better When You're Naked (Grey's Anatomy)|January 2010 episode]], Stevens leaves after she is unable to repair things with Alex. [[Joan Rater]], the episode's writer, explained that Stevens getting better propelled Karev to let her go.<ref name=Matter>{{cite web|url=http://www.greyswriters.com/2010/01/joan-rater-on-i-like-you-so-much-better-when-youre-naked.html |title=Joan Rater on \"I Like You So Much Better When You're Naked\"... |publisher=ABC |work=Grey Matter |date=January 21, 2010 |access-date=June 26, 2012 |author=Rater, Joan |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513155822/http://www.greyswriters.com/2010/01/joan-rater-on-i-like-you-so-much-better-when-youre-naked.html |archive-date=May 13, 2013 |df= }}</ref> Izzie's absence after this was intended to be temporary, with the character returning in the season's final five episodes. However, Heigl did not show up for filming on March 1, 2010 for the season's twentieth episode. Heigl's three month family leave in Utah propelled her to quit the show entirely, feeling she needed more time to bond with her adoptive daughter. She explained, \"So before I was due back, I spoke again to [[Shonda Rhimes|Shonda]] about wanting to leave. Then I waited at home until I was given the formal okay that I was off the show. The rumors that I refused to return were totally untrue.\" While Heigl felt the departure was \u201camicable\u201d, despite the shock and feeling that something could have worked out, Heigl felt Izzie returning only to leave again after already having done so twice would \"feel a little manipulative\" and she felt that she had not created a bond with her adoptive daughter yet that made her feel like she needed her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/03/24/katherine-heigl-greys-anatomy-official-ew/|title=This week's cover (exclusive!): Katherine Heigl confirms 'Grey's Anatomy' departure|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=March 24, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc]]|accessdate=April 5, 2010}}</ref> \n\nIn August 2010, Rhimes stated that she did not feel Alex and Izzie's arc had fully concluded, and hoped to give proper closure to their relationship in the [[Grey's Anatomy (season 7)|seventh season]].<ref name=\"Closure\">{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/08/22/greys-anatomy-closure-for-alex-izzie/|title='Grey's Anatomy' Exclusive: Closure is coming for Alex/Izzie fans |first=Michael|last=Ausiello|authorlink=Michael Ausiello |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc]]|date=August 22, 2010|accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref> She later confirmed that she had intended to kill off Izzie off-screen, but opted against this a day later as she felt that it would destroy Alex, rather than give him closure. Instead, she concluded: \"I'm open to seeing Izzie again. So if she [Katherine] were to come back, we would be thrilled to [wrap up her story]. But if she doesn't, we'll just move on.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/10/29/greys-anatomy-spoiler-alex-izzie/|title=Exclusive: 'Grey's Anatomy' boss vetoes controversial Alex/Izzie plot|first=Michael|last=Ausiello|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=October 29, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc]]|accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref> While Heigl originally considered the idea of her returning bleak and considered the chapter closed,<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1649167/katherine-heigl-on-greys-anatomy-that-chapter-closed.jhtml Katherine Heigl On 'Grey's Anatomy': 'That Chapter Is Closed']</ref> she later regretted it and expressed enthusiasm on returning in January 2012<ref name=kheiglreturn>{{cite web|title='Grey's Anatomy': Katherine Heigl wants to return|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/01/19/greys-anatomy-katherine-heigl-wants-to-return/|work=Inside TV|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=January 22, 2012}}</ref> but Rhimes, two months after, said that she was on a different track that they were not interested in changing.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/03/greys-anatomy-katherine-heigl-not-returning-plus-finale-scoop-from-shonda-rhimes.html |title='Grey's Anatomy': Katherine Heigl not returning, plus finale scoop from Shonda Rhimes |access-date=2012-03-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010041120/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/03/greys-anatomy-katherine-heigl-not-returning-plus-finale-scoop-from-shonda-rhimes.html |archive-date=2013-10-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Four months after, Rhimes cast [[Camilla Luddington]] as Jo Wilson,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2012/07/19/greys-anatomy-season-9-camilla-luddington/|title='Kate Middleton' Joins Grey's Anatomy Season 9|last=Mitovich|first=Matt Webb|work=Wetpaint|date=July 19, 2012|accessdate=December 4, 2012}}</ref> who became the new love interest for Chambers' character. Three years later, Rhimes said she has completely moved on from the idea of Izzie coming back, \"I\u2019m done with that story. I\u2019ve turned that idea over in my mind a thousand times and thought about how it would go. And I don\u2019t think so.\"<ref>[http://tvline.com/2015/08/05/greys-anatomy-izzie-season-12-katherine-heigl-returning/ Grey's Anatomy Boss Shonda Rhimes Crushes My Katherine Heigl Comeback Dream: 'I'm Done With That Story'] TV Line, Retrieved August 6, 2015</ref> \n\n{{quote box|align=left|width=30em|quote=Some fans were upset, particularly the Jolex shippers, that [Alex left Jo to be with Izzie] \u2014 and I understand why. But I would fight real hard anyone who tried to tell me that fans would not have been equally or more upset if I had killed Alex Karev off camera.\u201d|source= \u2014Vernoff on the decision to reunite Alex with Izzie after Chambers' abrupt exit.<ref name=KriVern>{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2020/04/09/greys-anatomy-alex-death-storyline-justin-chambers/|last=Ausiello |first=Michael |title=Grey's Anatomy Boss Never Considered Killing Off Alex Karev \u2014 Here's Why|work=TVLine|date=April 9, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\nAfter the season sixteen finale, showrunner [[Krista Vernoff]] elaborated on the decision to choose Alex's send-off. \u201cAt the end of the day, there were three choices,\u201d she explained to [[TVLine]]. \u201cKill Alex off camera; have Alex be alive and in Seattle \u2014 and still married to Jo \u2014 and we just never see him; or [reunite him] with Izzie.\u201d She felt that killing Alex would have been \u201ccruel to everyone \u2014 particularly Meredith and Jo,\u201d Alex's best friend and wife, respectively. \u201cThere was no way to not put those characters through gut-wrenching, ongoing grief if we had killed Alex off camera.\u201d She also felt the second option would have done a disservice to [[Camilla Luddington]] who plays Chambers' TV wife. \u201cIt wasn\u2019t fair to her to keep her married to a character who was off screen,\u201d Vernoff says. \u201cIt would absolutely eliminate [the chance for her to play] so many colors that she is so good at playing\u201d and finally evaluated as a result that it \u201c...wasn\u2019t even a debate in the writers room,\u201d adding that giving Alex a happy ending with Izzie \u201cwas so clearly the right course.\u201d<ref name=KriVern/>\n\n==Reception==\n===Ratings===\n\"Leave a Light On\" was originally broadcast on March 5, 2020 in the United States on the [[American Broadcasting Company]] (ABC). The episode was watched by a total of 6.30 million viewers, rising up from the previous episode's 6 million. In the key 18-49 demographic, the episode scored a 1.3/7 [[Nielsen ratings|rating]]/share, up two tenths from the previous episode and the best since the mid-season premiere \"[[Grey's Anatomy (season 16)#ep352|Help Me Through the Night]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pucci |first1=Douglas |title=Thursday Final Ratings: NBA on TNT Tops the 10 p.m. Hour in Adults 18-49, 18-34 and Key Male Demos |url=https://programminginsider.com/thursday-final-ratings-nba-on-tnt-tops-the-10-p-m-hour-in-adults-18-49-18-34-and-key-male-demos/ |website=Programming Insider |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Reviews===\n[[File:Justin Cambers 2014 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Justin Chambers]] made his final appearance as a series regular after fifteen years on the show.]]\n\"Leave the Light On\" received a polarizing response from television critics and fans alike.\n\n''[[USA Today]]'' noted the \"polarizing\" response for fans, and on discussing Alex's whole journey said, \"He was there for us as we watched a succession of doctors depart the series. Karev was a constant; Where else would he go? After a rough upbringing, he craved stability \u2013 making the timing of his exit all the more perplexing. Then again: Maybe Izzie was that stability all along.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/03/05/greys-anatomy-how-alex-karev-justin-chambers-said-goodbye/4955659002/|title=Ellen Pompeo calls Alex Karev's 'Grey's Anatomy' goodbye 'the best possible storyline'|work=USA Today|last=Oliver|first=David|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]'' noted \"fan favorite\" Alex's ending's similarities to that of [[ER (TV series)|ER]]'s [[Doug Ross|Doug]] and [[Carol Hathaway|Carol]], played by [[George Clooney]] and [[Julianna Margulies]] respectively, \"who also left the show at different times\" and there \"Carol also had given birth to the couple\u2019s twins unbeknownst to Doug, with the couple eventually reuniting to live happily ever after with their kids\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/greys-anatomyl-alex-karev-farewell-surprise-twist-wrap-story-izzie-shocker-showrunner-krista-vernoff-lvideo-1202875717/|title=\u2018Grey\u2019s Anatomy\u2019 Wraps Alex Karev\u2019s Story With Surprise Twist; Krista Vernoff Says: \u201cWe Will Miss Him Terribly\u201d|work=Deadline|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a three-out-of-five-star review, Maggie Fremont for ''[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]'' expressed disappointment that the \"clip show\" exit showed no physical reunion between Izzie and Alex. Then Fremont elaborated, \"It just felt like Alex dying, although tragic, would\u2019ve been the only way to write the character off that made sense after everything he went through\" and that \"Alex Karev we\u2019ve watched for \u2014 holy hell, almost two decades if we\u2019re rounding up \u2014 wouldn\u2019t do that\" although admitted the exit \"almost works\", as Alex chooses to not miss a second with his children and to be a great dad, but that \"Alex not being mad for one single second about the fact that Izzie had secret kids five years ago and never told him\" made \"less sense\". Fremont also noted that Alex could have asked Jo to move to Kansas to help him be there for his children so that it was obviously \"ALSO about the women he loves\". She discussed the dramatic nature of Richard's speech saying, \"I\u2019m sorry, Richard\u2019s speech is lovely and all, but he\u2019s acting like he can\u2019t just go to Kansas and see the guy. Richard thrives on that drama, you guys. Fremont also commented on Jo's reaction saying, \"Poor Jo! And poor me for having to sympathize with a character I can\u2019t stand, you know? Jo\u2019s letter truly sucks\", with both commenting on the impersonal nature of the letter.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/greys-anatomy-recap-season-16-episode-16-leave-a-light-on.html|title=Grey\u2019s Anatomy Recap: A Dear Jo Letter|work=Vulture|last=Fremont|first=Maggie|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAshley Bissette Sumerel for ''Telltale-TV'' gave a moderately positive 3.5 out of 5 star review of the episode. She complimented how the writers worked with the circumstances of Chambers' abrupt departure feeling \"[his] sudden exit meant the writers needed to change course and figure out the best way to write out his character, and I believe they did that, with a few exceptions\" and said, I\u2019d actually told a few people that there was one ending for Alex that I felt like I\u2019d be able to accept, and low and behold, this is it. The timing is terrible considering his relationship with Jo, but again, I think in this case, we do have to consider the circumstances.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telltaletv.com/2020/03/greys-anatomy-review-leave-a-light-on-season-16-episode-16/|title=Grey\u2019s Anatomy Review: Leave a Light On (Season 16 Episode 16)|work=Telltale TV|last=Bisette Sumerel|first=Ashley|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSonya Field for ''Hypable'' criticized the \"unrealistic\" storyline, feeling that it underscored Jo and Alex's story \"because he was so ready to leave her\". She opined that the Izzie/Alex flashbacks \"bothered\" her. She finished saying, \"It worries me that this might mean the whole issue will largely be swept under the rug after this episode. It\u2019s already upsetting to see how Alex was able to walk away from Jo so quickly, and I hope they at least handle things differently on Jo\u2019s end.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hypable.com/greys-anatomy-season-16-episode-16-alex-karev-written-off-the-show/|title=\u2018Grey\u2019s Anatomy\u2019 season 16, episode 16 review: Alex Karev says goodbye|work=Hypable|last=Field|first=Sonya|date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nJasmine Blu for ''TV Fanatic'' gave a mostly negative response to the episode. They noted Meredith as being \"self-absorbed\" saying, \"Meredith has been so far removed from the missing Alex storyline, and before that, she hasn't so much as visited him at Pac-North. Alex's final season had a startling lack of Merlex, so the final goodbye was even bitterer\", while also acknowledging how no goodbye, short of death, would satisfy everyone. The reviewer criticized Alex's development in the episode saying, \"Alex, who has spent years resenting people for abandoning him turned around and left those he loves. It's a struggle to wrap one's head around it.\" Blu also criticized Alex for seemingly using his sick mother as an alibi, and noted it as being uncharacteristic of the \"straight-shooter\" and \"guy who tells it like it is whether you like it or not\" that fans know him by. The reviewer also noted that it was \"already a disservice that it took so long for anyone to pay attention to his absence\" and that \"Jo probably should've contacted his mother ages ago\". Blu also criticized the storyline for how it will service Jo as a tragedy later, calling \"Woe is Joe hours [...] irritating\" and that \"so much of Alex's storylines in the last few seasons have been playing second to Jo.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvfanatic.com/2020/03/when-good-characters-cant-break-away-from-being-love-interests-w/|title=Grey's Anatomy Season 16 Episode 16 Review: Leave a Light On|work=TVFanatic|last=Blu|first=Jasmine|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Grey's Anatomy episodes|16}}\n\n[[Category:Grey's Anatomy (season 16) episodes]]\n[[Category:2020 American television episodes]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE: Leave a Light On (''Grey's Anatomy'')}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n|title = Leave a Light On\n|series = [[Grey's Anatomy]]\n|image =\n|image_size = 250px\n|caption = Meredith reads the letter that Alex sent her.\n|season = 16\n|episode = 16\n|length = 43 minutes\n|airdate = {{start date|2020|3|05}}\n|music = \n|writer = [[Elisabeth Finch]]\n|director = [[Debbie Allen]]\n|guests = * [[Jason George]] as Dr. Ben Warren\n*BJ Tanner as William George Bailey Jones\n| season_article = Grey's Anatomy (season 16)\n| episode_list = List of Grey's Anatomy episodes\n|prev = Snowblind\n|next = Life on Mars?\n}}\n\n'''\"Leave a Light On\"''' is the sixteenth episode of the [[Grey's Anatomy (season 16)|sixteenth season]] of the American [[medical drama]]  television series ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'' and the 358th episode  overall, which aired on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on March 5, 2020. The episode was written by [[Elizabeth Finch]] and directed by [[Debbie Allen]]. It marked the final appearance of [[Justin Chambers]] as [[Alex Karev]].\n\nOn January 10, 2020, it was announced that Chambers left the series, having already made his last physical appearance in the November 14, 2019 episode \"[[Grey's Anatomy (season 16)#ep350|My Shot]]\", the 350th episode revolving around the trial for Meredith's medical license.<ref name=\"last\">{{Cite web|url= https://deadline.com/2020/01/justin-chambers-leaving-greys-anatomy-exit-15-years-16-seasons-alex-karev-abc-1202826876/|title=Justin Chambers Leaving Grey\u2019s Anatomy After 15 Years|work=Deadline Hollywood|date=January 10, 2020|access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref> Showrunner [[Krista Vernoff]] discussed the challenge in writing Alex off without Chambers physically being there, having left the show suddenly. Vernoff said, \"It was a very careful threading of a needle, where we are giving a little bit of information and pain to Jo,\" she said, adding, \"We\u2019re, episode by episode, illuminating the story of where Alex is. And it takes us quite a few more episodes to get there and to give the audience clarity.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2020/03/05/greys-anatomy-alex-izzie-season-16-interview/|title=Grey's Boss Speaks Out in Wake of Shocking Alex Farewell Episode|work=TVLine|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe episode resolves several storylines, including the disappearance of Alex Karev after seven episodes, the disappearance of [[Izzie Stevens]] ([[Katherine Heigl]]) over ten years ago and [[Miranda Bailey]] ([[Chandra Wilson]]) choosing to take in a homeless teenager. Stevens was last seen in the episode, \"[[I Like You So Much Better When You're Naked (Grey's Anatomy)|I Like You So Much Better When You're Naked]]\" in 2010, and appears for the first time again in archive footage, as details of her current situation are revealed, along with Chambers' character. Chambers returns for the episode in voice-over, as the episode takes a retrospective approach, as he narrates much of what has happened to him since.\n\nThe episode's original broadcast was watched by 6.30 million viewers and registered the show's best ratings in six weeks, since the mid-season premiere. It received a polarizing response from fans and critics alike, who were divided on the show's handling of Alex's exit, but many largely felt it made sense given the circumstances of Chambers' abrupt departure.\n\n==Plot==\nThe episode opens with archive footage of [[Richard Webber]] ([[James Pickens Jr.]])'s speech to the original interns in the pilot episode. It features [[Meredith Grey]] ([[Ellen Pompeo]]), [[Cristina Yang]] ([[Sandra Oh]]), [[Alex Karev]] ([[Justin Chambers]]), [[Izzie Stevens]] ([[Katherine Heigl]]) and [[George O'Malley]] ([[T. R. Knight]]). Meredith Grey then provides her signature episodic [[voice-over]], telling a \"lame joke\" about a patient saying, \"Hey doc, it hurts when I go like this\" to which the doctor responds, \"Well don't go like this\" and says that while lame, \"it is nonetheless true that as human beings, we cannot help but want to follow our own instincts, guts and primal urges no matter how much it hurts\". A sequence follows, showing [[Jo Karev]] ([[Camilla Luddington]]), [[Miranda Bailey]] ([[Chandra Wilson]]) and Meredith Grey (Pompeo) receiving letters from Alex Karev (Chambers). As the three begin reading the letters, Alex (Chambers) provides voice-over of his written letters, declaring that he's not leaving, but has already left \u2015 he is gone.\n\nThe episode then provides a retrospective of landmark storylines in the series integral to Alex's whole journey, from his arrogant, smart-mouth days in the early seasons to his maturation as a successful pediatrics surgeon, devoted friend and partner to Izzie and later Jo. It also shows flashbacks of his relationship with Izzie, her cancer battle and their wedding. It also shows flashbacks of the original five interns' friendship and Meredith's growing friendship with Alex throughout all sixteen seasons. Alex explains to Meredith that the form of a letter was not the way he wanted to say goodbye. He tells Meredith that she was always the one to set him straight, and it provides flashbacks to Alex having to face up to his problems, rather than run away. Alex then says he does not want to be set straight, or for Meredith to say the right thing, because the one right thing isn't in Seattle. Alex then reveals he is with Izzie (Katherine Heigl).\n\nFollowing this revelation, flashbacks of Alex and Izzie's early relationship is shown. As this goes on, Alex reveals he contacted her during Meredith's trial to maintain her medical license for a recommendation letter. He admits the trial gave him an excuse to finally contact Izzie, to know if she was alive and well. After brief exchange on the phone, Alex says he heard little voices in the background and asked if Izzie had kids and after a silence, she revealed that she did. And it turns out they are his children.\n\n[[File:Alex16x08final.png|thumb|225px|right|[[Alex Karev]]'s ([[Justin Chambers]]) last physical appearance includes this scene in the 350th episode \"[[Grey's Anatomy (season 16)#ep350|My Shot]]\".<ref name=\"last\" />]]\n\nAlex reveals Izzie was single, wanted kids and because the cancer nuked her eggs, she could not have biological children but she had their embryos. Flashbacks from the fifth season show Alex and Izzie's scenes revolving around the embryos. Alex explains he was too freaked out to care what she did with them so he signed papers off so that she could do whatever she wanted with them, as a flashback to Alex's worries of her surviving cancer is shown. He says he is aware he should have told Jo and Meredith, but instead of telling them, he got through the trial and went to see his children. His children \u2015 twins named Alexis and Eli \u2015 are described as \"hilarious and stubborn\" like Izzie, Alexis having Izzie's eyes and Eli's smile being crooked like his, that the kids want to be doctors and they bake like Izzie, and that he lives on a farm in the middle of no-where in Kansas. He also reveals Izzie works as a surgical oncologist and has made so much progress. Alex again says she could come up and bring him back to Seattle, but he hopes she does not do that and that he is finally where he should be, and that he has never had that before. Alex says he hopes when she is ready and not mad that she can come up and meet his children.\n\nFlashbacks also show Jo and Alex's relationship, as well as Jo's own journey briefly, as Jo reads her letter from him. Alex details how deeply sorry he is, but that he is in love with Izzie as well. Alex admits the letter is the worst thing he is done, and that Jo has earned so much better, but also mentions the children he has with her. Alex tells Jo he felt he and Izzie had unfinished business and that they spoke as if no time had passed, that they were frozen in time. Alex says he needs to give the children the life he and Jo never had. Alex reveals he went to a lawyer, signed divorce papers and left her his shares at Grey Sloan.\n\nWebber, at an AA meeting, relates Alex's situation with Jo and Izzie to Ellis and Adele, and that he wishes he got to see [[Maggie Pierce]] ([[Kelly McCreary]]) grow up, so he cannot be mad at him no matter how hard he wants to be, although admits his bitterness that he could not say goodbye simply as a teacher. It finally shows another sequence of Izzie and Alex's relationship, this time through dialogue of Izzie's declarations of love and finally shows the resemblance of Izzie's children to her.\n\nBailey talks to Ben ([[Jason George]]) about Joey, and relates the situation to Alex's upbringing. They decide to keep caring for him. Meanwhile, Jo swallows her emotions and decides to continue to work casually after reading the letter as Link ([[Chris Carmack]]) calls her his hero. Jo responds, \"Mine too\". The episode ends with Meredith talking to her daughter, Zola (Aniela Gumbs) and preparing to tell her that Uncle Alex is gone, with a voice-over of Meredith to say there really is no good way to say goodbye.\n\n==Production==\n[[File:Katherine Heigl LF adjust.jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Katherine Heigl]]'s long-departed character was a source of critical analysis, as Chambers' character's decision to leave his wife for her drew many wide ranging responses.]]\nThe episode was written by [[Elisabeth Finch]] and directed by [[Debbie Allen]]. Several former characters appear in the episode through archive footage such as [[Izzie Stevens]] ([[Katherine Heigl]]), Denny Duquette (Jeffrey Dean Morgan), [[George O'Malley]] ([[T. R. Knight]]), [[Cristina Yang]] ([[Sandra Oh]]), [[Derek Shepherd]] ([[Patrick Dempsey]]), Shane Ross ([[Gaius Charles]]), [[Stephanie Edwards (Grey's Anatomy)|Stephanie Edwards]] ([[Jerrika Hinton]]), [[Arizona Robbins]] ([[Jessica Capshaw]]), Helen Karev ([[Lindsay Wagner]]) and Jimmy Evans ([[James Remar]]). The only current main cast members that appeared in new scenes were [[Meredith Grey]] ([[Ellen Pompeo]]), [[Miranda Bailey]] ([[Chandra Wilson]]), [[Richard Webber]] ([[James Pickens Jr.]]), Jo Karev ([[Camilla Luddington]]) and Atticus \"Link\" Lincoln ([[Chris Carmack]]).\n\nThe episode re-visits [[Katherine Heigl]]'s character, [[Izzie Stevens]], for the first time in over ten years. Alex and Izzie's storyline was left unresolved in the [[Grey's Anatomy (season 6)|sixth season]], after Heigl departed the series abruptly during her maternity leave. In a [[I Like You So Much Better When You're Naked (Grey's Anatomy)|January 2010 episode]], Stevens leaves after she is unable to repair things with Alex. [[Joan Rater]], the episode's writer, explained that Stevens getting better propelled Karev to let her go.<ref name=Matter>{{cite web|url=http://www.greyswriters.com/2010/01/joan-rater-on-i-like-you-so-much-better-when-youre-naked.html |title=Joan Rater on \"I Like You So Much Better When You're Naked\"... |publisher=ABC |work=Grey Matter |date=January 21, 2010 |access-date=June 26, 2012 |author=Rater, Joan |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130513155822/http://www.greyswriters.com/2010/01/joan-rater-on-i-like-you-so-much-better-when-youre-naked.html |archive-date=May 13, 2013 |df= }}</ref> Izzie's absence after this was intended to be temporary, with the character returning in the season's final five episodes. However, Heigl did not show up for filming on March 1, 2010 for the season's twentieth episode. Heigl's three month family leave in Utah propelled her to quit the show entirely, feeling she needed more time to bond with her adoptive daughter. She explained, \"So before I was due back, I spoke again to [[Shonda Rhimes|Shonda]] about wanting to leave. Then I waited at home until I was given the formal okay that I was off the show. The rumors that I refused to return were totally untrue.\" While Heigl felt the departure was \u201camicable\u201d, despite the shock and feeling that something could have worked out, Heigl felt Izzie returning only to leave again after already having done so twice would \"feel a little manipulative\" and she felt that she had not created a bond with her adoptive daughter yet that made her feel like she needed her.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/03/24/katherine-heigl-greys-anatomy-official-ew/|title=This week's cover (exclusive!): Katherine Heigl confirms 'Grey's Anatomy' departure|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=March 24, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc]]|accessdate=April 5, 2010}}</ref> \n\nIn August 2010, Rhimes stated that she did not feel Alex and Izzie's arc had fully concluded, and hoped to give proper closure to their relationship in the [[Grey's Anatomy (season 7)|seventh season]].<ref name=\"Closure\">{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/08/22/greys-anatomy-closure-for-alex-izzie/|title='Grey's Anatomy' Exclusive: Closure is coming for Alex/Izzie fans |first=Michael|last=Ausiello|authorlink=Michael Ausiello |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc]]|date=August 22, 2010|accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref> She later confirmed that she had intended to kill off Izzie off-screen, but opted against this a day later as she felt that it would destroy Alex, rather than give him closure. Instead, she concluded: \"I'm open to seeing Izzie again. So if she [Katherine] were to come back, we would be thrilled to [wrap up her story]. But if she doesn't, we'll just move on.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2010/10/29/greys-anatomy-spoiler-alex-izzie/|title=Exclusive: 'Grey's Anatomy' boss vetoes controversial Alex/Izzie plot|first=Michael|last=Ausiello|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=October 29, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time Inc]]|accessdate=September 5, 2011}}</ref> While Heigl originally considered the idea of her returning bleak and considered the chapter closed,<ref>[http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1649167/katherine-heigl-on-greys-anatomy-that-chapter-closed.jhtml Katherine Heigl On 'Grey's Anatomy': 'That Chapter Is Closed']</ref> she later regretted it and expressed enthusiasm on returning in January 2012<ref name=kheiglreturn>{{cite web|title='Grey's Anatomy': Katherine Heigl wants to return|url=http://insidetv.ew.com/2012/01/19/greys-anatomy-katherine-heigl-wants-to-return/|work=Inside TV|publisher=Entertainment Weekly|accessdate=January 22, 2012}}</ref> but Rhimes, two months after, said that she was on a different track that they were not interested in changing.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/03/greys-anatomy-katherine-heigl-not-returning-plus-finale-scoop-from-shonda-rhimes.html |title='Grey's Anatomy': Katherine Heigl not returning, plus finale scoop from Shonda Rhimes |access-date=2012-03-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010041120/http://blog.zap2it.com/frominsidethebox/2012/03/greys-anatomy-katherine-heigl-not-returning-plus-finale-scoop-from-shonda-rhimes.html |archive-date=2013-10-10 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Four months after, Rhimes cast [[Camilla Luddington]] as Jo Wilson,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvline.com/2012/07/19/greys-anatomy-season-9-camilla-luddington/|title='Kate Middleton' Joins Grey's Anatomy Season 9|last=Mitovich|first=Matt Webb|work=Wetpaint|date=July 19, 2012|accessdate=December 4, 2012}}</ref> who became the new love interest for Chambers' character. Three years later, Rhimes said she has completely moved on from the idea of Izzie coming back, \"I\u2019m done with that story. I\u2019ve turned that idea over in my mind a thousand times and thought about how it would go. And I don\u2019t think so.\"<ref>[http://tvline.com/2015/08/05/greys-anatomy-izzie-season-12-katherine-heigl-returning/ Grey's Anatomy Boss Shonda Rhimes Crushes My Katherine Heigl Comeback Dream: 'I'm Done With That Story'] TV Line, Retrieved August 6, 2015</ref> \n\n{{quote box|align=left|width=30em|quote=Some fans were upset, particularly the Jolex shippers, that [Alex left Jo to be with Izzie] \u2014 and I understand why. But I would fight real hard anyone who tried to tell me that fans would not have been equally or more upset if I had killed Alex Karev off camera.\u201d|source= \u2014Vernoff on the decision to reunite Alex with Izzie after Chambers' abrupt exit.<ref name=KriVern>{{cite web|url=https://tvline.com/2020/04/09/greys-anatomy-alex-death-storyline-justin-chambers/|last=Ausiello |first=Michael |title=Grey's Anatomy Boss Never Considered Killing Off Alex Karev \u2014 Here's Why|work=TVLine|date=April 9, 2020 |accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref>}}\n\nAfter the season sixteen finale, showrunner [[Krista Vernoff]] elaborated on the decision to choose Alex's send-off. \u201cAt the end of the day, there were three choices,\u201d she explained to [[TVLine]]. \u201cKill Alex off camera; have Alex be alive and in Seattle \u2014 and still married to Jo \u2014 and we just never see him; or [reunite him] with Izzie.\u201d She felt that killing Alex would have been \u201ccruel to everyone \u2014 particularly Meredith and Jo,\u201d Alex's best friend and wife, respectively. \u201cThere was no way to not put those characters through gut-wrenching, ongoing grief if we had killed Alex off camera.\u201d She also felt the second option would have done a disservice to [[Camilla Luddington]] who plays Chambers' TV wife. \u201cIt wasn\u2019t fair to her to keep her married to a character who was off screen,\u201d Vernoff says. \u201cIt would absolutely eliminate [the chance for her to play] so many colors that she is so good at playing\u201d and finally evaluated as a result that it \u201c...wasn\u2019t even a debate in the writers room,\u201d adding that giving Alex a happy ending with Izzie \u201cwas so clearly the right course.\u201d<ref name=KriVern/>\n\n==Reception==\n===Ratings===\n\"Leave a Light On\" was originally broadcast on March 5, 2020 in the United States on the [[American Broadcasting Company]] (ABC). The episode was watched by a total of 6.30 million viewers, rising up from the previous episode's 6 million. In the key 18-49 demographic, the episode scored a 1.3/7 [[Nielsen ratings|rating]]/share, up two tenths from the previous episode and the best since the mid-season premiere \"[[Grey's Anatomy (season 16)#ep352|Help Me Through the Night]]\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pucci |first1=Douglas |title=Thursday Final Ratings: NBA on TNT Tops the 10 p.m. Hour in Adults 18-49, 18-34 and Key Male Demos |url=https://programminginsider.com/thursday-final-ratings-nba-on-tnt-tops-the-10-p-m-hour-in-adults-18-49-18-34-and-key-male-demos/ |website=Programming Insider |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Reviews===\n[[File:Justin Cambers 2014 (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|150px|[[Justin Chambers]] made his final appearance as a series regular after fifteen years on the show.]]\n\"Leave the Light On\" received a polarizing response from television critics and fans alike.\n\n''[[USA Today]]'' noted the \"polarizing\" response for fans, and on discussing Alex's whole journey said, \"He was there for us as we watched a succession of doctors depart the series. Karev was a constant; Where else would he go? After a rough upbringing, he craved stability \u2013 making the timing of his exit all the more perplexing. Then again: Maybe Izzie was that stability all along.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/tv/2020/03/05/greys-anatomy-how-alex-karev-justin-chambers-said-goodbye/4955659002/|title=Ellen Pompeo calls Alex Karev's 'Grey's Anatomy' goodbye 'the best possible storyline'|work=USA Today|last=Oliver|first=David|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n''[[Deadline]]'' noted \"fan favorite\" Alex's ending's similarities to that of [[ER (TV series)|ER]]'s [[Doug Ross|Doug]] and [[Carol Hathaway|Carol]], played by [[George Clooney]] and [[Julianna Margulies]] respectively, \"who also left the show at different times\" and there \"Carol also had given birth to the couple\u2019s twins unbeknownst to Doug, with the couple eventually reuniting to live happily ever after with their kids\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/greys-anatomyl-alex-karev-farewell-surprise-twist-wrap-story-izzie-shocker-showrunner-krista-vernoff-lvideo-1202875717/|title=\u2018Grey\u2019s Anatomy\u2019 Wraps Alex Karev\u2019s Story With Surprise Twist; Krista Vernoff Says: \u201cWe Will Miss Him Terribly\u201d|work=Deadline|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn a three-out-of-five-star review, Maggie Fremont for ''[[Vulture (magazine)|Vulture]]'' expressed disappointment that the \"clip show\" exit showed no physical reunion between Izzie and Alex. Then Fremont elaborated, \"It just felt like Alex dying, although tragic, would\u2019ve been the only way to write the character off that made sense after everything he went through\" and that \"Alex Karev we\u2019ve watched for \u2014 holy hell, almost two decades if we\u2019re rounding up \u2014 wouldn\u2019t do that\" although admitted the exit \"almost works\", as Alex chooses to not miss a second with his children and to be a great dad, but that \"Alex not being mad for one single second about the fact that Izzie had secret kids five years ago and never told him\" made \"less sense\". Fremont also noted that Alex could have asked Jo to move to Kansas to help him be there for his children so that it was obviously \"ALSO about the women he loves\". She discussed the dramatic nature of Richard's speech saying, \"I\u2019m sorry, Richard\u2019s speech is lovely and all, but he\u2019s acting like he can\u2019t just go to Kansas and see the guy. Richard thrives on that drama, you guys. Fremont also commented on Jo's reaction saying, \"Poor Jo! And poor me for having to sympathize with a character I can\u2019t stand, you know? Jo\u2019s letter truly sucks\", with both commenting on the impersonal nature of the letter.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/greys-anatomy-recap-season-16-episode-16-leave-a-light-on.html|title=Grey\u2019s Anatomy Recap: A Dear Jo Letter|work=Vulture|last=Fremont|first=Maggie|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAshley Bissette Sumerel for ''Telltale-TV'' gave a moderately positive 3.5 out of 5 star review of the episode. She complimented how the writers worked with the circumstances of Chambers' abrupt departure feeling \"[his] sudden exit meant the writers needed to change course and figure out the best way to write out his character, and I believe they did that, with a few exceptions\" and said, I\u2019d actually told a few people that there was one ending for Alex that I felt like I\u2019d be able to accept, and low and behold, this is it. The timing is terrible considering his relationship with Jo, but again, I think in this case, we do have to consider the circumstances.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://telltaletv.com/2020/03/greys-anatomy-review-leave-a-light-on-season-16-episode-16/|title=Grey\u2019s Anatomy Review: Leave a Light On (Season 16 Episode 16)|work=Telltale TV|last=Bisette Sumerel|first=Ashley|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSonya Field for ''Hypable'' criticized the \"unrealistic\" storyline, feeling that it underscored Jo and Alex's story \"because he was so ready to leave her\". She opined that the Izzie/Alex flashbacks \"bothered\" her. She finished saying, \"It worries me that this might mean the whole issue will largely be swept under the rug after this episode. It\u2019s already upsetting to see how Alex was able to walk away from Jo so quickly, and I hope they at least handle things differently on Jo\u2019s end.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hypable.com/greys-anatomy-season-16-episode-16-alex-karev-written-off-the-show/|title=\u2018Grey\u2019s Anatomy\u2019 season 16, episode 16 review: Alex Karev says goodbye|work=Hypable|last=Field|first=Sonya|date=March 5, 2020|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nJasmine Blu for ''TV Fanatic'' gave a mostly negative response to the episode. They noted Meredith as being \"self-absorbed\" saying, \"Meredith has been so far removed from the missing Alex storyline, and before that, she hasn't so much as visited him at Pac-North. Alex's final season had a startling lack of Merlex, so the final goodbye was even bitterer\", while also acknowledging how no goodbye, short of death, would satisfy everyone. The reviewer criticized Alex's development in the episode saying, \"Alex, who has spent years resenting people for abandoning him turned around and left those he loves. It's a struggle to wrap one's head around it.\" Blu also criticized Alex for seemingly using his sick mother as an alibi, and noted it as being uncharacteristic of the \"straight-shooter\" and \"guy who tells it like it is whether you like it or not\" that fans know him by. The reviewer also noted that it was \"already a disservice that it took so long for anyone to pay attention to his absence\" and that \"Jo probably should've contacted his mother ages ago\". Blu also criticized the storyline for how it will service Jo as a tragedy later, calling \"Woe is Joe hours [...] irritating\" and that \"so much of Alex's storylines in the last few seasons have been playing second to Jo.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvfanatic.com/2020/03/when-good-characters-cant-break-away-from-being-love-interests-w/|title=Grey's Anatomy Season 16 Episode 16 Review: Leave a Light On|work=TVFanatic|last=Blu|first=Jasmine|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Grey's Anatomy episodes|16}}\n\n[[Category:Grey's Anatomy (season 16) episodes]]\n[[Category:2020 American television episodes]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toDeadline(link changed toDeadline Hollywood) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leave_a_Light_On_(Grey%27s_Anatomy)"}
{"title_page": "List of accolades received by Us (2019 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:List of accolades received by ''Us'' (2019 film)}}\n{{Infobox awards list\n| title        = List of accolades received by ''Us''\n| film         = y\n| image        = SXSW_2019_8_-_Lupita_Nyong'o_(46611809024).jpg\n| caption      = [[Lupita Nyong'o]] received widespread acclaim from critics and audiences with most acting nominations for her [[dual role]] in ''[[Us (2019 film)|Us]]''.\n| wins         = 42\n| nominations  = 68\n| awards       = \n{{Custom award|[[African-American Film Critics Association]]|3|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]]|1|2}}\n{{Custom award|[[Art Directors Guild]]|0|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[Austin Film Critics Association]]|1|2}}\n{{Custom award|[[:id:Festival Film Bandung|Bandung Film Festival]]|1|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[Black Reel Awards]]|4|7}}\n{{Custom award|[[BreakTudo Awards]]|0|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[Chicago Film Critics Association#Chicago Film Critics Awards|Chicago Film Critics Awards]]|0|2}}\n{{Custom award|[[Critics' Choice Movie Awards]]|0|4}}\n{{Custom award|[[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth Film Critics Association]]|0|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[Detroit Film Critics Society]]|0|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[Dorian Awards]]|0|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[Dublin Film Critics' Circle]]|1|2}}\n{{Custom award|[[Georgia Film Critics Association]]|1|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[Golden Trailer Awards]]|5|4}}\n{{Custom award|[[Hollywood Critics Association]]|3|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[Hollywood Music in Media Awards]]|1|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[Houston Film Critics Society]]|0|2}}\n{{Custom award|[[IndieWire Critics Poll]]|1|4}}\n{{Custom award|[[International Cinematographers Guild]]|0|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[International Cinephile Society]]|0|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[London Film Critics' Circle]]|0|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[Los Angeles Film Critics Association Awards]]|1|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild#Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild Awards|Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild Awards]]|0|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[MTV Movie & TV Awards]]|0|3}}\n{{Custom award|[[NAACP Image Awards]]|2|6}}\n{{Custom award|[[New York Film Critics Circle Awards]]|1|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[New York Film Critics Online]]|1|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[Online Film Critics Society]]|2|2}}\n{{Custom award|[[People's Choice Awards]]|0|4}}\n{{Custom award|[[The ReFrame Stamp]]|1|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[San Diego Film Critics Society#Awards|San Diego Film Critics Society]]|1|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[San Francisco Bay Area Film Critics Circle]]|1|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[Santa Barbara International Film Festival]]|1|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[Saturn Award]]s|1|7}}\n{{Custom award|[[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s|0|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[Seattle Film Critics Society]]|1|2}}\n{{Custom award|[[St. Louis Film Critics Association]]|1|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[Toronto Film Critics Association]]|1|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[Vancouver Film Critics Circle]]|1|0}}\n{{Custom award|[[Washington D.C. Area Film Critics Association]]|2|2}}\n{{Custom award|[[Women Film Critics Circle]]|1|1}}\n{{Custom award|[[World Soundtrack Academy|World Soundtrack Awards]]|1|0}}\n}}\n\n'''[[Us (2019 film)|Us]]''' is a 2019 American [[horror film]] written and directed by [[Jordan Peele]], starring [[Lupita Nyong'o]], [[Winston Duke]], [[Shahadi Wright Joseph]], Evan Alex, [[Elisabeth Moss]], and [[Tim Heidecker]]. The film follows Adelaide Wilson (Nyong\u2019o) and her family, who are attacked by a group of menacing [[doppelg\u00e4ngers]].\n\nThe film had its world premiere at [[South by Southwest]] on March 8, 2019 and was theatrically released in the United States on March 22, 2019 through [[Universal Pictures]]. It was later released on [[Ultra HD Blu-ray|4K UHD Blu-ray]], Blu-ray and [[DVD]] on June 18. ''Us'' was a commercial success, grossing $255.1 million worldwide against a budget of $20 million and received praise for Nyong'o's [[dual role]] performance and [[Michael Abels]]' [[Film score|musical score]].\n\n''Us'' was nominated for one [[Art Directors Guild]], eleven [[Black Reel Awards]] (winning four), four [[Critics' Choice Movie Awards]], nine [[Golden Trailer Awards]] (winning five), one [[Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild#Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild Awards|Make-Up Artists and Hair Stylists Guild]], three [[MTV Movie & TV Awards]], eight [[NAACP Image Awards]] (winning two), four [[People's Choice Awards]], seven [[Saturn Awards]] (winning one), one [[Screen Actors Guild Award]], and one [[World Soundtrack Academy|World Soundtrack Awards]] (won).\n\n== Accolades ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\" style=\"width: 100%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Award\n! scope=\"col\"| Date of ceremony\n! scope=\"col\"| Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Recipient(s)\n! scope=\"col\"| Result\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[African-American Film Critics Association]]<ref name=\"AAFCAA19\">{{cite web | url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/2019-aafca-african-american-film-critics-association-awards-full-winners-list-1261259| title=Jordan Peele's 'Us' Named Best Film by African-American Film Critics Association| publisher=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] | date= December 10, 2019| accessdate=December 10, 2019 | author= Rahman, Abid}}</ref>\n| scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| December 10, 2019\n| [[African-American Film Critics Association#Best Picture|Best Film]]\n| ''Us''\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Actress\n| [[Lupita Nyong'o]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| Best Director\n| [[Jordan Peele]]\n| {{won}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]]<ref name=\"eda19\">{{cite web | url=https://awfj.org/eda-awards-2/2019-eda-award-winners/ | title=2019 EDA Award Winners| publisher= [[Alliance of Women Film Journalists]] | accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n| scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\